WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.820
- ... were standing there. Everyone is waiting,
'cause at any moment an arrow could just

00:00:04.260 --> 00:00:07.520
fly through your neck, and there's
people holding shotguns. And the

00:00:07.540 --> 00:00:10.880
anthropologist, this little guy, is standing
there in the front, and he's going,

00:00:10.900 --> 00:00:14.370
"Enimole." He's going, "Brothers."
And then it happened. Then you

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:17.720
start hearing people screaming,

00:00:17.740 --> 00:00:21.460
"Mashco! Mashco!" And people
are screaming and women are

00:00:21.520 --> 00:00:25.430
lifting children and running into the
huts and the dogs and chickens are going

00:00:25.440 --> 00:00:25.780
nuts and—

00:00:25.820 --> 00:00:26.970
- So fear, fear.

00:00:26.980 --> 00:00:30.940
- Fear. He's going, "Look there. He has a
bow. He has a bow." And we're looking

00:00:30.980 --> 00:00:34.949
up the beach and there's just this
clan walking down the beach with

00:00:34.980 --> 00:00:38.940
these seven-foot bows and they're hunched over
and they're pointing at us. They're going,

00:00:38.960 --> 00:00:42.890
"Look at that one. Look, there's a gun
there." And you can see them communicating

00:00:42.900 --> 00:00:46.840
to each other and the butterflies are swirling
off the beach and they can hit a spider

00:00:46.900 --> 00:00:50.720
monkey out of the treetops
at 40 meters. They can sneak

00:00:50.820 --> 00:00:54.410
up and you will never know they're there.
And so when that arrow passes through your

00:00:54.500 --> 00:00:58.340
body, you'll only have a moment to
realize it before you fall over.

00:00:58.360 --> 00:01:01.760
In order for any of this to make sense,
I have to show you this footage.

00:01:01.800 --> 00:01:05.120
- And this has not been shown ever before.

00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:06.980
- This is a world first.

00:01:08.560 --> 00:01:12.450
- The following is a conversation with Paul
Rosolie, his third time on the podcast.

00:01:12.460 --> 00:01:16.000
Paul is a naturalist, explorer,
writer and is someone who has

00:01:16.080 --> 00:01:19.960
dedicated his life to protecting the
Amazon rainforest and celebrating

00:01:20.020 --> 00:01:23.480
the beauty of the natural world.

00:01:23.580 --> 00:01:27.000
He has a new book coming out in
a few days titled Jungle Keeper

00:01:27.520 --> 00:01:30.800
that you should definitely
go pre-order now.

00:01:30.860 --> 00:01:34.610
It tells some intense stories about
his time in the jungle over the

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:42.120
past several years, building up to a
few epic recent events, including a new

00:01:42.160 --> 00:01:45.860
extended encounter with a non-contacted
tribe that we discuss in this podcast.

00:01:45.870 --> 00:01:49.440
Both the book and audiobook are great.

00:01:49.450 --> 00:01:53.080
I highly recommend it. If you would
like to support Paul and his team

00:01:53.300 --> 00:01:58.640
in their mission to protect the
jungle, go to junglekeepers.org.

00:01:58.700 --> 00:02:02.190
You can help with donations or

00:02:02.220 --> 00:02:06.020
by spreading the word or checking out the
gala that Paul is hosting in New York

00:02:06.040 --> 00:02:10.038
on January 22nd in a few days.

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:13.900
They are doing all they can to help
raise funds for the mission of

00:02:13.940 --> 00:02:16.930
safeguarding as much of the
rainforest as possible,

00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:20.049
and I think it's a mission
worth fighting for.

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:23.190
The Amazon jungle is one of the most
special and beautiful places on Earth.

00:02:23.320 --> 00:02:27.140
As an aside, allow me to look back

00:02:27.160 --> 00:02:31.140
briefly and mention something that
I've been struggling with a bit.

00:02:31.180 --> 00:02:35.140
For context, I traveled to the Amazon
rainforest with Paul a while back.

00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:39.100
It was an adventure of a lifetime,
with lots of crazy twists and turns.

00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:42.980
We did record a podcast out
there, literally in the jungle.

00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:49.810
Episode 429, if you want to go
check it out. It was awesome.

00:02:49.880 --> 00:02:53.620
And we also recorded a bunch of disparate
footage of the journey just for fun.

00:02:53.660 --> 00:02:57.580
And I would still love to somehow

00:02:57.660 --> 00:03:01.460
put all that together into a cohesive
video in case it's interesting to someone.

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:05.480
But I've learned just how difficult it is

00:03:05.560 --> 00:03:09.300
to organize and edit a pile of
chaotically recorded footage like that.

00:03:09.340 --> 00:03:16.960
So, let's see if I can pull it off.
But in any case, this kind of raw

00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:21.260
vlog-style video is something that I
would love to be able to do more of

00:03:21.860 --> 00:03:25.260
as a way to celebrate amazing
human beings like Paul and others,

00:03:25.360 --> 00:03:32.420
including everyday people who I meet
on my travels. So, I'll keep trying,

00:03:32.480 --> 00:03:36.360
tinkering, learning, and I ask for your
patience and support along the way.

00:03:36.600 --> 00:03:44.260
Now, back to our regularly scheduled
programming. This is the Lex Fridman Podcast.

00:03:44.340 --> 00:03:48.240
To support it, please check out our
sponsors in the description where you

00:03:48.280 --> 00:03:52.260
can also find links to contact
me, ask questions, give

00:03:52.300 --> 00:03:58.200
feedback, and so on. And now, dear
friends, here's Paul Rosolie.

00:03:59.300 --> 00:04:03.260
We've survived a challenging time
out in the jungle about a year and a

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:06.660
half ago, and since then, your life has

00:04:06.700 --> 00:04:10.660
increasingly gotten more
intense. So, you've achieved

00:04:10.700 --> 00:04:16.969
the incredible feat of saving now more
than 130,000 acres of rainforest.

00:04:17.040 --> 00:04:23.040
And the goal that you're working towards
is protecting 200,000 acres more.

00:04:23.080 --> 00:04:26.320
And doing so while facing
extreme danger from narcos,

00:04:26.360 --> 00:04:30.180
narco-traffickers, so-called
Cocaine Mafia in an escalating

00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:34.160
drug war. This is insane.
These are new developments.

00:04:34.200 --> 00:04:38.120
Illegal loggers, as we've talked
about before. Gold miners, and the

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:41.400
incredible recent encounter
with an uncontacted

00:04:41.460 --> 00:04:45.220
tribe. And we'll talk about
all of this. So your new

00:04:45.300 --> 00:04:49.240
book, Jungle Keeper, opens with
the killing of two loggers

00:04:49.250 --> 00:04:57.420
by the warriors of an uncontacted
tribe, the Mashco Piro, in August 2024.

00:04:57.540 --> 00:05:01.340
And then you reveal that you had your own
dramatic encounter with the tribe two

00:05:01.380 --> 00:05:08.340
months later in October 2024. So if I
may, let me read the opening of the book.

00:05:09.200 --> 00:05:13.120
"Far out on the western edge
of the Amazon rainforest, deep

00:05:13.140 --> 00:05:16.580
in the Peruvian jungle, a
pair of loggers plunged their

00:05:16.620 --> 00:05:23.120
chainsaws into the buttressed roots of
an ancient ironwood. An ironwood, or

00:05:23.460 --> 00:05:27.220
shihuahuaco, of this size
is a giant among giants, an

00:05:27.280 --> 00:05:31.160
emergent sentinel that
reaches heights of 160 feet,

00:05:31.170 --> 00:05:34.830
towering over the rest of the
canopy." I've read that many are

00:05:34.960 --> 00:05:38.860
over 1,000 years old, by the way,
as an aside. And you've found

00:05:39.140 --> 00:05:41.800
ones that are 1,200 years old.

00:05:41.820 --> 00:05:43.100
- Incredibly old.

00:05:43.140 --> 00:05:47.040
- Anyway, you continue. "This particular
tree had started its life as a

00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:50.840
tiny sapling in the great jungle,
a story that began before the

00:05:50.860 --> 00:05:54.100
Spanish reached Peru, long before
the United States was even a

00:05:54.200 --> 00:05:58.160
dream. At a time when
Leonardo da Vinci was still

00:05:58.220 --> 00:06:01.780
honing his talents in a far away
part of the world, through the

00:06:01.820 --> 00:06:05.570
Renaissance, the First and Second
World Wars, and the birth of our

00:06:05.640 --> 00:06:09.256
grandparents." This tree
was out there slowly

00:06:09.316 --> 00:06:13.256
charging upward, anonymous, just
one pillar among the billions

00:06:13.296 --> 00:06:19.966
of others. But on this day, in August
2024, when the two loggers worked, this

00:06:20.016 --> 00:06:23.856
witness of the centuries came
crashing down to the canopy

00:06:23.916 --> 00:06:27.096
with such cataclysmic power
that it shook the earth.

00:06:28.056 --> 00:06:31.766
And then you go on to talk about
how the shaking of the earth was

00:06:31.796 --> 00:06:34.846
felt and heard by the uncontacted tribe.

00:06:34.956 --> 00:06:39.685
You go on to describe how these
particular loggers were killed

00:06:39.715 --> 00:06:42.416
by the uncontacted tribe of

00:06:42.456 --> 00:06:47.456
Mashco Piro. What do we know about these
warriors of the uncontacted tribe?

00:06:48.976 --> 00:06:55.156
- We know that across the Amazon basin
there's still perhaps thousands of clans of

00:06:55.696 --> 00:06:59.216
uncontacted peoples,
people that are living in

00:06:59.236 --> 00:07:06.516
nomadic isolation in what remains of the intact
Amazon basin and want to remain that way.

00:07:06.576 --> 00:07:10.336
And so, what happened with
these loggers was that

00:07:10.416 --> 00:07:14.336
local people told them,
"Don't go out there. Don't go

00:07:14.396 --> 00:07:18.286
into these territories." And what happens is that
people that aren't from... There's this thing with

00:07:18.316 --> 00:07:21.216
the jungle, people don't believe that

00:07:22.056 --> 00:07:25.816
it's as wild as the legends say.
And so when they say there's

00:07:25.836 --> 00:07:29.786
calatos out there, there's
wild people out there,

00:07:29.786 --> 00:07:33.486
these loggers from another region
go, "Yeah, that's just some story.

00:07:33.516 --> 00:07:37.336
We're fine. We'll go. We have
shotguns." They don't realize

00:07:37.396 --> 00:07:40.826
you're dealing with a
civilization of people that is

00:07:40.916 --> 00:07:44.806
still nomadic, still uses
bamboo-tipped arrows, still

00:07:44.836 --> 00:07:48.636
lives naked in the Amazon rainforest,
has knowledge of medicines that we've

00:07:48.776 --> 00:07:52.636
yet to encounter or may never
discover, and that they can

00:07:52.696 --> 00:07:56.676
hit a spider monkey out of the
treetops at 40 meters. And so

00:07:56.696 --> 00:08:00.656
while you're using a chainsaw, they
can sneak up and you will never know

00:08:00.676 --> 00:08:04.556
they're there. And so when that
arrow passes through your body,

00:08:04.616 --> 00:08:07.536
you'll only have a moment to
realize it before you fall over.

00:08:07.556 --> 00:08:10.736
- And we're looking at something
you posted on your Instagram-

00:08:11.036 --> 00:08:15.345
... which are the arrows that they
use, which are bigger than you.

00:08:15.376 --> 00:08:16.646
So they're like six or seven feet.

00:08:16.655 --> 00:08:19.396
- Six, seven feet. More like
seven feet. And that's-

00:08:19.536 --> 00:08:19.806
- Look how sharp that is.

00:08:19.806 --> 00:08:23.326
- ... incredibly sharp. They cure it over the
fire and they have a way of sharpening it.

00:08:23.376 --> 00:08:27.356
That edge of bamboo becomes incredibly
knife-sharp. You can cut meat with it

00:08:27.416 --> 00:08:30.716
easily; I've done it. These
arrows... Look at that. I mean, I'm

00:08:30.996 --> 00:08:34.655
5'9". That's easily a seven-foot arrow.

00:08:34.696 --> 00:08:38.445
- Yeah, so for people who are just
listening, this "arrow" is really a spear.

00:08:38.445 --> 00:08:42.436
Some people would think it was a spear, but
they're shooting this thing with a gigantic bow.

00:08:43.395 --> 00:08:45.436
That's crazy.

00:08:45.476 --> 00:08:49.216
- Yeah, and so to be holding that...
Look at that, they even twist the

00:08:49.256 --> 00:08:52.576
fletching so the arrow spins in
the air. They have incredible

00:08:52.636 --> 00:08:56.556
craftsmanship, and then you see all the little
string on there is plant fibers they've

00:08:56.576 --> 00:08:58.756
woven, and then this is them.

00:09:01.276 --> 00:09:03.236
- Yeah, the warriors of the tribe.

00:09:03.256 --> 00:09:07.156
- The warriors of the tribe. And so the
fact that we're sitting here talking

00:09:07.216 --> 00:09:11.206
on microphones, and that we have airplanes
and cell phones and all the things we have in

00:09:11.236 --> 00:09:15.206
the modern world, and there's still...
We still live in this age where there's,

00:09:15.236 --> 00:09:19.216
right now at this moment, people
living out in the jungle who have been

00:09:19.276 --> 00:09:23.005
there since before history,
is an incredible thing.

00:09:24.316 --> 00:09:27.876
- Let me look this up on Perplexity:
what are the technologies

00:09:29.596 --> 00:09:32.976
we modern humans have
that the Mashco Piro do

00:09:33.016 --> 00:09:36.336
not? It's just interesting
to think about the kind of

00:09:36.436 --> 00:09:40.096
technologies we take for
granted. Energy and power,

00:09:40.156 --> 00:09:43.946
obviously all the electricity generation,
grids, batteries, solar panels, and

00:09:43.996 --> 00:09:47.536
electric motors, metals and
materials, mass-produced steel,

00:09:47.576 --> 00:09:51.296
aluminum, advanced alloys,
plastics, composites, glass,

00:09:51.336 --> 00:09:52.476
concrete, all of those things.

00:09:52.496 --> 00:09:52.576
- All of those things.

00:09:52.616 --> 00:09:56.536
- Tools, of course, and machinery.
The infrastructure of

00:09:56.576 --> 00:10:00.256
roads and bridges and buildings, and the

00:10:00.296 --> 00:10:04.116
weapons of war—everything but the spears
and arrows that they have—and the

00:10:04.316 --> 00:10:09.116
medicine and biology. Of course they
probably have complicated medicines

00:10:10.176 --> 00:10:14.356
that they've developed for their own—
...that are available within the jungle.

00:10:14.396 --> 00:10:16.536
- I mean, that entire list is no.

00:10:16.556 --> 00:10:17.436
- No.

00:10:17.476 --> 00:10:20.996
- I mean, metal, I think you have to
be able to excavate into the earth

00:10:21.196 --> 00:10:23.136
and forge metal.

00:10:23.936 --> 00:10:27.896
These people don't even... As one of
the local anthropologists said to me, a

00:10:27.975 --> 00:10:31.915
Peruvian anthropologist, he said,
"You know, people think of them as

00:10:32.036 --> 00:10:36.016
Stone Age tribes." And he was like, "They
don't have stones." He's like, "They don't..."

00:10:36.026 --> 00:10:39.886
So they don't know that water... They
see water that they drink. They don't

00:10:39.915 --> 00:10:43.856
know that water freezes, because they've never
seen it. They don't know that water boils,

00:10:43.896 --> 00:10:47.476
because they don't even make clay pots. They
just have their bamboo and their string.

00:10:48.136 --> 00:10:51.966
And so they're living an
incredibly simple life. So all of

00:10:52.036 --> 00:10:54.106
that, I mean, even a camera is a miracle

00:10:55.036 --> 00:10:58.776
to them. You have to bend your mind to
even understand how far back they are.

00:10:58.816 --> 00:11:03.836
It's like looking into thousands
of years ago, like the Stone Age.

00:11:03.915 --> 00:11:09.076
- When they hear the sounds of the chainsaws,
the sounds of machinery in the distance-

00:11:09.096 --> 00:11:12.576
...I wonder how they can possibly
comprehend what that is.

00:11:12.676 --> 00:11:19.616
- I think they view it as a demonic
destructive force. And when I show you the

00:11:19.656 --> 00:11:23.396
encounter that we had,
we got a few takeaways.

00:11:23.415 --> 00:11:27.176
We left with more questions than
answers, but one of the things they were

00:11:27.256 --> 00:11:31.076
able to communicate across the
language barrier was, "Why are you

00:11:31.116 --> 00:11:33.776
cutting down the trees?"
They don't like it.

00:11:34.415 --> 00:11:38.096
- Yeah. That represents to them the

00:11:38.136 --> 00:11:42.165
danger and destruction that
the outside world brings.

00:11:42.196 --> 00:11:45.756
- They see us as the destroyers of worlds.

00:11:45.836 --> 00:11:51.976
- So tell me about this
encounter in October of 2024.

00:11:52.016 --> 00:11:55.596
- So, in order to tell you about
that encounter I think we need to

00:11:55.676 --> 00:11:59.636
orient people into where we're talking
about. We're talking about this river that

00:11:59.696 --> 00:12:03.556
runs through the western edge of
the Amazon rainforest that you know

00:12:03.596 --> 00:12:07.176
well now, after spending time
there with me. It's a high

00:12:07.236 --> 00:12:11.106
tributary of the Amazon where you
have the main river channel and

00:12:11.136 --> 00:12:15.124
then smaller and smaller and smaller
tributaries. And the smaller

00:12:15.184 --> 00:12:18.804
you get, the less trafficked
they are. And so this river has

00:12:18.884 --> 00:12:22.223
remained wild through the centuries. And

00:12:22.843 --> 00:12:26.723
even during the '90s when there was a
mahogany boom where people went out for it,

00:12:26.784 --> 00:12:31.324
trees, there were very few
people going up this river.

00:12:32.464 --> 00:12:36.324
20 years ago when I first got to the region and
people told me there were uncontacted tribes

00:12:36.364 --> 00:12:39.764
out there, it was always in
the realm of something...

00:12:39.864 --> 00:12:43.744
You know, it's like people say,
"There's Bigfoot," or, "Don't go there,

00:12:43.804 --> 00:12:47.723
it's haunted." It was
like a tall tale almost.

00:12:47.764 --> 00:12:51.274
And even the Peruvian government at the
time I first went to Peru, which was

00:12:51.424 --> 00:12:55.044
2006, their official position
was that the tribes are a

00:12:55.103 --> 00:12:58.744
myth. There's no such thing as
the tribes. That was the official

00:12:58.784 --> 00:13:02.364
position. And you just... You would
hear these stories of people that got

00:13:02.404 --> 00:13:06.244
shot. You'd meet someone high up a
river, four days upriver, deep in the

00:13:06.304 --> 00:13:10.193
Amazon, that had an arrow. And you'd
look at this thing and it had this,

00:13:10.264 --> 00:13:17.103
you know, mega gravity. And so as we've created
Jungle Keepers and now we're protecting

00:13:17.204 --> 00:13:21.004
130,000 acres of this river, we're protecting
the plants and the animals and the

00:13:21.064 --> 00:13:25.004
ancient trees, and trying to preserve the ecosystem,
and counting the butterflies and conducting

00:13:25.044 --> 00:13:29.493
ecological surveys, and what we've
inadvertently found ourselves

00:13:30.384 --> 00:13:34.264
the caretakers of, is the fact that
these people, in order to continue

00:13:34.343 --> 00:13:37.884
living, have to remain
isolated, want to remain

00:13:37.964 --> 00:13:41.924
isolated. That's their one mandate
as a civilization: the tribes

00:13:41.983 --> 00:13:51.404
of the Mashco Piro. And so, in
October, as Jungle Keepers now, we're

00:13:51.444 --> 00:13:55.364
working with the indigenous people. What we do
is we take loggers and gold miners and make

00:13:55.404 --> 00:13:58.743
them into rangers and give them better
jobs, and we try to protect the forest.

00:13:58.754 --> 00:14:02.654
And those people who live
up in the remote indigenous

00:14:02.704 --> 00:14:07.044
community, they called us on a satellite
phone and they said, "Directors,

00:14:08.064 --> 00:14:11.983
you've been working with us and telling us
you wanna help us. The tribes are coming out.

00:14:12.024 --> 00:14:13.584
What do we do?"

00:14:13.624 --> 00:14:18.194
- So, even they don't really know, when
the tribes emerge from the deep jungle-

00:14:18.194 --> 00:14:19.404
... what to do?

00:14:19.444 --> 00:14:20.444
- They were terrified.

00:14:20.504 --> 00:14:23.223
- What was your thinking when
you got the phone call?

00:14:23.264 --> 00:14:27.204
- When we got the phone call, it was a mix
of... because we're over here trying

00:14:27.223 --> 00:14:30.973
to get land concessions and doing all this
important work, and part of me was like,

00:14:30.983 --> 00:14:34.164
"That can't be real, so we're
gonna keep our heads down."

00:14:34.204 --> 00:14:35.964
- Bigfoot is emerging- ... from the forest.

00:14:35.983 --> 00:14:39.884
- Like, yeah, sure. And then we
hung up and we said, "Okay, maybe

00:14:39.924 --> 00:14:43.884
tomorrow if they're still there or
something." And then it was crazy because

00:14:43.924 --> 00:14:47.664
it was probably about noon and we had an important
day of meetings. We had a meeting with the

00:14:47.704 --> 00:14:51.124
police, we had a meeting with the landowner, we were
trying to do all this stuff for the conservation work.

00:14:52.104 --> 00:14:55.954
And then I got together with the core team
of directors, JJ, Mohsin, Stéphane, and

00:14:55.983 --> 00:14:59.804
we said, "Wait, if this
is real, we have to get

00:14:59.864 --> 00:15:03.524
there now. Like now, now." And
so we dropped what we were

00:15:03.564 --> 00:15:07.544
doing, canceled the meetings,
and put other people on them. We

00:15:08.324 --> 00:15:12.784
got a boat and we called Ignacio,
our most hardcore ranger.

00:15:12.804 --> 00:15:14.424
- Who has been shot.

00:15:14.483 --> 00:15:18.473
- Who in 2019 was shot in
the head by an arrow

00:15:18.504 --> 00:15:22.483
and still bears the scar, and
he barely survived. And we

00:15:22.524 --> 00:15:26.104
said, "Look, this is going down." He said, "I
already know because the whole river knows."

00:15:26.164 --> 00:15:30.044
We said, "Can you get us there by
tomorrow morning?" And he said, "Look,

00:15:30.084 --> 00:15:34.044
it's a two-day journey by boat. So,
no." And we said, "Is there any way you

00:15:34.064 --> 00:15:37.824
can you get us there?" And he went,
"I'll get you there." And so we got a

00:15:37.864 --> 00:15:41.204
couple of sacks of rice, a couple
of cans of tuna, our dry bags, our

00:15:41.243 --> 00:15:46.564
tents. We got on a boat by 6:00 PM
and we started riding up the river

00:15:46.604 --> 00:15:47.384
- Through the night?

00:15:47.394 --> 00:15:51.214
- ...through the night. And so a two-day boat
journey that we're trying to flex into one

00:15:51.284 --> 00:15:54.614
night. And so I was at the
front with the headlamp—

00:15:54.624 --> 00:15:58.324
...with the torch. And so the first
few hours it was clear, and that

00:15:58.404 --> 00:15:59.554
comet... Remember that comet—

00:15:59.584 --> 00:16:03.514
...that was going? There was that comet in the
sky. I remember looking at it and going, "This is

00:16:03.584 --> 00:16:07.504
it." I knew this was it. And the
first few hours were clear and the

00:16:07.584 --> 00:16:11.304
stars were out and it was beautiful, and
then it clouded over and the lightning

00:16:11.364 --> 00:16:15.184
started, and then it just apocalypse
downpoured. And from midnight

00:16:15.424 --> 00:16:18.824
until 8:00 AM it was just the front of
the boat with the light, and it was just

00:16:19.304 --> 00:16:23.124
a Star Wars vision of raindrops and

00:16:23.223 --> 00:16:27.164
galaxies and moths flying
in my eye. People don't

00:16:27.184 --> 00:16:31.064
realize you can get hypothermia in the tropics,
but as you're going at night, even if it's

00:16:31.184 --> 00:16:35.084
80 degrees outside, in the rain, in
the wind at night, in a lightning

00:16:35.204 --> 00:16:41.404
storm, you're freezing. And so by 2:00
AM I'm convulsively shivering, and

00:16:41.784 --> 00:16:45.704
we're using the caiman eyes on the
side of the river because it was

00:16:45.763 --> 00:16:49.733
so dark we couldn't see where we were
going, so those shine back at you. So I'm

00:16:49.844 --> 00:16:53.763
finding the caiman eyes and then
motioning with the light to Ignacio

00:16:53.804 --> 00:16:56.374
where to go, and he knew how to find
the channel and we had to jump the

00:16:56.404 --> 00:17:02.384
waterfalls. We did the two-day
boat ride in one night.

00:17:02.404 --> 00:17:06.324
And we arrive at this community
where... And it's morning now

00:17:06.364 --> 00:17:10.164
and the howler monkeys are calling
over the jungle, and the little naked

00:17:10.204 --> 00:17:13.983
children are all by the side and
everyone's scared. And we get a

00:17:14.003 --> 00:17:17.964
hug from this guy, Bacho, who we know, and
they're like, "Come in, come in, come in."

00:17:18.003 --> 00:17:21.993
And they're like, "The tribe came out yesterday.
We saw a few of them on the beach and

00:17:22.023 --> 00:17:22.594
they're gone now."

00:17:24.644 --> 00:17:28.624
And so we collapsed, we fell asleep.
Rained the whole day. That night we went

00:17:28.684 --> 00:17:31.704
out and we looked for them and
there was this crazy moment where

00:17:32.864 --> 00:17:36.543
we're standing on this beach and
their footprints were there.

00:17:36.584 --> 00:17:44.224
And the local indigenous anthropologist
was standing there, looking out into the

00:17:44.293 --> 00:17:48.124
Amazon beyond, and there's just all this
wreckage. It looked like something very

00:17:48.184 --> 00:17:52.074
Cormac McCarthy: just dark
sky, iron clouds, and

00:17:52.104 --> 00:17:55.654
we're standing there. Everyone is waiting,
'cause at any moment an arrow could

00:17:55.684 --> 00:17:59.563
just fly through your neck. And there's
people holding shotguns, and the

00:17:59.584 --> 00:18:03.063
anthropologist, this little guy, is standing
there in the front and he's going, "No

00:18:03.104 --> 00:18:06.964
mole." He's going, "Brothers." There's
only a few words that intersect

00:18:07.004 --> 00:18:10.944
between the languages and he's going,
"Brothers, we're here. We don't want to hurt

00:18:11.004 --> 00:18:14.964
you." He's speaking in the Yine language.
And he's saying, "Come out." And you can

00:18:15.104 --> 00:18:18.254
tell by their footprints—the trackers
explained this—that you could see...

00:18:18.284 --> 00:18:22.144
it was just the balls of their feet. So right
as we pulled up to the beach, they ran.

00:18:22.184 --> 00:18:26.128
So they were there listening to
us, and he's going, "Nomole, come

00:18:26.168 --> 00:18:30.148
out. It's okay. Lay down your arms.
We'll lay down ours. Nomole."

00:18:30.187 --> 00:18:34.068
He just kept saying, "Nomole." And nothing
happened. And we went back to the village and went

00:18:34.128 --> 00:18:38.638
to sleep. We wake up the next
morning, and it's 5:00 AM. And

00:18:40.628 --> 00:18:44.308
again, we're trying to save the jungle. We're
in a race against time to get these land

00:18:44.328 --> 00:18:48.298
concessions. And so my team, like
Mohsin and JJ—Stefan couldn't

00:18:48.328 --> 00:18:51.648
come because he was in town signing
paperwork and interviewing loggers

00:18:51.668 --> 00:18:55.508
and landowners. And also, he didn't
think there was any chance this

00:18:55.528 --> 00:18:59.348
was gonna be real because in his entire
50-something years in the Amazon, he's

00:18:59.388 --> 00:19:01.707
never seen them. And so

00:19:02.568 --> 00:19:06.508
we're getting ready to leave in the morning. We
had tents on the boat, and Ignacio comes up to

00:19:06.548 --> 00:19:09.888
me and he goes, "You're my director,
right? You're my boss?" And I went,

00:19:09.908 --> 00:19:13.878
"Yeah." He goes, "I need to talk
to you like a friend." I was like,

00:19:13.878 --> 00:19:17.668
"Yeah, shoot. Go." And he goes, "You'd
be an idiot to leave right now."

00:19:17.687 --> 00:19:21.528
He goes, "They're coming." And so
he convinced us to stay. We pull

00:19:21.568 --> 00:19:25.528
our tents off the boat. Stefan and Mohsin go
off with their cameras. They start shooting,

00:19:25.548 --> 00:19:28.947
you know, people. These are
monkey eaters and fishermen—the

00:19:29.208 --> 00:19:32.687
community that we're in. And
everything's quiet. And I opened my

00:19:32.708 --> 00:19:38.648
laptop, and I was working, just
writing my book. And then it

00:19:38.708 --> 00:19:41.988
happened. Then you start
hearing people screaming,

00:19:42.008 --> 00:19:45.728
"Mashco, Mashco!" And people
are screaming and women are

00:19:45.788 --> 00:19:49.648
lifting children and running into the
huts, and the dogs and chickens are going

00:19:49.708 --> 00:19:50.217
nuts. And I mean—

00:19:50.228 --> 00:19:51.228
- So fear. Fear.

00:19:51.248 --> 00:19:52.058
- Fear.

00:19:52.128 --> 00:19:56.098
- Because we should say, the
obvious thing is, as far as

00:19:56.148 --> 00:20:00.578
anyone remembers, any minimal,
small encounters with these tribes—

00:20:00.648 --> 00:20:01.808
... have been violent.

00:20:01.828 --> 00:20:05.447
- Extremely violent. These
tribes have remained alive

00:20:05.508 --> 00:20:09.038
because of their violence. Like the Spartans
or the Comanches, they seem to have

00:20:09.088 --> 00:20:12.437
adopted violence as a
first response to contact.

00:20:12.528 --> 00:20:16.428
- Maybe you can correct me on this,
but I read that in the late 19th

00:20:16.488 --> 00:20:23.928
century, early 20th century, there was
documentation of encounters with these tribes

00:20:24.228 --> 00:20:27.648
by the private armies
of the rubber barons.

00:20:27.687 --> 00:20:33.108
And those encounters were, from the rubber
barons' armies' perspective, violent.

00:20:33.127 --> 00:20:37.108
And so maybe the lesson the
uncontacted tribes learned

00:20:37.128 --> 00:20:41.107
is that any interaction with the
outside world is gonna have to be

00:20:41.187 --> 00:20:43.108
violent because they have
to defend themselves.

00:20:43.168 --> 00:20:47.148
- Yeah. You had colonial missionaries
in the 1600s and 1700s. Then you

00:20:47.187 --> 00:20:50.908
had the rubber barons, late 1800s
into the 1900s, just periods of

00:20:50.947 --> 00:20:54.598
extraction and domination and
cruelty. And these tribes—their

00:20:54.608 --> 00:20:57.828
grandparents must have told them, "When
the outside world comes, you shoot

00:20:57.928 --> 00:21:00.558
first. That's the only thing
that's gonna keep you alive."

00:21:00.588 --> 00:21:04.467
- Do you think the memory of those
violent encounters is defining

00:21:04.768 --> 00:21:06.928
to how they think about the world?

00:21:06.988 --> 00:21:10.908
- Yeah. Because even in my lifetime there,
in the 20 years I've spent in the

00:21:10.988 --> 00:21:14.648
Amazon, Ignacio was shot
in the head. My friend

00:21:14.748 --> 00:21:18.467
Victor survived a violent encounter
where they murdered somebody on a

00:21:18.508 --> 00:21:22.417
beach. They've shot numerous people.
They've even shot people who were trying

00:21:22.447 --> 00:21:26.228
to help them, people who were trying
to give them clothing and bananas.

00:21:26.268 --> 00:21:29.928
They call it porcupining them, where they
find a body on the beach with so many

00:21:30.008 --> 00:21:33.908
arrows that when they fall over,
all the arrows are sticking up.

00:21:33.947 --> 00:21:37.788
And they'll do it out of curiosity
too. It's like, "Hey, you're wearing a

00:21:37.888 --> 00:21:41.298
suit. That's weird. We've never seen
anybody in a black and white suit."

00:21:41.728 --> 00:21:44.868
The way Teddy Roosevelt would
shoot a bird for science.

00:21:44.888 --> 00:21:48.808
They just want to look at
you. And so they're operating

00:21:48.848 --> 00:21:52.808
on a different... They don't have the
moral system that we have or understand.

00:21:52.868 --> 00:21:56.048
They're truly wild.

00:21:56.088 --> 00:21:59.248
- How does Ignacio think about them?
Because they almost killed him.

00:21:59.288 --> 00:22:03.028
- Yes. It depends on the mood you
get him in, because if you ask

00:22:03.128 --> 00:22:07.088
him... One day I asked him, "If you
could see the people who shot you

00:22:07.108 --> 00:22:10.588
in the head, what would you say to them?"
And he looked at me with that Ignacio look

00:22:11.428 --> 00:22:15.108
and said, "I wouldn't say anything. I
would kill as many of them as I could."

00:22:15.128 --> 00:22:19.088
He also had a time where he
was in a really remote guard

00:22:19.148 --> 00:22:23.108
station working for the Ministry of Culture,
and they showed up and he knew that

00:22:23.148 --> 00:22:27.068
they were going to kill him.
So he climbed into the peak of

00:22:27.108 --> 00:22:31.028
the little structure there. And
just like a dog in a car, that

00:22:31.068 --> 00:22:35.018
greenhouse effect in the top at midday
with the sun beating down, he was

00:22:35.068 --> 00:22:38.318
huddled over a mattress while
they were walking on the deck—

00:22:38.447 --> 00:22:41.818
...moving pots and pans and looking
at our items and artifacts.

00:22:41.868 --> 00:22:45.808
And he knew that if he was
found, they'd kill him. But

00:22:45.848 --> 00:22:49.728
if he stayed up there, he was literally
frying. He said he was soaking the mattress.

00:22:49.748 --> 00:22:53.648
He could feel himself dying. For
two hours he had to stay there.

00:22:53.688 --> 00:22:57.638
And he was constantly making this decision:
"If I come out, I die. If I stay,

00:22:57.768 --> 00:23:01.588
I probably die." He's like, "Probably
die is better than definitely die."

00:23:01.708 --> 00:23:05.487
So he was terrified. And as they're
screaming, "Mashko," everybody's running,

00:23:05.588 --> 00:23:09.528
Ignacio comes and finds me. You
can see in his eyes, you can see

00:23:09.568 --> 00:23:11.348
when somebody has that PTSD response,

00:23:12.188 --> 00:23:16.088
he's breathing heavy.
He's moving behind trees.

00:23:16.168 --> 00:23:19.708
He's keeping me close to him and
going, "Look there. He has a bow."

00:23:19.788 --> 00:23:23.358
"He has a bow." And we're looking
up the beach, and there's just this

00:23:23.408 --> 00:23:27.338
clan of naked men walking down the
beach with these seven-foot bows,

00:23:27.348 --> 00:23:31.318
and they're hunched over, pointing at
us. They're going, "Look at that one."

00:23:31.328 --> 00:23:34.548
"Look, there's a gun there." You can
see them communicating to each other.

00:23:34.557 --> 00:23:38.368
The butterflies are swirling off
the beach. In these moments you go,

00:23:38.408 --> 00:23:42.308
"Am I entering a moment that
is— is this a one-way door?"

00:23:42.348 --> 00:23:46.108
"Is this an irreversible situation?"
Because there's an unfolding situation

00:23:46.208 --> 00:23:50.088
where they're coming towards us. Are
they going to attack? What do they want?

00:23:50.168 --> 00:23:55.438
Is there going to be a... I mean, I am

00:23:56.528 --> 00:24:00.428
soaked in chills right now talking about
it, because I remember standing there,

00:24:00.438 --> 00:24:04.108
going, "There's no way this is real
life." It's burned into my memory, them

00:24:04.188 --> 00:24:07.928
walking down the beach with the
bows. And of course, you know,

00:24:07.967 --> 00:24:11.628
Stefan is up there firing off pictures
and Mohsin is down getting video.

00:24:11.668 --> 00:24:15.638
And the community that
we're with, people had...

00:24:15.668 --> 00:24:18.717
You hear shotgun shells loading home.

00:24:18.748 --> 00:24:22.728
They're getting ready. And there's this
one guy, this anthropologist named Romel,

00:24:22.788 --> 00:24:30.704
who has been the only person who has
communicated with them peacefully. He did it

00:24:30.714 --> 00:24:34.104
in 2013, where he stood on the beach
and spoke to them. He knows enough

00:24:34.184 --> 00:24:37.974
of the local dialect that
overlaps with theirs that he can

00:24:38.043 --> 00:24:41.694
speak to them. And as they're coming down
the beach, the butterflies are flying up,

00:24:41.744 --> 00:24:45.714
and we're all waiting. And again,
shotgun, you're talking, you

00:24:45.744 --> 00:24:49.283
know, how many meters? 30, 40 meters?
I don't know accurate. For an

00:24:49.384 --> 00:24:53.313
arrow, you loose a seven-foot arrow that
weighs nothing, you're talking about

00:24:53.343 --> 00:24:57.184
300 meters easy. They can shoot
you from across the river. So

00:24:57.224 --> 00:25:01.083
Ignacio was pulling me and he
was like, "Down. You go down."

00:25:01.104 --> 00:25:05.033
"You stay behind this tree. Watch them
from there. Watch out, he has an arrow."

00:25:05.043 --> 00:25:08.624
He was watching everyone because you could
see, he's like, "This is how it happens."

00:25:08.944 --> 00:25:14.684
- Did you think this might be the last day
you have on this earth? Were you afraid?

00:25:14.823 --> 00:25:18.583
- I was, yeah, of course I
was afraid. You're with-

00:25:18.604 --> 00:25:22.204
I'm with my two best friends and
people that I work very closely

00:25:22.244 --> 00:25:26.173
with. You're in the middle of nowhere,
there's no help coming, and you're with-

00:25:26.604 --> 00:25:30.404
...26 people and there's
50 of the tribe that you

00:25:30.444 --> 00:25:34.303
can see, and you know they're surrounding
us. There are men on the other side

00:25:34.322 --> 00:25:38.204
of the river. And then we had
guns looking back towards the

00:25:38.244 --> 00:25:42.073
jungle because we knew we were being
surrounded. And so, again, this is

00:25:42.124 --> 00:25:45.934
always the story of someone's
uncle, brother, or cousin

00:25:46.444 --> 00:25:50.264
telling a story that happened, and now
it's happening. Not in the shadows,

00:25:50.303 --> 00:25:53.583
not in the middle of the night.
It's happening in broad daylight.

00:25:53.924 --> 00:25:57.813
They're walking out onto the beach.
It's like the first time they saw the

00:25:57.813 --> 00:26:02.033
dinosaurs in Jurassic Park.
You're going, "There's no way."

00:26:02.033 --> 00:26:06.394
- And you are walking on the knife's
edge. And it's funny you say this,

00:26:06.394 --> 00:26:11.204
about taking pictures. Because there's two
ways to think of this situation. This is

00:26:11.264 --> 00:26:16.684
fascinating, or this is extremely
dangerous. It's both. It's a knife's edge.

00:26:16.704 --> 00:26:18.594
So you could approach it one of two ways.

00:26:18.664 --> 00:26:22.024
"If I die, I die. I'm going
to take some good pictures."

00:26:22.043 --> 00:26:25.934
- But that was also our
mission. As the directors of

00:26:25.944 --> 00:26:29.494
Jungle Keepers, we work with this
community to ensure their lifestyle can

00:26:29.524 --> 00:26:33.384
continue, and they're saying,
"Hey, that's great, but as an

00:26:33.444 --> 00:26:37.333
indigenous community, we're dealing with
people that raid our stuff, try and

00:26:37.464 --> 00:26:41.444
steal our women, and kill our hunters. Now
they're coming out. We want you to see

00:26:41.484 --> 00:26:45.323
it." Documenting it is part
of our job. We have to

00:26:45.384 --> 00:26:49.114
show what happened that
day. And so those guys were

00:26:49.114 --> 00:26:52.904
shooting. And very
seriously, it's actually...

00:26:53.424 --> 00:26:57.254
Mohsin's wife and I always joked,
"If the tribe ever comes out,

00:26:57.264 --> 00:27:01.024
you stand in front of him, you
take the arrow. He has kids."

00:27:01.103 --> 00:27:04.704
And that day, we were
strategically positioning

00:27:04.724 --> 00:27:08.624
ourselves, being like,
"You, down. You cannot

00:27:08.664 --> 00:27:12.563
get killed." In those moments,
you start to go, "Okay, where

00:27:12.583 --> 00:27:16.424
will I be safe from arrows?
Where can I run to the

00:27:16.444 --> 00:27:20.424
river if they come over?" And you
start planning, "Okay, if I jump

00:27:20.464 --> 00:27:24.364
into the river..." I was going, "Okay, I got my
bag. I have a can of tuna. I have a flashlight."

00:27:24.384 --> 00:27:27.924
I was like, "If I jump into the river
and float down and I live, I'm still

00:27:28.384 --> 00:27:32.244
days upriver." And so you start
going through all these things.

00:27:32.283 --> 00:27:35.984
- And of course, the Mashco Piro people
are thinking exactly the same thing,

00:27:36.823 --> 00:27:37.504
probably.

00:27:37.543 --> 00:27:40.894
- Well, the interesting thing is that
they're initiating the contact, right?

00:27:40.944 --> 00:27:44.823
They are the ones coming out of
the jungle and confronting us.

00:27:44.884 --> 00:27:51.264
- And fundamentally, that contact is- they're
at least giving peace a chance. They're

00:27:51.344 --> 00:27:55.323
trying the peaceful contact
first, correct? Or was there

00:27:55.344 --> 00:27:58.964
a violent element? Like,
what did you sense in the

00:27:59.024 --> 00:28:02.063
caution of them emerging to the beach?

00:28:02.144 --> 00:28:07.764
- Fear. As they came out, you could
see fear on them because the way

00:28:07.823 --> 00:28:11.783
they were hunched over, the
way they had their bows ready,

00:28:11.823 --> 00:28:15.524
they were worried. And so they
came and Romel is standing there

00:28:15.603 --> 00:28:19.524
closer than any of us at the edge, on
one side of the river. And it was like

00:28:19.563 --> 00:28:21.783
shirts versus skins. It was two
tribes looking at each other

00:28:23.004 --> 00:28:26.864
with a thousand years of civilization
between them. And Romel's

00:28:26.904 --> 00:28:28.293
going, "Put down your bows.

00:28:29.103 --> 00:28:32.934
Put down your bows and we can talk."
And he's saying, "Namole, Namole."

00:28:32.964 --> 00:28:35.033
He kept saying, "Brothers,
brothers, please put down your..."

00:28:35.043 --> 00:28:39.543
- So Namole means brother in a language
that they might be able to understand?

00:28:39.553 --> 00:28:43.273
- Namole means brother in a language
that they do understand, and

00:28:43.303 --> 00:28:48.783
it seems like they refer to themselves
as the Namoles. The brothers.

00:28:48.803 --> 00:28:53.754
- So potentially, that's what they
call themselves as a tribe, Namoles?

00:28:53.803 --> 00:28:58.424
- Exactly. And actually, the anthropologists
that we've been speaking to post-event

00:28:59.303 --> 00:29:03.244
have been explaining to us
that- you know, Piro is the

00:29:03.264 --> 00:29:07.144
group that they're from,
these various nomadic tribes.

00:29:07.164 --> 00:29:12.324
And Mashco basically means "wild Piros." One
thing we know they call themselves is Namoles.

00:29:12.333 --> 00:29:16.103
- So we might converge towards the
name of this tribe being Namole

00:29:16.184 --> 00:29:17.214
versus Mashco Piro?

00:29:17.224 --> 00:29:21.004
- The Namoles, yeah. It seems like
the most current self-appointed

00:29:21.083 --> 00:29:24.244
identity is the brothers, Namole.

00:29:24.283 --> 00:29:29.214
- Anyway, there's these shredded warriors
on the beach. They're gigantic.

00:29:29.214 --> 00:29:32.824
- With seven-foot arrows, and
we're all standing there. And so

00:29:32.904 --> 00:29:36.734
the first thing, again,
you just think of like the

00:29:36.824 --> 00:29:40.654
peace pipe in the old stories.
And the first thing is,

00:29:40.704 --> 00:29:44.144
"Let's make them an offering of
peace." So they got a canoe with no

00:29:44.264 --> 00:29:48.114
motor, and we piled it
with plantains, just

00:29:48.283 --> 00:29:51.984
full of plantains, 16 feet
of endless green bananas.

00:29:52.024 --> 00:29:56.014
And then, I mean, the balls on
this guy, the anthropologist-

00:29:56.063 --> 00:29:59.774
he gets into the river, takes
the canoe, and it's the

00:29:59.824 --> 00:30:03.224
dry season, so the river's only
about three or four feet deep at the

00:30:03.283 --> 00:30:07.224
channel. And so he walks
this thing out, this one man

00:30:07.264 --> 00:30:10.964
walking in the face of all these
warriors. He takes the boat and he

00:30:10.984 --> 00:30:14.764
pushes it towards them. And
they rush out, and they start

00:30:14.884 --> 00:30:18.764
grabbing the bananas, and they're
not going, "Okay, we will unload

00:30:18.803 --> 00:30:22.154
these bananas and use them
later." They're my bananas.

00:30:22.154 --> 00:30:26.094
And they're fighting, yelling,
and they're all grabbing 'em,

00:30:26.103 --> 00:30:27.333
and then they push the boat back

00:30:28.283 --> 00:30:31.824
and he talks to them a little bit.
It's not a perfect translation,

00:30:31.864 --> 00:30:35.644
so he's saying, "Where have you come from?
What do you want? Who's your leader?"

00:30:35.884 --> 00:30:39.764
And he's trying to establish these things,
and they all sort of talk at the same

00:30:39.803 --> 00:30:43.364
time, like a flock of birds.
It wasn't like one man speaks.

00:30:43.543 --> 00:30:47.444
And there were no women.
The women were nowhere

00:30:47.484 --> 00:30:51.216
to be seen. And actually,
at one point as we were

00:30:51.256 --> 00:30:54.876
preparing, I think it was while we were
preparing the second canoe of bananas,

00:30:55.696 --> 00:30:59.815
there was a moment of absolute panic.

00:31:00.776 --> 00:31:04.596
It happened when there was a noise
behind us and you just hear shotguns

00:31:04.676 --> 00:31:08.356
swing behind us. And, you
know, Mohsin goes down. I go

00:31:08.456 --> 00:31:11.876
running away from the river because I
want to see if there's an attack coming.

00:31:11.916 --> 00:31:15.636
And I'm standing, me and this guy
were sharing a tree as cover,

00:31:15.976 --> 00:31:19.206
and he's got a shotgun and he's
looking back into the forest.

00:31:20.196 --> 00:31:24.096
And what was happening was the
women of the tribe had come

00:31:24.156 --> 00:31:27.816
silently, and they were just pulling
yucca out of the ground and taking the

00:31:27.836 --> 00:31:31.816
banana plants and ruining the farm
completely. They were raiding the farm

00:31:31.836 --> 00:31:35.805
behind us while the men were
talking up here. So again,

00:31:35.836 --> 00:31:40.796
were they peacefully contacting us or were
they like, "Hey, go make a diversion and

00:31:40.856 --> 00:31:42.836
take the food out the back"?

00:31:42.846 --> 00:31:44.736
- So I mean, you really were surrounded.

00:31:44.796 --> 00:31:46.756
- We were completely surrounded.

00:31:46.796 --> 00:31:51.096
- So they could have murdered
all of you, probably.

00:31:51.176 --> 00:31:54.856
- Easily. We were outnumbered
five to one at the least.

00:31:54.916 --> 00:31:58.776
- Yeah. And maybe they wanted peace,
but part of the reason is they

00:31:58.816 --> 00:32:04.596
didn't know how deep this goes.
They didn't know if you had backup.

00:32:04.656 --> 00:32:08.566
- They don't know if we have backup.
They also had questions. Some of

00:32:08.576 --> 00:32:12.496
their questions were incredible: "How
do we tell the difference between,

00:32:12.536 --> 00:32:16.176
how do we know who the good
guys and the bad guys are?"

00:32:16.235 --> 00:32:19.996
Because to them, all you
outsiders are the same.

00:32:20.036 --> 00:32:22.485
So why, who were the ones
cutting down the trees?

00:32:22.516 --> 00:32:25.506
- And those are the ones they
know are the bad guys.

00:32:25.536 --> 00:32:29.406
- Well, the big trees seemed to have
incredible significance to them.

00:32:29.436 --> 00:32:33.186
They're significant to us in a
different way, but to them, it's

00:32:33.235 --> 00:32:37.016
offensive on an almost religious

00:32:37.116 --> 00:32:40.046
level to cut a big tree, as
if you're killing their gods.

00:32:40.296 --> 00:32:43.026
- So there's a spirituality
to the trees to them.

00:32:43.076 --> 00:32:43.906
- It seems like that.

00:32:43.916 --> 00:32:46.796
- And so whoever's cutting them down
is a source of destruction on a

00:32:46.896 --> 00:32:50.836
spiritual, existential level.

00:32:50.876 --> 00:32:54.636
- spiritual, existential level. They
ask, "Why would you destroy our home?"

00:32:54.696 --> 00:32:58.185
- In a deep sense, the uncontacted tribes

00:32:58.476 --> 00:33:01.716
represent the deep
jungle. And so if they're

00:33:01.735 --> 00:33:06.016
threatened, that means the jungle,
the deep jungle is threatened.

00:33:06.756 --> 00:33:10.006
- They are the human voice of the jungle and

00:33:10.116 --> 00:33:14.046
they're asking questions and they're also
demanding. You know, they're clapping at

00:33:14.116 --> 00:33:18.026
us and they're waving and they're saying,
"Send more bananas." And so they loaded up

00:33:18.056 --> 00:33:21.856
another boat and they pushed another boat
out, and this time they gave them some rope.

00:33:21.876 --> 00:33:25.116
They all had rope tied around
their waists, penises tied up.

00:33:25.216 --> 00:33:29.016
But they love rope and some of them
were wearing rope that they had

00:33:29.036 --> 00:33:32.936
made, which is brown or reddish. And
then some of them were wearing rope

00:33:33.156 --> 00:33:37.116
that they had clearly pillaged from logging
camps or the communities because it was

00:33:37.176 --> 00:33:41.056
modern nylon paracord. And they had
this wound around their waists like

00:33:41.216 --> 00:33:44.965
a thick belt. And they took
the second boat and they had

00:33:44.996 --> 00:33:47.646
some rope and they had
some plantains on there.

00:33:47.656 --> 00:33:51.636
- So, some of these guys might have been
the ones that murdered the loggers.

00:33:51.646 --> 00:33:51.946
- Could be.

00:33:51.976 --> 00:33:53.905
- From a couple of months before that.

00:33:53.996 --> 00:33:57.916
- Absolutely, could be. But what Ramal
said as he was talking to them,

00:33:57.936 --> 00:34:01.566
he turned to us and he said,
"The other groups call me the

00:34:01.616 --> 00:34:04.816
Grandfather." He said, "This group, I don't
know any of these." He said, "This is first

00:34:04.896 --> 00:34:08.755
contact." He said, "This is the
first time this group is talking to

00:34:08.815 --> 00:34:12.835
us." And you saw people
from maybe 12 years old to

00:34:13.676 --> 00:34:18.716
what looks like 40-something,
like a banged-up 40.

00:34:18.735 --> 00:34:22.496
And no really old people and no women.

00:34:22.556 --> 00:34:24.685
- So this is a particular
clan of the uncontacted-

00:34:24.685 --> 00:34:25.065
- It's a particular clan,

00:34:25.076 --> 00:34:28.525
- a tribe who they've never contacted.

00:34:28.536 --> 00:34:32.355
Is there, just from your memory,
interesting aspects about the way they were

00:34:32.396 --> 00:34:36.315
trying to communicate? Like you
said, clapping. I think it's,

00:34:36.335 --> 00:34:40.275
from an anthropology perspective, from a human
perspective, fascinating. How do you talk to

00:34:40.396 --> 00:34:43.136
people from an uncontacted
tribe like this?

00:34:43.146 --> 00:34:47.076
So clapping, yelling. It's interesting
to know that there's not a hierarchy

00:34:47.116 --> 00:34:51.036
where there's a leader that represents.
Or is that something we know for sure?

00:34:51.096 --> 00:34:54.436
- Before even coming to talk to you
about this, we passed this through

00:34:54.496 --> 00:34:57.856
anthropologists and ethicists
and we said, "Look, is it

00:34:57.936 --> 00:35:01.826
even okay? Can we talk about this?"
Because if you talk about this,

00:35:02.056 --> 00:35:05.586
and you tell people there's these uncontacted
tribes, people have misconceptions.

00:35:05.586 --> 00:35:09.556
They go, "They're the last free
people on Earth. We need to go

00:35:09.616 --> 00:35:13.366
join them. We want to see them." There's
all this bad stuff that happens,

00:35:13.956 --> 00:35:17.776
and all these people want to be left
alone. So the last thing we want to do is

00:35:18.056 --> 00:35:21.356
kill the thing we're trying to protect
and tell the world. But at the same

00:35:21.416 --> 00:35:25.395
time, they're speaking out. They're
saying, "Stop cutting our trees. Leave

00:35:25.436 --> 00:35:29.256
us alone." And so if we're
not successful in the greater

00:35:29.336 --> 00:35:32.416
Jungle Keepers' mission of
protecting this river, they cease to

00:35:32.476 --> 00:35:36.316
exist. And so advocating
for these people requires

00:35:36.396 --> 00:35:39.836
us to have this conversation. It requires
us to have this footage and to show the

00:35:39.896 --> 00:35:42.176
world, and then leave them alone.

00:35:43.836 --> 00:35:46.636
In order for any of this to make sense,
I have to show you this footage.

00:35:46.676 --> 00:35:49.536
- And this has not been shown ever before.

00:35:49.996 --> 00:35:53.736
- This is a world first. I mean, up until now...
You know, we're sitting there this day and-

00:35:53.756 --> 00:35:57.586
the only thing you've ever seen are these
blurry images of them from someone's

00:35:57.636 --> 00:36:01.596
cellphone from 100 meters away of the
uncontacted tribes. And we're sitting there with

00:36:01.636 --> 00:36:05.376
800 millimeters with a 2X
teleconverter and, you know, R5s.

00:36:05.436 --> 00:36:09.996
And so, this is as we're
looking through the vines,

00:36:11.216 --> 00:36:15.696
anticipating the tribe coming. I'll put a
little bit of volume so you can hear it.

00:36:16.776 --> 00:36:20.606
And then you can see, this is the moment. This
is us running when they're like, "They're

00:36:20.656 --> 00:36:23.156
out. They're coming down the beach."

00:36:25.596 --> 00:36:29.596
- Oh, wow. Oh, wow.

00:36:31.716 --> 00:36:33.096
- You see how many thousands of

00:36:33.136 --> 00:36:37.036
butterflies? But look at the
way they move. Look at the

00:36:37.056 --> 00:36:39.586
way they point. Look at him with his bow.

00:36:39.616 --> 00:36:43.656
- Wow.

00:36:45.696 --> 00:36:46.276
- There it is.

00:36:48.476 --> 00:36:54.304
- They're trying to figure out
what they're looking at.

00:36:54.324 --> 00:36:57.884
- And they didn't know the cameras were there.
So this was the guys looking out the back.

00:36:57.924 --> 00:37:00.084
So he's going, "There's
something back here." He could-

00:37:00.094 --> 00:37:04.024
hear the women in the farm. And I'm
looking in every direction because I'm

00:37:04.044 --> 00:37:05.534
going, "Which way is
the arrow coming from?"

00:37:06.344 --> 00:37:10.284
But see, he has his shotgun. This is just like a
farm shotgun. Even if he shot it, you have to use a

00:37:10.324 --> 00:37:14.124
stick to bang out the shell. But
see, as they come closer, they start

00:37:14.204 --> 00:37:20.344
laying down their... See, he's laying
down his bow and arrow. They understand.

00:37:22.144 --> 00:37:25.884
- So these are warriors, and the way
they were at first moving, it really

00:37:26.004 --> 00:37:31.284
looked like they're ready for violence.
And now they're all standing in a relaxed-

00:37:31.324 --> 00:37:33.764
And they're smiling? Are they smiling?

00:37:33.824 --> 00:37:40.074
- Smiles come at some point. I would say
that one of these guys seemed like

00:37:40.164 --> 00:37:43.124
he was in a leadership position.
He did most of the talking.

00:37:43.164 --> 00:37:47.124
- What's with the different
hand gestures? This,

00:37:47.164 --> 00:37:51.184
the holding your hand up to the
face. All of this means something.

00:37:51.254 --> 00:37:55.744
- All of this means something. Some had red
smeared on their faces. Some had yellow.

00:37:55.764 --> 00:37:58.284
- Did you have a sense of
hierarchy at all, like the boss?

00:37:58.324 --> 00:38:02.124
- Again, there were just these two dominant guys.
And, like, this guy and one other guy who

00:38:02.144 --> 00:38:09.944
looked almost like him, like his
brother. A lot of gesturing.

00:38:10.084 --> 00:38:22.204
- Wow. This is incredible, Paul.

00:38:22.304 --> 00:38:29.214
- Yeah. You see the rope?
Some of that rope is...

00:38:31.144 --> 00:38:33.844
- Yeah, I can kind of tell
who the bosses are.

00:38:33.884 --> 00:38:44.544
- Right? All right, so a few of But
see, even that, as he's pointing-

00:38:44.624 --> 00:38:48.664
what are you pointing at?

00:39:02.484 --> 00:39:05.524
- You guys are nuts. You guys are nuts.

00:39:07.244 --> 00:39:09.874
- You see, though, they're rushing in.
There's this desperation. They're

00:39:09.984 --> 00:39:12.104
hungry. They also—

00:39:12.164 --> 00:39:15.034
- Is that in the water, or is that
Ramo in the water in that case?

00:39:15.034 --> 00:39:18.244
- The, in this particular video,
it's a guy named Liner.

00:39:19.744 --> 00:39:23.384
But see these guys? They're fighting over it.
It's not that we're all going to share it later.

00:39:23.404 --> 00:39:27.364
It's, "I get mine, you get yours."
And so what does that mean?

00:39:27.444 --> 00:39:31.104
- Yeah. But here, they're in
peaceful mode, for sure.

00:39:31.144 --> 00:39:32.664
- Now, after we'd given them,

00:39:33.844 --> 00:39:37.244
after we'd given them several boatloads
of bananas, things did calm down.

00:39:37.324 --> 00:39:41.244
Ramo said to them, "Look, we've given
you what we can give you. We gave

00:39:41.304 --> 00:39:45.613
you sugarcane. We gave you
boatloads of plantains."

00:39:47.224 --> 00:39:50.744
And so then there came a time where things
were a little more relaxed. They were walking

00:39:50.784 --> 00:39:54.664
around. We had a great moment

00:39:54.704 --> 00:39:58.414
where we'd given them the
plantains. We'd given them the

00:39:58.444 --> 00:40:02.384
bananas. And he'd said, "Look,
that's it." He said, "We've given

00:40:02.424 --> 00:40:06.414
you what you asked for. You
asked for bananas. We don't—

00:40:06.484 --> 00:40:10.204
we don't cut the trees here. All of us here
are not tree-cutters. We're indigenous

00:40:10.264 --> 00:40:14.184
people." And he couldn't explain
who the hell we were, but they were

00:40:14.224 --> 00:40:17.953
like, "We don't cut the trees. We're not the
loggers." And they're like, "Okay." So then

00:40:18.124 --> 00:40:20.724
at some point, Ignacio
went out and sort of like

00:40:21.424 --> 00:40:25.404
started, you know, he'd go like this
and they'd go like this. And he'd dance

00:40:25.424 --> 00:40:29.204
a little bit, they'd dance a little bit.
And then there was this human moment of

00:40:29.264 --> 00:40:29.984
just joking.

00:40:30.024 --> 00:40:31.744
- So even Ignacio warmed up.

00:40:31.804 --> 00:40:35.744
- Even Ignacio warmed up. Once he realized
no one was going to die that day,

00:40:36.724 --> 00:40:39.624
things did calm down.
It was a false sense of

00:40:39.664 --> 00:40:43.634
security. Here, I'll show you.
There's a couple more things that

00:40:43.664 --> 00:40:48.244
are relevant here, though. Yeah, this
is just them interacting with the boat.

00:40:48.264 --> 00:40:51.044
- This is truly incredible, man.

00:40:51.084 --> 00:40:54.874
- But then they don't have boats. They
don't have stone tools. They don't...

00:40:54.884 --> 00:40:59.453
Imagine if you showed them ice.
You know, they wouldn't...

00:40:59.464 --> 00:41:01.264
- This is historic.

00:41:03.484 --> 00:41:07.124
- I mean, it's the... you
hear of Percy Fawcett

00:41:07.144 --> 00:41:11.064
encountering the tribes. We've heard of
anecdotal accounts. This is the first

00:41:11.104 --> 00:41:15.734
time that the tribes have been filmed,
that we can hear their voices—

00:41:15.744 --> 00:41:19.464
...that there's a documented
interaction happening. I mean, look how

00:41:19.504 --> 00:41:22.304
comfortable he's getting. He's
so close. They asked him for his

00:41:22.344 --> 00:41:24.684
shirt. He gave his shirt.

00:41:24.694 --> 00:41:25.164
- This is incredible.

00:41:25.184 --> 00:41:29.584
- They asked him for his pants. He gave
his pants. He was in his underwear.

00:41:29.624 --> 00:41:32.884
You see this? The shirt that's over his

00:41:32.904 --> 00:41:36.444
shoulder? Ignacio took off his
JungleKeeper shirt and threw it

00:41:36.524 --> 00:41:40.504
to the anthropologist, and then the
anthropologist walked off and threw it to them.

00:41:40.564 --> 00:41:44.384
So over the shoulder of that
uncontacted naked warrior

00:41:44.464 --> 00:41:47.444
is a JungleKeeper shirt
with the logo showing.

00:41:47.464 --> 00:41:47.514
- That's great.

00:41:47.514 --> 00:41:49.254
- So their, like, their
second shirt and they're...

00:41:49.264 --> 00:41:52.924
- You just upgraded that guy's status in
the tribe. He's going to be the new

00:41:53.024 --> 00:41:54.134
boss with that shirt.

00:41:54.144 --> 00:42:00.584
- He's got a dope polo. And he didn't even
have to order it. But yeah, this is

00:42:00.594 --> 00:42:04.404
in the aftermath when things
were calm. And then my

00:42:04.444 --> 00:42:07.644
moment with this that really
stuck with me was when

00:42:08.304 --> 00:42:11.764
Ramo said to me, "You
know, they're asking about

00:42:11.824 --> 00:42:15.164
you." And I said, "What are they asking?"

00:42:15.224 --> 00:42:18.894
He goes, "Yeah, they're asking about
you." And again, I'm not tall but

00:42:18.924 --> 00:42:22.824
compared to the people in the village,
I was a little bit taller and had big

00:42:22.844 --> 00:42:26.604
shoulders. And he said, "They said you
look like a warrior. Could you come

00:42:26.704 --> 00:42:30.234
forward? Show them that you don't
mean any harm. Show them your

00:42:30.324 --> 00:42:34.664
palms." And so he pulled me up onto
the beach, right before they left.

00:42:35.864 --> 00:42:48.404
I hold up my hands. Listen. And
they sang back. They're singing.

00:42:48.414 --> 00:42:50.244
They raised their hands.
I raised my hands.

00:42:50.344 --> 00:43:07.948
- Wow.

00:43:08.028 --> 00:43:13.508
- And then we were left watching
them walk off the beach

00:43:14.608 --> 00:43:16.648
into the jungle with everything
that we'd given them,

00:43:18.148 --> 00:43:22.028
and they were gone. And so
we went downriver the next

00:43:22.088 --> 00:43:25.798
day and the community said to us, "Okay,
now you understand this is real. This is

00:43:25.848 --> 00:43:29.817
terrifying. You felt that fear. You have a
duty, if you're gonna protect this river,

00:43:29.848 --> 00:43:33.628
to protect us from them and to help us

00:43:33.728 --> 00:43:37.568
figure out what future they want. If they
want to come to us, if they want to learn

00:43:37.748 --> 00:43:40.308
farming, if they... whatever it is,

00:43:41.588 --> 00:43:44.408
that's fine." But they were like,
"We need protection from you

00:43:44.468 --> 00:43:47.348
guys." And then in this video in the

00:43:47.388 --> 00:43:51.128
beginning, I'm narrating to
the camera and walking around

00:43:52.348 --> 00:43:57.188
right as they're coming up the
beach. But you see this guy,

00:43:58.528 --> 00:44:00.598
right there in the blue shirt?

00:44:00.628 --> 00:44:04.528
That's George. And he was very friendly,
very confident with this. He said, "Don't be

00:44:04.688 --> 00:44:08.418
scared. They're not going to hurt us."
And the next day, we went back to

00:44:08.468 --> 00:44:12.398
town—long journey back to town.
We go to sleep, we wake up in the

00:44:12.468 --> 00:44:15.208
morning, and we find out
that the following early

00:44:15.288 --> 00:44:18.928
morning, our friends in the community
had said, "Okay, the tribe is

00:44:18.968 --> 00:44:22.808
gone. We gave them sugarcane,
bananas, and said, 'Please

00:44:22.868 --> 00:44:26.848
come back, you're welcome here
anytime.'" And George was driving a boat

00:44:27.428 --> 00:44:31.408
with people on board, and as they
were going upriver, 200 of the

00:44:31.448 --> 00:44:35.358
tribe ran out, surrounded the boat, and they
started firing arrows. Everybody else hit

00:44:35.388 --> 00:44:38.958
the deck and got under the
benches and hid behind

00:44:39.768 --> 00:44:43.688
bags of rice. George was driving
as fast as he could, leaning back

00:44:43.728 --> 00:44:47.188
while driving. And one arrow came
in just above his scapula and came

00:44:47.288 --> 00:44:52.128
out by his belly button. And so
he had that seven-foot arrow tip

00:44:53.208 --> 00:44:57.108
through him. They pulled
him out, and I saw the boat

00:44:57.228 --> 00:45:00.848
afterward, and there's just horrific
amounts of blood all over the

00:45:00.868 --> 00:45:04.748
boat. He had to be medevacked
out, and somehow he lived.

00:45:04.768 --> 00:45:07.848
And we were able to help getting
him a helicopter, getting him

00:45:07.908 --> 00:45:11.038
evaced, all this. But again, you just go,

00:45:11.088 --> 00:45:14.888
"What..." you know, these
people came out of the

00:45:14.908 --> 00:45:17.818
jungle and they asked for
bananas. We gave them bananas and

00:45:17.868 --> 00:45:21.428
we, in every way possible
said, "We mean peace. We want

00:45:21.528 --> 00:45:28.128
friendship with you." And then
the next day, they attacked.

00:45:28.168 --> 00:45:32.068
- What do you think happened? Why do
you think their mind turned? Or

00:45:34.208 --> 00:45:40.928
maybe this has to do with the role of
violence in their society. Maybe it's so

00:45:41.408 --> 00:45:46.008
integrated into how they interact with the
world that they don't even see that as a

00:45:47.348 --> 00:45:50.508
fundamental shift in the interaction.

00:45:50.648 --> 00:45:54.508
- I don't know. I don't know what to make of it.
And the only thing I can think is that the

00:45:54.528 --> 00:45:58.388
way they hid the women from us, you don't know
for them, maybe we're not allowed to see their

00:45:58.428 --> 00:46:02.408
women, you know? Because the one
thing that we got was that as George—

00:46:02.428 --> 00:46:06.288
George's boat and this other boat
were going upriver, which is how they

00:46:06.308 --> 00:46:10.098
live—it's not like they were doing anything
wrong. These people live in a community days

00:46:10.128 --> 00:46:14.048
into the Amazon, they were going
fishing. And so they came around

00:46:14.108 --> 00:46:18.048
a bend and I think they spooked the
tribe. The tribe might have just acted

00:46:18.068 --> 00:46:21.998
defensively and said, "We don't know who this
is." The motors could have set them off, we don't

00:46:22.008 --> 00:46:29.128
know. But they shot him. And then the other
thing is the thing with the necklace.

00:46:29.188 --> 00:46:33.108
I've asked anthropologists about
this, and their answer was that at

00:46:33.148 --> 00:46:40.688
this point they said, "You
know more than we do."

00:46:40.698 --> 00:46:44.568
Because two of them had the
exact same item around their

00:46:44.668 --> 00:46:47.888
necks, and it seems to be a Brazil nut

00:46:48.588 --> 00:46:52.398
and then some sort of casing around the
side, and it looked like animal teeth

00:46:52.668 --> 00:46:55.408
positioned in there. And it's like, what are
you carrying? Are you carrying medicine?

00:46:55.448 --> 00:46:59.128
Are you carrying some sort of a totem?
But both of them... and it's not a

00:46:59.188 --> 00:47:03.848
comfortable thing to wear around your neck—
you know, grapefruit-sized or bigger.

00:47:03.868 --> 00:47:08.728
- Do you have a sense if that's a
container or is it just like a totem?

00:47:08.788 --> 00:47:12.668
- It seems like a container. If they
didn't let it get wet, they cared

00:47:12.728 --> 00:47:16.308
for it. The guy in this picture,
he's got this... this is a piece

00:47:16.388 --> 00:47:20.148
of tree fiber that he has it on
him, and then he's gotten his

00:47:20.188 --> 00:47:23.848
hands on Brazil nut sacks, plastic
sacks from one of the farms

00:47:23.908 --> 00:47:27.508
across the river. And so they just
take, they take. And one of them got a

00:47:27.548 --> 00:47:31.308
machete and he was walking. As they were leaving,
again, during that period where they got

00:47:31.388 --> 00:47:35.068
friendly, he was leaving and he had the
machete, playing with it and swinging it at

00:47:35.088 --> 00:47:38.788
butterflies. And one of my friends,
this guy Bacho, he goes, "Oye, deja mi

00:47:38.888 --> 00:47:43.248
machete." He's like, "Drop the machete." And the guy just
looked at him and was like, "Yeah, come and get it."

00:47:43.288 --> 00:47:45.468
You know, it's like, "Yeah, you cross
the river and see what happens."

00:47:46.528 --> 00:47:51.328
- Do you think he figured out, or they
later figured out, how to use a machete?

00:47:51.388 --> 00:47:52.648
- Oh, they know the machete.

00:47:52.688 --> 00:47:53.318
- They understand the machete?

00:47:53.348 --> 00:47:56.478
- Yeah, they do raids for machetes.

00:47:56.488 --> 00:47:59.068
- They understand the power
of sharpened metal.

00:47:59.108 --> 00:48:05.868
- It's an Excalibur sword to them. But
yeah, that one has stuck with me

00:48:05.908 --> 00:48:07.678
because I wonder, what were
they carrying in there?

00:48:08.548 --> 00:48:10.328
- So what are some of the
questions? Like if you could

00:48:11.488 --> 00:48:14.548
know everything you'd
want to know about them—

00:48:14.588 --> 00:48:17.368
Maybe in the space of communication and
language, that's really interesting.

00:48:17.388 --> 00:48:21.598
You mentioned that there's all
kinds of calls, animal calls.

00:48:21.608 --> 00:48:25.368
So they obviously know
how to fake animal calls.

00:48:25.408 --> 00:48:28.868
- Yeah, they can use animal calls with

00:48:28.908 --> 00:48:32.768
enough complexity that they can
do basic commands. They can speak

00:48:32.808 --> 00:48:36.588
in Capuchin; they use
Tinamou calls. Some of our

00:48:36.608 --> 00:48:40.118
rangers were upriver a few
months ago. This is recently,

00:48:40.248 --> 00:48:47.868
they were upriver and they found a
Nomole trail, a Mashco-Piro trail,

00:48:47.988 --> 00:48:51.688
and it was Ignacio, of course.
He made a secret whistle

00:48:51.748 --> 00:48:56.308
out into the jungle and he's listening,

00:48:57.248 --> 00:49:00.832
and they whistle back. So he
and everybody on the team just

00:49:00.992 --> 00:49:04.372
ran back to the boat and got out of
there. But at least they answered.

00:49:04.412 --> 00:49:08.291
They didn't just shoot. He whistled,
they whistled, and they said, "Out,"

00:49:08.872 --> 00:49:11.112
and he got out. But we don't know,

00:49:11.992 --> 00:49:15.762
where are the old people? Do
they not survive? What are

00:49:15.812 --> 00:49:19.672
the marriage rituals? How
is reproduction handled?

00:49:19.792 --> 00:49:23.632
There are one or two
children in the Amazon that

00:49:23.812 --> 00:49:27.342
I know of who have washed
downriver on a log and

00:49:27.352 --> 00:49:31.152
been rescued by communities
and raised. They either

00:49:31.192 --> 00:49:34.601
learn the native dialect or Spanish, and
then, at some point, somebody will go and

00:49:34.652 --> 00:49:40.232
ask, "What was it like when you lived with
them?" The answer is always the same:

00:49:40.912 --> 00:49:45.912
"I forget." They don't talk about it.

00:49:46.112 --> 00:49:48.912
- So maybe we know that they value

00:49:49.012 --> 00:49:52.372
secrecy. I mean, when you're
afraid of the outside world,

00:49:52.432 --> 00:49:57.772
part of that is confidentiality.
They all sign NDAs.

00:49:57.782 --> 00:49:59.512
- Yeah, there are some really good NDAs.

00:50:00.592 --> 00:50:03.912
- It's an understood NDA. There are no

00:50:04.012 --> 00:50:08.012
lawyers. There's only one
way to execute the law.

00:50:08.072 --> 00:50:11.962
- Yeah. It's either a really
strong NDA or that it is

00:50:11.962 --> 00:50:15.642
savage living out there in the
jungle, where you're eating

00:50:15.712 --> 00:50:19.612
monkeys and turtles and you're
hungry for days on end.

00:50:19.672 --> 00:50:23.482
Your wife might get stolen by
another tribe. Your baby might get

00:50:23.532 --> 00:50:27.412
stolen—imagine the botflies and the things

00:50:27.452 --> 00:50:31.092
that they must put up with.
It's just... I mean, what we

00:50:31.132 --> 00:50:36.032
experienced in three days of living
with modern camping gear, headlamps,

00:50:36.932 --> 00:50:39.972
and a sense of direction—they're
doing none of that. Put us out there

00:50:40.072 --> 00:50:42.992
naked, a very different story.

00:50:43.012 --> 00:50:44.822
- Yeah, the brutality of nature—

00:50:44.872 --> 00:50:49.242
Werner Herzog comes to mind.
They have to live in that.

00:50:49.272 --> 00:50:51.992
But then there's something about the

00:50:52.032 --> 00:50:57.002
jungle that serves as a catalyst for
spirituality, so they must also have

00:50:57.892 --> 00:51:01.392
a religious component,
a spiritual component

00:51:01.402 --> 00:51:06.162
that probably unifies them. There must
be an ideology they operate under.

00:51:06.192 --> 00:51:09.261
- Oh, there must be. There's
many things they must have.

00:51:09.272 --> 00:51:12.932
They must have a belief system.
They probably have amazing origin

00:51:13.032 --> 00:51:16.872
stories. It would be
amazing to know what things

00:51:16.912 --> 00:51:20.792
they have accurately and
inaccurately guessed about

00:51:20.832 --> 00:51:24.792
us, about the outside world. I
mean, they've never heard of

00:51:24.832 --> 00:51:30.672
the country they live in or of World War
II or any of it. And so seeing them come

00:51:30.692 --> 00:51:36.752
across the beach was surreal because
it's like this aperture into history.

00:51:36.772 --> 00:51:40.141
- By the way, you do have a certain
look, so you realize like—

00:51:40.152 --> 00:51:43.852
as I'm speaking to you, your face
is carved in some wood somewhere,

00:51:44.832 --> 00:51:46.412
And there's a few of them gathering around

00:51:47.312 --> 00:51:50.662
and like still singing about
the great gringo with the—

00:51:50.662 --> 00:51:54.412
- The full beard and the big nose. They
probably drew this like, "He's got

00:51:54.712 --> 00:51:57.752
hair all over his face and a huge
nose, and they tell their children.

00:51:57.812 --> 00:51:59.332
- Yeah. And it could be anything. They—

00:51:59.352 --> 00:52:03.172
To the children, they say, "This is
the monster you should be afraid

00:52:03.232 --> 00:52:07.212
of," or this could be the most beautiful

00:52:07.272 --> 00:52:10.852
encapsulation of the outside
world. It could be everything in

00:52:10.892 --> 00:52:12.882
between. You don't get
to control the myths.

00:52:12.932 --> 00:52:16.742
- You don't get to control the
myths. Yeah, God only knows, but

00:52:16.752 --> 00:52:17.852
- That's so interesting.

00:52:17.912 --> 00:52:21.892
- So now, in that 130,000 acres
that we have, we know—and this

00:52:21.952 --> 00:52:25.112
is what we sort of have to come out with—

00:52:25.812 --> 00:52:29.752
we are now protecting
these people. And the

00:52:29.832 --> 00:52:33.752
only way to do that is to make sure
that they're not contacted, let

00:52:33.812 --> 00:52:37.372
alone that they don't get
machine guns shot at them by the

00:52:37.392 --> 00:52:41.342
narcos, or that crazy hippie
gringos don't go down

00:52:41.392 --> 00:52:46.472
there thinking they're going to
join the coolest commune on Earth.

00:52:46.552 --> 00:52:49.872
- So how much of the land that they move

00:52:50.012 --> 00:52:53.782
about is within the 130,000
acres of rainforest you've been

00:52:53.832 --> 00:52:57.272
able to save? And how much of it is not?

00:52:57.312 --> 00:53:01.212
How much of it is in the extra 200,000
acres that you're trying to save?

00:53:01.332 --> 00:53:05.312
- Most of the rest, most of that 200,000
that we're still trying to protect

00:53:05.412 --> 00:53:09.332
is territory that is theirs. And in order-

00:53:09.372 --> 00:53:12.952
People always ask me this. They're
like, "How could you buy the

00:53:13.032 --> 00:53:16.972
Amazon?" They're like, "That doesn't make
sense." And it's like, well, I have bad

00:53:17.012 --> 00:53:20.852
news for you. Somebody already owns it and
we have to buy it from them so that they

00:53:20.892 --> 00:53:24.852
don't log it. And so these
landowners are going

00:53:24.912 --> 00:53:28.392
to sell their forest to the
logging companies because owning

00:53:28.432 --> 00:53:32.032
10,000 acres of the Amazon doesn't
help you if you're a third-generation

00:53:32.132 --> 00:53:36.082
jungle man. And now it's just something
that's up there and you live in the city,

00:53:36.112 --> 00:53:40.012
and so they're going to contract either the
narcos, the loggers, or the miners to go

00:53:40.052 --> 00:53:44.012
out there and use it, and they'll get a
little money. And when those people see

00:53:44.112 --> 00:53:47.932
these people, they will kill
them. That's for sure. And

00:53:47.992 --> 00:53:52.972
shotguns and machine guns in the end
will win, not to mention the germs.

00:53:53.052 --> 00:53:56.872
- So all the money you're trying to raise
and all the land that you're trying to

00:53:56.892 --> 00:54:00.652
save, it's all towards that:
protecting the deep jungle.

00:54:00.732 --> 00:54:04.532
So when you buy up the jungle,
you just want to let it

00:54:04.592 --> 00:54:08.472
be, let the natural ecosystem
come back to life in the cases

00:54:08.492 --> 00:54:12.352
when it was logged or just
flourish- ...if it hasn't?

00:54:12.392 --> 00:54:15.892
- Again, we're talking about
the last great jungle.

00:54:15.932 --> 00:54:19.562
I always called it the last endless
forest because this place is

00:54:19.632 --> 00:54:23.322
so incredibly remote. And then the other

00:54:23.352 --> 00:54:27.132
question I always get is, "Well, why
is this river so, so important?" And

00:54:27.812 --> 00:54:31.672
for my whole career, 20 years
in the Amazon, it's been

00:54:31.752 --> 00:54:35.532
that it's massively intact
forest. Places like the ancient

00:54:35.632 --> 00:54:39.362
forest where the trees have never
been cut, growing since the dawn of

00:54:39.412 --> 00:54:43.082
time. Thousands of species can be
on a single shihuahuaco tree, and

00:54:43.132 --> 00:54:46.952
it's Avatar on Earth. You
can see the sweat come off

00:54:46.992 --> 00:54:50.982
your skin and rain down and then drink it
out of the river, and you're part of the

00:54:51.932 --> 00:54:56.492
chemical physical reality there. It's
one of the last places that's untouched.

00:54:58.812 --> 00:55:02.772
This changed everything because
we realized that along with

00:55:02.832 --> 00:55:05.752
the butterflies and the monkeys and
the jaguars and the trees and the

00:55:05.812 --> 00:55:09.644
ecosystem—there's also
a human culture that

00:55:09.863 --> 00:55:13.823
will, in the next few
years, cease to exist, that

00:55:13.843 --> 00:55:17.683
will be exterminated if we don't
protect them. And when you look

00:55:17.763 --> 00:55:21.754
back at what happened to indigenous cultures
all over the world over the past few centuries,

00:55:21.803 --> 00:55:25.703
that they've been wiped
out, we collectively now,

00:55:25.723 --> 00:55:29.663
because we know this,
have a chance to undo all

00:55:29.703 --> 00:55:33.163
the injustices of the past
by at least doing one

00:55:33.243 --> 00:55:37.084
right, by saying these people
want one thing: to just be left

00:55:37.163 --> 00:55:41.104
alone. Imagine if we just
protected the river.

00:55:41.144 --> 00:55:44.843
And then it's not that they're
this thing that's vanishing from

00:55:44.884 --> 00:55:48.694
reality, but they get to continue living
that way. And if they want to come out and

00:55:48.763 --> 00:55:52.504
contact us, great, and if they want to continue
living like this for 10,000 years, they

00:55:52.564 --> 00:55:56.294
can. And that's what we're
working with now. It's

00:55:56.303 --> 00:56:00.124
become so much more important
than just, you know, trying to

00:56:00.144 --> 00:56:03.703
protect the environment. It's
like, no, we're trying to protect

00:56:03.743 --> 00:56:07.444
things like Yellowstone and
Yosemite and the sequoias that

00:56:07.584 --> 00:56:11.243
occur nowhere else on Earth. You
protect the things that are unique and

00:56:11.384 --> 00:56:18.584
special, the crown jewels, and in both a
biological way and an anthropocentric way,

00:56:18.644 --> 00:56:26.663
this has now become a river with global
historic significance because this story

00:56:26.683 --> 00:56:30.163
is going to play out
in the next 18 months.

00:56:30.183 --> 00:56:34.024
- You're trying to save
more and more rainforest.

00:56:34.044 --> 00:56:40.144
And the mission is clear because
there's just this deep jungle...

00:56:40.484 --> 00:56:44.183
...that's full of this incredible life.
And now we know with uncontacted tribes,

00:56:44.263 --> 00:56:49.203
there's a lot of interests that don't care
about the jungle they're pushing into...

00:56:49.323 --> 00:56:53.283
...and want to cut it down, want to destroy
it. And the mission is pretty clear.

00:56:53.323 --> 00:56:56.823
You just want this whole
territory to be preserved.

00:56:56.863 --> 00:57:00.644
- Yeah. And that's what makes it so beautiful
is that this is one of those crown jewels.

00:57:00.703 --> 00:57:04.584
This is one of those special places on earth
where it's like a time capsule for nature,

00:57:04.663 --> 00:57:11.743
for human culture, for biodiversity,
for climate services, for everything.

00:57:11.783 --> 00:57:15.703
I think people get overwhelmed when you
say, "We have to save the environment.

00:57:15.723 --> 00:57:20.544
We have to save the ocean."
This is one watershed.

00:57:20.564 --> 00:57:24.444
It's 300,000 acres, and
we're already at 130,000.

00:57:24.484 --> 00:57:28.444
We've shown we can do it. The loggers
are happy to turn into rangers.

00:57:28.484 --> 00:57:32.274
People all over the world have
become Junglekeeper supporters.

00:57:32.283 --> 00:57:36.173
We have several thousand people
that every month give us

00:57:36.203 --> 00:57:39.504
between five and a thousand dollars,
and that keeps the rangers going,

00:57:39.513 --> 00:57:43.393
that employs the local people. So it's
not just drawing a line and making a park

00:57:43.424 --> 00:57:47.134
and saying, "Everybody stay out."
It's like, no, you have the Nomoles,

00:57:47.183 --> 00:57:51.004
you have the indigenous people, you
have a future for the indigenous people

00:57:51.064 --> 00:57:58.644
where their kids don't have to worry about
eating monkeys. They can be park rangers.

00:57:58.663 --> 00:58:02.553
I get blowback when I say, "People can
even come see it through the treehouse."

00:58:02.584 --> 00:58:06.513
People go, "Oh, are you going to bring
tourists into the wildest place on earth?"

00:58:06.564 --> 00:58:09.732
And it's like, look at that
jungle. In those 300,000 acres,

00:58:09.823 --> 00:58:13.604
if you're talking about a football field,
we're talking about two blades of grass

00:58:13.663 --> 00:58:17.484
that we access so people can see
it, which makes a huge difference.

00:58:17.524 --> 00:58:23.843
The fact that we can share it with people...
I mean, the amount of people that listen,

00:58:23.904 --> 00:58:28.283
look, since the first time I
came here and spoke to you,

00:58:29.484 --> 00:58:33.303
the amount to which you've made it
possible for us to protect this place,

00:58:33.343 --> 00:58:37.124
the amount of spider monkeys,
jaguars, and giant anteaters,

00:58:37.144 --> 00:58:43.904
and those ancient millennium trees that you've
made it possible to protect is monstrous.

00:58:43.964 --> 00:58:44.803
- Thank you, brother.

00:58:45.084 --> 00:58:45.374
- No, thank you.

00:58:45.374 --> 00:58:49.004
- It's been an honor of a lifetime to be
able to watch you. I tell this to people,

00:58:49.044 --> 00:58:54.263
there's certain people I'm
glad exist in this world,

00:58:55.144 --> 00:59:00.584
because you've educated me and millions
of people about the beauty of the jungle,

00:59:01.424 --> 00:59:05.363
and how important the fight
to save the jungle is.

00:59:05.544 --> 00:59:09.464
So if you're listening to this, you
absolutely must go. Please donate,

00:59:09.524 --> 00:59:13.484
post about it, and share it with
friends: Junglekeepers.org.

00:59:13.564 --> 00:59:19.904
You're also doing a gala in New
York at the end of January.

00:59:19.964 --> 00:59:25.124
So if you can, please go and
donate to help save the jungle.

00:59:25.183 --> 00:59:28.604
- Yes, please do. And because our first

00:59:28.624 --> 00:59:34.053
conversation led to the first surge where
people realized what Junglekeepers was—

00:59:34.444 --> 00:59:38.183
and because we got this surge of support, we
were able to expand our work, protect more

00:59:38.203 --> 00:59:41.924
acres, a lot of our major donors,
a lot of our small scale donors

00:59:42.024 --> 00:59:45.964
came in because of that. So these are people
that went, "Wait, if Lex thinks it's a

00:59:46.024 --> 00:59:50.453
good idea, then we'll do it." I think based
on your trust they came in. And so...

00:59:50.453 --> 00:59:54.064
- I guess also I should
say it's not enough to

00:59:54.283 --> 00:59:58.044
speak and communicate the importance
of saving the rainforest. You

00:59:58.053 --> 01:00:01.763
actually have to have incredible people
there making it happen. And we have

01:00:01.823 --> 01:00:05.763
talked and we'll talk more about the dangers
and the complexities involved on how

01:00:05.803 --> 01:00:09.703
to navigate everything.
And one of the things, and

01:00:10.303 --> 01:00:14.203
the reason I'm really excited about what
you're doing is I just got to meet the

01:00:14.263 --> 01:00:18.153
team, and it brings a smile to my face—

01:00:18.153 --> 01:00:21.944
several of the people I know who
are extremely competent. Stefan,

01:00:21.984 --> 01:00:28.223
somebody we've talked about— Yes, he likes
to take pictures of stuff but primarily,

01:00:29.163 --> 01:00:35.703
the thing he does incredibly well is
run everything, organize everything

01:00:35.723 --> 01:00:39.584
to make sure that stuff happens and
happens quickly and efficiently,

01:00:39.644 --> 01:00:47.033
all the kind of things that are required
to make stuff like this happen in

01:00:47.064 --> 01:00:50.624
the complex environment that
the jungle operates in, the

01:00:50.903 --> 01:00:52.754
sometimes lawless environment—

01:00:52.763 --> 01:00:56.604
that the jungle operates in. So
the team is incredible, which

01:00:56.644 --> 01:01:03.584
is why when you sort of connect the money,
how does the money lead to the solution

01:01:03.624 --> 01:01:07.743
of the problem? It's the team
and the team makes it happen.

01:01:07.823 --> 01:01:10.544
- I didn't know that people
like Stefan existed.

01:01:10.852 --> 01:01:11.732
- Yeah, me neither.

01:01:11.752 --> 01:01:12.272
- You know, because I—

01:01:12.292 --> 01:01:16.452
- When I met him— He was a
beautiful, wonderful human being.

01:01:16.512 --> 01:01:21.772
- I just... I'm, you know, again, I
can use a machete to catch a fish.

01:01:21.812 --> 01:01:25.332
But his systems knowledge and
his ability... I mean, his

01:01:25.532 --> 01:01:28.832
bandwidth is the size of a
country. It has its own area code.

01:01:28.852 --> 01:01:32.792
It's... He's... You know,
just like JJ opened the door

01:01:32.832 --> 01:01:36.752
of the Amazon and gave us that local
indigenous perspective. I mean,

01:01:36.792 --> 01:01:40.592
yeah, okay, I told some stories about
it, but Stefan came in and went,

01:01:40.602 --> 01:01:44.142
"Okay, you guys have good ideas,
but you're both jungle guys."

01:01:44.142 --> 01:01:48.042
"You're not helping each other." And running
those systems and making the website

01:01:48.092 --> 01:01:51.772
and making it possible to connect the
people that care with the indigenous ranger

01:01:51.782 --> 01:01:55.592
program and make sure the rangers have shirts
and cans of tuna and that there's a person

01:01:55.612 --> 01:01:59.212
running the ranger team— I mean, these are
things I couldn't dream of organizing.

01:01:59.232 --> 01:02:06.092
I can't even organize my... I can't even
make my bed. I can't even get that far.

01:02:06.172 --> 01:02:07.552
- Caveman want fish.

01:02:07.592 --> 01:02:09.072
- Caveman want fish.

01:02:09.112 --> 01:02:12.452
- Watching you hunt for fish with a machete

01:02:13.332 --> 01:02:17.232
is one of the most awesome things
I've seen. You were literally able to

01:02:17.292 --> 01:02:19.042
catch a fish with a machete.

01:02:19.072 --> 01:02:22.132
That's what you're good at. And
Stefan is good at everything else.

01:02:22.192 --> 01:02:25.712
- Everything else. You remember the meme of
the most interesting man in the world?

01:02:25.732 --> 01:02:28.562
Where they say, "He once had an awkward
moment just to see how it felt."

01:02:28.572 --> 01:02:31.932
It's like Stefan's to-do list
doesn't exist because it's already

01:02:31.992 --> 01:02:35.352
done. It's just incredible.

01:02:35.392 --> 01:02:36.852
- Quick pause. Bathroom break.

01:02:36.912 --> 01:02:41.012
- Oh, 100%. Yes, sir.

01:02:41.112 --> 01:02:44.182
- And we're back. One thing I forgot
to ask you is about the diet

01:02:44.272 --> 01:02:51.932
of the uncontacted tribes. You mentioned
potentially monkeys and turtles,

01:02:52.032 --> 01:02:56.372
maybe eggs? So, what do we know about
what they eat? What's the source of

01:02:56.392 --> 01:02:59.032
protein? Do they eat monkeys?

01:02:59.072 --> 01:03:02.032
- Their primary sources of food would be

01:03:02.652 --> 01:03:06.452
monkeys, turtles, turtle
eggs, and small game

01:03:06.512 --> 01:03:10.392
like paca, the large rodent
that's the size of a beagle.

01:03:10.572 --> 01:03:14.542
Capybaras. Stuff they can
shoot. They don't really fish.

01:03:14.572 --> 01:03:16.682
And we know these things because

01:03:17.592 --> 01:03:21.492
our indigenous trackers and
rangers find their camps.

01:03:21.532 --> 01:03:25.352
They'll find some of those little thatch
structures they make on the beaches,

01:03:26.192 --> 01:03:29.712
and we see the bones. There'll be
tapir bones, there'll be turtle

01:03:29.792 --> 01:03:32.672
shells, which seem like
their closest thing to a

01:03:32.812 --> 01:03:36.632
bowl. The day that we
interacted with them,

01:03:36.692 --> 01:03:40.612
they did find a bowl. We saw them
walking away with it in one of

01:03:40.732 --> 01:03:44.632
the farms, and then days later
we found it destroyed. So they

01:03:44.652 --> 01:03:47.672
didn't seem like they saw
much utility in the bowl.

01:03:47.712 --> 01:03:49.972
- A temporary container.

01:03:49.982 --> 01:03:53.832
- It's temporary. They make a fire.
They must be amazing at making fire.

01:03:53.852 --> 01:03:55.992
I don't know how they do it out there.

01:03:56.032 --> 01:03:59.032
- It's very difficult
because everything is wet.

01:03:59.152 --> 01:04:02.432
- I don't know how they do it. And
I'm a really good firestarter.

01:04:02.472 --> 01:04:03.452
- And it's tough in the jungle.

01:04:03.512 --> 01:04:09.572
- It's almost impossible most of the year
because everything is wet to its core.

01:04:09.612 --> 01:04:11.552
- So you think they cook the meat?

01:04:11.932 --> 01:04:15.922
- They have to be cooking their
meat from a parasite standpoint,

01:04:15.972 --> 01:04:16.792
...everything. We know that—

01:04:16.802 --> 01:04:20.552
...they're cooking their meat. We
see it. You know, there's not a lot

01:04:20.592 --> 01:04:24.412
of excess berries. Things
like berries and nuts and

01:04:24.512 --> 01:04:26.212
fruits, that the monkeys
and the birds are—

01:04:26.222 --> 01:04:29.492
...and the bats are getting to those first.
I mean, that's what fruit does, right?

01:04:29.532 --> 01:04:33.372
A tomato is green until
its seeds are mature,

01:04:33.412 --> 01:04:37.392
then it turns red to advertise,
"Eat me," so that you eat it and

01:04:37.412 --> 01:04:41.172
your gut transports that somewhere
else. It gets free transportation.

01:04:41.192 --> 01:04:45.432
In the jungle, that happens so quick
that we're never getting produce.

01:04:45.492 --> 01:04:49.772
- In the book, you have a picture of
a native girl on the Los Piedras...

01:04:49.792 --> 01:04:52.812
...having monkey for lunch.

01:04:52.872 --> 01:04:53.652
- Yes.

01:04:53.792 --> 01:05:01.272
- It looks really strange when you
have— The monkey kind of looks—

01:05:02.512 --> 01:05:08.432
It looks a little bit like cannibalism
because it looks like a small human.

01:05:08.472 --> 01:05:13.572
I don't know what it is about
monkeys. There's a human—

01:05:13.592 --> 01:05:17.522
...element to them. In their eyes, in

01:05:17.552 --> 01:05:21.752
their form factor, but even in the
warmth they bring to the interaction.

01:05:22.492 --> 01:05:27.492
- Yeah, I was babysitting her. She
was six at the time, Dira, and

01:05:28.752 --> 01:05:32.392
her parents went out and we were left at
camp. They said, "Keep an eye on her.

01:05:32.432 --> 01:05:36.232
Make sure nothing eats her." She
was like, "Hey, I want lunch."

01:05:36.272 --> 01:05:39.112
I said, "Great, what is there?" And
she pulls out this monkey head.

01:05:39.972 --> 01:05:43.792
She was like, "It's ready," and
she starts pulling at the ear.

01:05:43.832 --> 01:05:47.162
She's like, "Can you help me?" So I
pulled off the ear with my teeth—

01:05:47.212 --> 01:05:51.292
...and then I gave it to her. We just
shared this monkey head back and forth.

01:05:51.312 --> 01:05:54.312
We're sitting there and I took a few
pictures of her as she's eating.

01:05:54.352 --> 01:05:58.332
I have this video where I go, "What's
your favorite food?" She said, "Monkey."

01:05:58.342 --> 01:06:03.252
I said, "Not cake?" And
she was like, "Monkey."

01:06:03.272 --> 01:06:04.922
She was pulling its lips
off and, like you said—

01:06:04.922 --> 01:06:09.922
...you see the teeth and the eyes.
It's sort of grilled in static agony.

01:06:09.972 --> 01:06:12.432
It looks like a tortured human,
and she was just enjoying it.

01:06:12.452 --> 01:06:19.482
- Let me look it up on Perplexity.
How many people in the world eat—

01:06:19.492 --> 01:06:23.892
monkey? Does it taste good?

01:06:24.032 --> 01:06:31.452
- If it were prepared right, it would taste
good, but they just throw it over the fire.

01:06:31.472 --> 01:06:33.952
And even if you took a perfectly good chicken
and did that, it wouldn't taste great.

01:06:33.962 --> 01:06:37.872
- There's no reliable global count of
how many people eat monkey meat,

01:06:37.912 --> 01:06:41.532
but available data suggests many millions
regularly or occasionally consume

01:06:41.552 --> 01:06:45.592
primate bushmeat—

01:06:45.712 --> 01:06:49.612
...especially in parts of Africa, Latin
America and Asia. I mean, she looks

01:06:49.672 --> 01:06:53.292
like that is her favorite meal— is monkey.

01:06:53.352 --> 01:06:55.052
- Yeah, we had a great time.

01:06:55.072 --> 01:06:56.512
- Who are we to judge?

01:06:56.552 --> 01:07:02.892
- Who are we to judge? I mean, have a tuna
sandwich or a monkey face, whatever.

01:07:02.992 --> 01:07:05.842
- She's loving it. That's awesome.
That's a good picture there.

01:07:05.842 --> 01:07:06.632
- And she's adorable.

01:07:06.672 --> 01:07:10.542
- Yeah. Now that some time has
passed, when you look back at

01:07:10.592 --> 01:07:14.480
that encounter, which I
really do think is historic,

01:07:14.700 --> 01:07:19.680
with the uncontacted tribe, what do you
think about? What lingers with you?

01:07:19.740 --> 01:07:23.339
- Honestly, I'm still processing it. I'll
still find myself just staring off, sort of

01:07:23.399 --> 01:07:30.190
remembering it or looking at
the footage. But it felt like

01:07:31.740 --> 01:07:35.700
the voice of the jungle was
speaking. You know, these

01:07:35.759 --> 01:07:39.620
people are... there's that separation

01:07:39.640 --> 01:07:43.500
between humans and nature where we go,
"We have to protect nature." You know?

01:07:43.560 --> 01:07:47.440
It's like explaining what water is to
a fish. We're part of it. We depend

01:07:47.500 --> 01:07:51.350
on it. And these are people that
depend on it 100%. And as we sit

01:07:51.379 --> 01:07:56.799
here surrounded by technology,
concrete and civilization, they're

01:07:57.640 --> 01:08:01.359
still out there right now. And the

01:08:01.399 --> 01:08:05.080
fact that we've been trying to
protect their home without even

01:08:05.200 --> 01:08:07.680
really knowing that they were in
it because they're so elusive,

01:08:09.299 --> 01:08:13.109
it gives you perspective on where we
came from and how far we've come.

01:08:14.399 --> 01:08:18.319
You know, I look at simple
things. You board an

01:08:18.380 --> 01:08:22.139
airplane or you take a picture
and you go, "This is a miracle."

01:08:22.220 --> 01:08:25.760
And I think having that perspective of
having interacted with them where you

01:08:25.800 --> 01:08:32.269
go, "How much work does
it take to make this?"

01:08:32.340 --> 01:08:35.700
If you and I were standing in the jungle
and somebody said, "You have to make this,"

01:08:35.779 --> 01:08:39.700
how many years before we
came up with this? How

01:08:39.740 --> 01:08:43.680
many rubber trees, and where would we get
the metal, and what would we use as dye?

01:08:43.700 --> 01:08:47.580
How do we make the spring mechanism
and figure out how to make it rotate?

01:08:47.639 --> 01:08:51.220
I don't know. And it's like they are
working with the bare essentials.

01:08:51.279 --> 01:08:55.240
And so it's an interesting reference point
to start at in terms of how incredibly

01:08:55.279 --> 01:08:59.120
at in terms of how incredibly

01:08:59.180 --> 01:09:02.880
privileged we are. You know,
the other thing is we have

01:09:03.000 --> 01:09:06.920
written text—so many different types
of text. We have code, and we have

01:09:06.979 --> 01:09:10.779
language, and we have music, and we can
communicate in all these different ways.

01:09:10.859 --> 01:09:18.340
And they have spoken word. They have oral
tradition, and that's it. And so they're

01:09:18.420 --> 01:09:22.399
operating the way our
ancestors did through the

01:09:22.438 --> 01:09:27.720
power of what operated and
is persisting in modern

01:09:27.779 --> 01:09:31.740
And so I think, for me, I
come back to the world and

01:09:31.800 --> 01:09:38.120
it moves very fast when I see
it because I'm still stuck on,

01:09:38.160 --> 01:09:41.340
you know, whether or not me and
you can drink out of that puddle.

01:09:41.420 --> 01:09:42.729
Thinking about that.

01:09:42.729 --> 01:09:43.800
- The big questions of life.

01:09:43.840 --> 01:09:45.559
- The big questions of life.

01:09:45.620 --> 01:09:49.540
- Yeah. I mean, you're right from the
perspective of the uncontacted tribe.

01:09:51.059 --> 01:09:55.340
Going from the technological
world to the jungle, you realize

01:09:56.260 --> 01:10:00.019
the majesty, the magic of
the biological system that

01:10:00.099 --> 01:10:03.440
is the jungle, that is
nature. But from their

01:10:03.480 --> 01:10:06.920
perspective, also there is
a majesty and magic to the

01:10:06.960 --> 01:10:10.250
technological world. The human-created

01:10:11.480 --> 01:10:15.639
technological world of
the pen and the computer,

01:10:15.900 --> 01:10:20.220
and the light bulb, that too
is magical. So sometimes we

01:10:20.240 --> 01:10:20.250
- Absolutely

01:10:20.250 --> 01:10:23.840
- don't give enough credit to both:

01:10:25.180 --> 01:10:28.980
the magic of the technological world, all
the incredible things humans have been

01:10:29.040 --> 01:10:34.460
able to build, and the
magic of the natural world.

01:10:34.500 --> 01:10:40.180
- I mean, what we've been able to achieve,
I think you and I and people that spend

01:10:41.260 --> 01:10:45.019
large amounts of time in the wilderness,
especially somewhere as remote and fundamental

01:10:45.099 --> 01:10:48.980
as the Western Amazon, have
a different perspective

01:10:49.040 --> 01:10:51.449
on it. Because I think that when
you're born in it, you don't

01:10:51.449 --> 01:10:56.880
necessarily have the framework to
appreciate how far we've come.

01:10:57.000 --> 01:11:00.910
You go, "Yeah, I got on the train
today. I checked my phone. I FaceTimed

01:11:01.019 --> 01:11:04.920
my mom," and you're like, "This is
all normal." And it's like we found

01:11:05.000 --> 01:11:06.000
a way to take

01:11:07.120 --> 01:11:10.720
things out of the ground and mix them
together into magic devices that can do

01:11:10.729 --> 01:11:14.019
anything. And it's mind-blowing.

01:11:14.059 --> 01:11:18.040
- There's a deep optimism to that. You write in
the book, which I really like, I think somewhere

01:11:18.080 --> 01:11:21.820
in the beginning, quote, "Given
all the death and destruction I've

01:11:21.860 --> 01:11:25.660
witnessed, it would be easy to
slip into the popular anti-human

01:11:25.760 --> 01:11:29.320
narrative that we are
a plague on the planet

01:11:29.840 --> 01:11:33.759
and there's nothing that can be done, but
my career in conservation has given me a

01:11:33.840 --> 01:11:37.460
glimpse into an alternate
narrative. I've met people who are

01:11:37.500 --> 01:11:41.410
proving more and more that
something can be done.

01:11:41.440 --> 01:11:45.410
I'm talking about real heroes, people who
have dedicated their lives to redeeming

01:11:45.420 --> 01:11:48.680
the evil that is capable of
being waged by the human

01:11:48.720 --> 01:11:51.550
soul, people who are guarding
the flame amidst the

01:11:51.700 --> 01:11:58.920
storm, proving every day what so many have
forgotten. There is still hope." And that

01:11:58.940 --> 01:12:03.180
speaks against the cynicism and apathy,

01:12:04.000 --> 01:12:07.780
and the view that humans are
a destructive force in the

01:12:07.840 --> 01:12:13.950
world. That speaks to the fact that
humans, with all the technological

01:12:14.780 --> 01:12:16.970
elements that we have created,
can actually do a lot of

01:12:17.000 --> 01:12:24.849
good. I wrote in my notes here a quote
from the great Jane Goodall: "The

01:12:24.920 --> 01:12:28.440
greatest danger to our
future is apathy." So

01:12:28.519 --> 01:12:32.450
caring about the world, having optimism
for the world, having a hope for the

01:12:32.500 --> 01:12:40.740
world is the way to help have an impact,
help save it. But on that, I have

01:12:40.820 --> 01:12:43.680
to ask you about Jane. She
passed away on October

01:12:43.880 --> 01:12:47.780
1st. Some humans in this
human civilization of

01:12:47.860 --> 01:12:51.450
ours can open our eyes
to the beauty of the

01:12:51.500 --> 01:12:58.360
world, and she is one of the best of them.
And she's had an impact on your life.

01:12:59.440 --> 01:13:02.420
Maybe can you speak to the
impact that she's had?

01:13:03.180 --> 01:13:07.030
- I mean, when I grew up,
you know, my parents...

01:13:07.059 --> 01:13:10.960
Being dyslexic, I couldn't read for
a very long time. And so my parents

01:13:11.120 --> 01:13:15.110
read to us every night, which
was amazing considering

01:13:15.140 --> 01:13:19.100
how hard they were working. But they'd find the
time to give us an hour of reading every night,

01:13:19.140 --> 01:13:22.190
whether it was Lord of the Rings or
Sherlock Holmes or Jane Goodall. And

01:13:23.100 --> 01:13:26.620
so I grew up with Jane
being this figurehead of

01:13:26.700 --> 01:13:30.200
conservation and of adventure
and sort of a living

01:13:30.760 --> 01:13:34.590
historical figure, this
legendary person. And so then

01:13:34.660 --> 01:13:37.960
one time, right around the time that
I'd been going to the jungle for a few

01:13:38.000 --> 01:13:41.800
years, I got to go see Jane
speak, I think it was at

01:13:41.880 --> 01:13:45.680
NYU. And, you know, sitting in the crowd,

01:13:45.740 --> 01:13:49.300
watched her, completely amazed.
And I had, at the time, my

01:13:49.340 --> 01:13:53.160
cousins had been telling me that I should write
down my stories, the stories of taking care of an

01:13:53.180 --> 01:13:56.500
anteater and stories of catching anacondas.
And they're like, "Write, you know?

01:13:56.540 --> 01:14:00.300
These are such good stories." And so
I'd been writing them down and I just

01:14:00.340 --> 01:14:07.640
remember after the talk, she did
at least an hour on stage and then

01:14:07.700 --> 01:14:12.320
hundreds of people lined up, and

01:14:13.380 --> 01:14:17.140
she sat there and each of
those people wants a moment

01:14:17.199 --> 01:14:21.040
with this legend. And so she has to take a
picture, shake their hand, they say, "You mean so

01:14:21.080 --> 01:14:25.040
much to me." She says, "Thank you." And then
they move on and they say, "We'll send you

01:14:25.080 --> 01:14:29.020
the picture." "Okay, great." So then I got
my moment and we waited in line and I gave

01:14:29.040 --> 01:14:32.720
her this manila envelope with two
chapters in it. And one chapter

01:14:32.780 --> 01:14:36.550
was "Lulu the Giant Anteater" for Mother
of God, and the other chapter was me,

01:14:36.580 --> 01:14:40.570
JJ and Pico out on the river catching
anacondas, and just talking about how

01:14:40.620 --> 01:14:44.460
amazing the jungle was. And I said, "I'd
love it if you could endorse my book that

01:14:44.480 --> 01:14:48.440
doesn't exist yet." And I felt like
such a loser doing that. And I felt so

01:14:48.580 --> 01:14:52.570
stupid because I feel like everyone was
probably asking something of her, and I,

01:14:52.600 --> 01:14:56.540
you know, it's incredibly draining
to talk to that many people, even if

01:14:56.600 --> 01:15:00.580
it is for a good reason. And
48 hours later, she got back

01:15:00.630 --> 01:15:04.300
and she said, "You know, this
is incredible. I would love

01:15:04.460 --> 01:15:07.540
to write a recommendation for
your book as soon as you find a

01:15:07.580 --> 01:15:10.180
publisher." And what
happened with that is that

01:15:11.640 --> 01:15:15.440
Jane—the way I think of it
is, you know, she waved her

01:15:15.480 --> 01:15:19.060
very powerful magical wand in
my direction, and she had the

01:15:19.100 --> 01:15:22.719
incredible compassion and presence to

01:15:22.880 --> 01:15:26.720
actually—I mean, after talking to that many
people and being on the road 300 days a year

01:15:26.760 --> 01:15:32.120
and being Jane Goodall, this living
legend scientist, to actually

01:15:33.340 --> 01:15:37.240
do something so mundane as look
at some kid's writing. And

01:15:37.320 --> 01:15:41.300
of course, when I went to publishers, they
said, "Jane who? Who said that they would

01:15:41.440 --> 01:15:45.030
endorse your book?" Because
everyone had said no. Every

01:15:45.120 --> 01:15:49.080
publisher in New York had already said no.
And then after that, HarperCollins took

01:15:49.120 --> 01:15:52.320
me on and they said, "Well, if Jane Goodall thinks
it's a good idea, then we think it's a good

01:15:52.380 --> 01:15:59.180
idea." And it became Mother of God and
then because of that, Jungle Keepers,

01:15:59.220 --> 01:16:03.100
Dax, everything else stemmed
from that. So had Jane

01:16:03.140 --> 01:16:06.840
not been the legend that she
is truly in every moment,

01:16:07.500 --> 01:16:10.920
my whole career would never have happened,
which also means that those thousands

01:16:11.020 --> 01:16:14.940
of heartbeats and thousands of acres in the
Amazon wouldn't be protected because we

01:16:14.980 --> 01:16:17.080
never would've started Jungle Keepers.

01:16:17.100 --> 01:16:22.120
- And she did that not because you're
special; she did that to everybody.

01:16:22.140 --> 01:16:27.740
And now just imagine the scale, the
impact she's had because of that.

01:16:27.780 --> 01:16:31.120
And guess what? You have a bit
of that responsibility now as

01:16:31.180 --> 01:16:34.670
well. There's young people that
walk up to you in that way,

01:16:35.160 --> 01:16:38.280
and you have that responsibility
of seeing them, of giving them a

01:16:38.360 --> 01:16:45.340
chance, of seeing the potential in every
single human being that walks up to you.

01:16:45.350 --> 01:16:49.340
- It definitely... I would say that
with Jane, we could do four hours

01:16:49.380 --> 01:16:53.160
on just Jane: what she did for
humanity, for science, for

01:16:53.220 --> 01:16:56.680
women, for wildlife, the amount
of other people that she

01:16:56.700 --> 01:16:58.490
inspired and gave careers to,

01:16:59.380 --> 01:17:03.200
everything she did for me.
But to me, that presence of

01:17:03.280 --> 01:17:07.160
mind when you reach that level, to not be
worried about your own travel and your own

01:17:07.740 --> 01:17:11.380
schedule and busy with getting
some rest—and that she actually

01:17:11.480 --> 01:17:15.310
looked at it—has informed
how I operate. And

01:17:15.340 --> 01:17:19.110
indeed like you say, at this point,
as strange as it is, people will

01:17:19.160 --> 01:17:23.030
stop me on the street and say,
"Hey, I watch your videos every

01:17:23.120 --> 01:17:27.020
night with my kids." Or someone
will say, "How do I get your

01:17:27.060 --> 01:17:30.760
job? I've been watching you for years
and I'd love to help conservation."

01:17:31.500 --> 01:17:35.440
So it's made it so that I
follow her example where

01:17:35.460 --> 01:17:38.260
it's like you stop what
you're doing and you

01:17:39.060 --> 01:17:42.970
pay attention. Because you don't know, that
might be the next kid that's out there saving

01:17:43.020 --> 01:17:46.620
a river, or the next person that makes an
innovation that makes it possible to clean rivers,

01:17:46.680 --> 01:17:49.740
or whatever it is,
whatever their dream is.

01:17:49.880 --> 01:17:53.780
Jane was in the hope business.
She always said it: you know,

01:17:53.820 --> 01:17:56.320
that not losing hope was key to

01:17:57.200 --> 01:18:01.000
staying in the fight. And
that we live at a time when,

01:18:03.340 --> 01:18:07.200
apathy is a poison peddled
by the darkness. It's—

01:18:07.220 --> 01:18:10.460
they're trying to make you feel
disoriented, apathetic, and

01:18:10.620 --> 01:18:14.340
scared. And fighting back
against that and having

01:18:14.440 --> 01:18:16.560
conviction and passion and fire and hope

01:18:17.920 --> 01:18:21.660
are the only way that we're gonna fight that. She
understood that and spent her whole life spreading

01:18:21.720 --> 01:18:25.520
it, guarding the flame
against the storm, and

01:18:25.640 --> 01:18:30.620
tipping her candle to others to light
them. I mean, that was her whole thing.

01:18:30.640 --> 01:18:37.730
- What advice would you give to young people
on how to do that? Those young Pauls sitting

01:18:37.740 --> 01:18:41.040
there—and your life story
is just incredible in that

01:18:41.100 --> 01:18:44.800
way. You've taken a leap into adventure,

01:18:45.380 --> 01:18:49.060
into the unknown. What would
you recommend they do?

01:18:49.140 --> 01:18:53.080
- I think the thing that I
try to communicate to them—

01:18:53.120 --> 01:18:56.700
and again, my inbox is filled with people.
"I'm from Finland. I'm from Spain.

01:18:56.740 --> 01:19:00.640
I'm from Georgia." People saying, "How
do I get your job? How do I get out

01:19:00.680 --> 01:19:04.340
there and do it?" And it
really is just that: you

01:19:04.460 --> 01:19:08.300
throw yourself headfirst into
adventure. You just do it.

01:19:08.340 --> 01:19:12.260
I remember hearing people say,
"You know, if I can do it,

01:19:12.300 --> 01:19:15.760
you can do it." And I remember how hollow that
sounds 'cause I'm like, "Yeah, you're on a

01:19:16.320 --> 01:19:20.180
talk show or you just wrote a
book..." You know, these titans

01:19:20.240 --> 01:19:24.060
of their industries and innovators
saying, "Oh, if I can do it,

01:19:24.080 --> 01:19:27.800
anybody can do it." But now that
we're protecting all this rainforest,

01:19:27.900 --> 01:19:31.856
and that I've lived with
the animals and met

01:19:31.896 --> 01:19:35.876
the tribes, and it's becoming
this global movement.

01:19:35.996 --> 01:19:39.716
You know, I didn't have a PhD.
There's that quote that someone

01:19:39.776 --> 01:19:43.536
less qualified than you is living
your dream life and has your dream

01:19:43.636 --> 01:19:47.556
job right now, and I am the poster
child for that because I went there

01:19:47.596 --> 01:19:51.316
when I failed out of high school and
started taking unmatriculated college

01:19:51.396 --> 01:19:55.316
classes and going to the jungle with my
friend JJ and just doing it for the sheer

01:19:55.516 --> 01:19:59.486
love of it for years,
almost a decade before

01:19:59.556 --> 01:20:03.446
anything surfaced. And the
other thing is there's not

01:20:03.476 --> 01:20:07.245
even a path. There was no path
ahead of us. There was no,

01:20:07.245 --> 01:20:11.205
"Okay, you go to school. You get trained in this,
and you're gonna become a this." I went there and it

01:20:11.236 --> 01:20:14.696
was like, "You're never gonna be a conservation
biologist 'cause you don't have the grades.

01:20:14.736 --> 01:20:17.866
You don't have a PhD. You don't
have family money. You're not

01:20:17.896 --> 01:20:21.446
gonna be able to protect rainforests."
So I said, "All right, well then,

01:20:21.476 --> 01:20:25.156
selfishly, I just wanna see it." And
then I ended up getting trained by the

01:20:25.196 --> 01:20:28.896
indigenous people, and
like what happens so many

01:20:28.956 --> 01:20:32.856
times—you could use a restaurant
example as the best one,

01:20:32.896 --> 01:20:36.056
where you might start washing
dishes, but at least you're in the

01:20:36.096 --> 01:20:40.086
restaurant, you know? And then at some
point, the manager's gonna need you to help

01:20:40.116 --> 01:20:44.046
with restocking and so on.
And after a few years, you're

01:20:44.076 --> 01:20:48.056
gonna be helping the new guy, and after
a few years you might end up being

01:20:48.096 --> 01:20:51.636
the manager, and at some point you might
end up starting your own restaurant.

01:20:51.656 --> 01:20:55.596
That's the only way to do that. You
can't just search it on a computer.

01:20:55.636 --> 01:20:58.596
You have to go sweat and bleed and do it.

01:20:58.616 --> 01:21:02.476
- And that said, especially if you
fall in love with the journey,

01:21:02.596 --> 01:21:06.496
the path you take is full of
difficult periods. I think you

01:21:06.636 --> 01:21:10.206
said somewhere this just
seems to be the nature of it.

01:21:11.276 --> 01:21:14.596
That there's going to be pain and
suffering along the way. You have

01:21:14.606 --> 01:21:16.706
a really nice post...

01:21:16.706 --> 01:21:23.116
...that I recommend people watch
about just this. When people ask for

01:21:23.176 --> 01:21:27.126
advice: that the hardship, the suffering—

01:21:27.126 --> 01:21:30.986
—and I've seen how much you
care. When I've seen you,

01:21:31.056 --> 01:21:38.076
just in your face, when you see a tree
being cut down or you see the fires,

01:21:39.375 --> 01:21:42.296
there's real pain there in
your heart and you have to

01:21:43.456 --> 01:21:47.385
carry that. And so the
post is, "How honest can

01:21:47.516 --> 01:21:51.476
I be? What do I tell these
kids who message me asking how

01:21:51.496 --> 01:21:55.416
they can do what I do? It's not
David versus Goliath. There's

01:21:55.456 --> 01:21:59.445
no sword or sling that can hold back
a dragon this big. You're going

01:21:59.476 --> 01:22:03.296
against the current of global
economic entropy and human apathy.

01:22:03.356 --> 01:22:06.636
Swimming against the current
is tiring, a great way to

01:22:06.656 --> 01:22:14.216
drown. Every day we don't win, we lose,
and when we do, worlds burn. The more you

01:22:14.256 --> 01:22:17.966
know, the more it bleeds. The
heartbeats all stop when the flames

01:22:17.996 --> 01:22:21.376
come through. Constellations
of species turn to

01:22:21.416 --> 01:22:25.396
ghosts, and we're the only
ones saving them. Cupped

01:22:25.496 --> 01:22:28.676
our hands around a candle
in the howling darkness."

01:22:29.676 --> 01:22:33.496
And people want to be inspired.
Keep that social media going,

01:22:33.616 --> 01:22:36.536
keep it up. You're doing
great. They want to know we're

01:22:36.596 --> 01:22:40.546
winning, and we've done a lot
of winning, but not right

01:22:40.636 --> 01:22:44.156
now. We're getting slaughtered.
We're at that part of the

01:22:44.236 --> 01:22:47.896
story. We're almost at the
end game. We can think

01:22:47.906 --> 01:22:51.746
positively, as positively
as we want. Thoughts and

01:22:51.836 --> 01:22:55.385
prayers won't stop a chainsaw,
and the motor that's carrying us

01:22:55.456 --> 01:22:59.316
against the current towards the
miraculous goal only works when there's

01:22:59.356 --> 01:23:06.176
gasoline in it. As soon as that stops,
we drown. We drown. We can take the

01:23:06.316 --> 01:23:10.296
warm light from all of those
who help and not let it bother

01:23:10.356 --> 01:23:14.216
us that there are people who could buy
a planet, claiming to care. At some

01:23:14.256 --> 01:23:17.796
point you realize what's
really happening."

01:23:17.806 --> 01:23:21.376
"As a kid you'd rather be
Aragorn. You don't want to

01:23:21.476 --> 01:23:25.076
actually carry the ring, not when
you learn what it's going to

01:23:25.136 --> 01:23:28.976
cost, even if you make
it. How can you explain

01:23:29.016 --> 01:23:32.466
to Sam why you can't get
on the boats? Whatever it

01:23:32.516 --> 01:23:36.236
takes, whatever it takes.
It's that time of year

01:23:36.276 --> 01:23:40.176
again. Here come the flames.
Whatever it takes, it's

01:23:40.216 --> 01:23:44.096
coming." And people should watch the
video that goes along with this. But that

01:23:44.196 --> 01:23:49.406
speaks to the pain, the difficulty,
the challenge, the suffering involved—

01:23:49.556 --> 01:23:51.656
when you're faced with the possibility of

01:23:51.696 --> 01:23:57.056
destruction. And that's the other side of
the sword of caring for something deeply.

01:23:57.096 --> 01:24:00.896
- Yeah, we've watched a lot of
forest burn. We've pulled a lot of

01:24:00.996 --> 01:24:04.956
animals out of the flames.
Yeah, I wrote that at a

01:24:04.996 --> 01:24:08.936
time where we were just getting
hammered. Funding wasn't

01:24:08.986 --> 01:24:12.696
coming in. There were miners. It was
just months and months out in the jungle

01:24:12.776 --> 01:24:16.656
alone, and yeah, that— it's

01:24:16.836 --> 01:24:20.376
a Thom Yorke track that I'd just been
listening to again and again, and it was so

01:24:20.476 --> 01:24:27.116
low. There was then a huge
new invasion where they just—

01:24:28.176 --> 01:24:33.166
burned the whole side of the river. And
you know, it's never going to come back.

01:24:34.436 --> 01:24:38.116
And it's part of the forest that I loved,
and I knew the animals there and it's,

01:24:38.236 --> 01:24:42.036
it's gone. And so we have
to live through that on a

01:24:43.416 --> 01:24:46.376
weekly basis, at least
a day-to-day basis. And

01:24:47.856 --> 01:24:50.296
when you take on responsibility
for something like this, you—

01:24:51.836 --> 01:24:52.856
you go to sleep thinking,

01:24:54.656 --> 01:24:58.636
"If we don't do it then worlds burn. If
we don't save it, then..." Every time you

01:24:58.676 --> 01:25:02.016
said the sadness that surrounds
a happy moment— well, it's

01:25:02.076 --> 01:25:06.026
like, how am I supposed to go to a
party and talk with people about

01:25:06.036 --> 01:25:10.576
anything, or how am I supposed
to go to sleep when if we don't

01:25:12.096 --> 01:25:16.056
succeed at what we're trying to do,
if we don't outrace the chainsaws and

01:25:16.096 --> 01:25:20.076
the roads, then those trees die,
those millennium trees, and

01:25:20.136 --> 01:25:23.846
we're the only ones out there protecting
them. When you see that black scorched

01:25:23.916 --> 01:25:31.548
earth with nothing left, it's just ashes
on the ground and the cacophony of life is

01:25:31.558 --> 01:25:38.468
silenced, and it's just this horrible,
violent silence. It makes you sick. And so,

01:25:38.508 --> 01:25:41.748
yeah, there's a lot of weight
that comes with that where

01:25:43.808 --> 01:25:47.668
we're not theoretically doing

01:25:47.728 --> 01:25:51.908
something. We're black and
white, practically doing it.

01:25:51.948 --> 01:25:55.508
- So that's the other side of
the advice to young people.

01:25:55.628 --> 01:25:56.538
- Oh, yeah.

01:25:56.768 --> 01:25:58.068
- It's not gonna be easy.

01:25:58.128 --> 01:26:02.047
- No. When they say, "How do I get
your job?" it's like, "Well, you

01:26:02.088 --> 01:26:05.928
don't want my job. You don't want the botflies,
and you don't want the dengue, and you

01:26:05.968 --> 01:26:09.848
don't want—don't even
inquire what a normal life

01:26:09.868 --> 01:26:12.518
looks like." I lived out
of a backpack for 20

01:26:12.728 --> 01:26:16.658
years. You know how many monkey
faces I had to eat because

01:26:16.668 --> 01:26:19.598
there was no other food? Like, seriously.

01:26:20.448 --> 01:26:24.308
Just that shot, being alone on
the boat in the river and how

01:26:24.328 --> 01:26:28.248
many days the motor didn't work. And you sleep
out there, and you get rained on because

01:26:28.268 --> 01:26:32.228
you don't have any protection, and you have
some leaves over your face. And then you go

01:26:32.268 --> 01:26:36.218
home, and everyone's got a job, and everyone's
got kids, and everyone's happy. And they're like,

01:26:36.218 --> 01:26:39.518
"What are you doing down there?"
"I'm trying to save the rainforest."

01:26:40.368 --> 01:26:44.868
They're like, "Sure." And now
we're at this point where,

01:26:45.728 --> 01:26:49.628
I've cared a whole lot for a long
time. We've had rises, and then

01:26:49.648 --> 01:26:53.548
we've had falls, and we've had wins, and then
we've had failures. And the last few years,

01:26:53.568 --> 01:26:57.388
we've had this rolling
success of people finding out

01:26:57.428 --> 01:27:01.348
about our work and coming in. And we start
to go, "Wow, if we protected 130,000 acres,

01:27:01.408 --> 01:27:05.248
we might actually be able to do
this." And so, there's that moment in

01:27:05.468 --> 01:27:08.908
300 where they show Leonidas, and they
say, "Even the king allows himself

01:27:08.968 --> 01:27:13.588
a moment of hope that this might be
okay," right before they get slaughtered.

01:27:13.668 --> 01:27:18.968
And someone very dear to me
recently said, "In celebration

01:27:19.028 --> 01:27:23.018
of where we've gotten to, that if it happened
in any harder of a way, it would have

01:27:23.128 --> 01:27:26.918
actually killed you. And if it
had happened in an easier way, it

01:27:26.948 --> 01:27:28.968
wouldn't have been so divine."

01:27:30.908 --> 01:27:34.308
And that slapped me in the face because
it was like, "Man, it has been so

01:27:34.348 --> 01:27:41.138
hard, but look where we are.
We might actually do this."

01:27:41.188 --> 01:27:48.768
- It just has to be that way. Speaking of
which, another complexity in all of this,

01:27:49.828 --> 01:27:51.508
you write about in the
afterword of the book,

01:27:53.188 --> 01:28:00.468
about the narco-traffickers that have
moved into the river basin. They are not

01:28:01.428 --> 01:28:05.028
the loggers that we've spoken
about anymore. They're

01:28:05.248 --> 01:28:11.248
growing coca for cocaine, and
they're building airstrips. So

01:28:12.048 --> 01:28:13.597
tell me how this came to be.

01:28:14.348 --> 01:28:18.068
- Like you said, the loggers... our
whole life on this river, when

01:28:18.128 --> 01:28:21.988
loggers come in, JJ and I would walk
up to them and say, "Hey, what's up?"

01:28:22.068 --> 01:28:25.888
Sit down with them and have a
beer or share a meal and talk to

01:28:25.948 --> 01:28:29.838
them and ask who their father was and if we
know them and then hire them. And they're

01:28:29.868 --> 01:28:32.918
friendly.

01:28:32.918 --> 01:28:38.238
- They are, in a way, brothers,
JJ. They're the same.

01:28:38.248 --> 01:28:42.188
- They come from the same people. They're
simple local people. They're not evil.

01:28:42.208 --> 01:28:45.968
They're just people who usually have a
kid and a wife, and they're looking for

01:28:46.008 --> 01:28:48.848
work. And so they work with the
chainsaw because that's what they

01:28:48.908 --> 01:28:56.008
know. And they work for, you know, $30
a day, if that, in very challenging,

01:28:56.068 --> 01:28:59.848
harsh environments. And so when we see
clearings, I would always go with the drone

01:28:59.888 --> 01:29:03.728
and fly it over clearings. We'd get some
intel, and then we'd go bring that to the

01:29:03.748 --> 01:29:07.598
police. And the police, you know...
Jungle Keepers supports the

01:29:07.648 --> 01:29:09.308
police at this point because the Peruvian

01:29:10.628 --> 01:29:14.368
government has a hard time
with resources, trying to

01:29:15.168 --> 01:29:17.967
manage Amazonia. And when
you're three days from

01:29:18.008 --> 01:29:21.868
civilization, getting cops out there is not
the easiest thing. So sometimes we'll lend

01:29:21.928 --> 01:29:29.258
boats or gasoline or logistical support.
There was a moment in March, several hours

01:29:29.328 --> 01:29:33.288
upriver from, you know, home
base. And I'm with JJ on

01:29:33.308 --> 01:29:37.138
the boat, and I fly the drone, and there's this
big new clearing, and I flew the drone over, and

01:29:37.168 --> 01:29:41.028
we lower the drone. And a few times, I've had
people come out and wave at the drone or say

01:29:41.068 --> 01:29:43.208
like, "Get away." And

01:29:44.368 --> 01:29:48.197
we're out in the middle of the river just sort
of idling, staying in one place, and I lower the

01:29:48.268 --> 01:29:52.198
drone. And I see the, these little huts, and
we're saying, "Okay, this is a big clearing."

01:29:52.228 --> 01:29:56.058
I'm snapping images, snapping images. There
are people on the boat with us, these

01:29:56.068 --> 01:29:58.898
visitors who had flown
in, and I have my local

01:29:58.948 --> 01:30:02.608
team, and all of a sudden,
people come running out of the

01:30:02.668 --> 01:30:06.588
houses. And they run straight to their
boats, and we're already above where

01:30:06.628 --> 01:30:10.468
their boat is. So home is in
downriver direction. They get in

01:30:10.488 --> 01:30:11.908
their boats and start chasing us,

01:30:13.068 --> 01:30:16.808
and we start driving, and we're
going at full speed. We have a 60

01:30:16.868 --> 01:30:20.728
horsepower. They had a 40, and we're
driving up these... We're just

01:30:20.748 --> 01:30:24.628
doing this chase now, and
our guests, who are gonna

01:30:24.668 --> 01:30:28.428
be potential funders. At one point, the
father looked at me, and he goes, "Hey, this

01:30:28.488 --> 01:30:32.348
whole running from the Pirates of the Caribbean
thing," he's like, "It's getting scary.

01:30:32.368 --> 01:30:36.248
You're scaring us." He
was like, "Can we..."

01:30:36.268 --> 01:30:40.188
I'm like, "What are we doing?" He goes, "When
are you gonna put the drone down?" And I go,

01:30:40.248 --> 01:30:44.148
"I'm flying the drone at full speed to keep up
with the boat." And I just crash-landed the drone

01:30:44.208 --> 01:30:46.788
on the side of the river near a big tree. I
just said, "Forget it. We'll get it later."

01:30:46.828 --> 01:30:50.528
And I was like, "Fine. This happens
all the time." "They get mad. They

01:30:50.668 --> 01:30:54.568
chase us. It's no big deal." And I smiled
at him, and JJ's smiling. He goes, "This is

01:30:54.648 --> 01:30:55.278
so bad."

01:30:55.278 --> 01:30:59.088
And he's smiling. And JJ looked at me, and
the smile fell off him like a mask, and he

01:30:59.128 --> 01:31:04.638
looked at me, and he was like, "This is
not good." And we kept going upriver

01:31:05.608 --> 01:31:09.408
and luckily, there was a camp of
police that we've worked with quite a

01:31:09.468 --> 01:31:13.458
bit. And I went to a friend of mine, and

01:31:13.568 --> 01:31:17.448
I remember we got off the boat. I shook his hand. He
said, "What's going on?" I said, "Look downriver, and

01:31:17.468 --> 01:31:22.028
there's a boat tearing upriver towards
us." And he did three things. He

01:31:22.828 --> 01:31:26.748
got the rest of the guys, they armed up,
they got on the boat with guns. They

01:31:26.768 --> 01:31:30.588
put ski masks on. They got ready for
combat. They told us to get down. He also

01:31:30.628 --> 01:31:34.168
said, "Hey, turn on the
sat-link. Call for support back

01:31:34.208 --> 01:31:37.284
home." We turned our boat
around. And as soon as the

01:31:37.384 --> 01:31:41.104
narcos, which we didn't
even realize were narcos

01:31:41.144 --> 01:31:43.004
chasing us. We thought we
were looking at loggers.

01:31:43.884 --> 01:31:47.844
When they saw the guns and they saw us face them,
they turned their boat around, and they went back

01:31:47.884 --> 01:31:51.744
downriver. So we got
escorted downriver, and I

01:31:51.804 --> 01:31:55.624
remember shaking his hand, my
friend, and saying, "Thank you

01:31:55.724 --> 01:31:59.524
for saving us today." And telling
the other guys they did a good

01:31:59.564 --> 01:32:03.504
job. I said, "Get back upriver." We'd been
brought home safe. This is hours later.

01:32:03.564 --> 01:32:07.464
I said, "Good job. Thank
you so much." And they went

01:32:07.544 --> 01:32:11.304
and then that night, I'm sitting
at the station that you know.

01:32:11.344 --> 01:32:15.064
know. And I get a phone
call from Stefan. And he

01:32:15.124 --> 01:32:18.914
He goes, "Pick up the phone." I go,
"I'm in the middle of a conversation."

01:32:19.084 --> 01:32:26.164
He goes, "Pick up the phone." And my
friend, whose hand I had just shaken,

01:32:26.224 --> 01:32:29.984
they went back upriver, and as they were unloading
their boat and washing off in the stream,

01:32:30.064 --> 01:32:33.904
the narcos did a drive-by and
shotgun straight to the chest,

01:32:34.004 --> 01:32:37.224
shot him in the chest. And
so all of that enthusiasm,

01:32:37.364 --> 01:32:41.303
and "We're protecting the
biodiversity" and "This is so great,"

01:32:41.404 --> 01:32:45.224
there's people from around the world...
it's like that scene in the movie

01:32:45.304 --> 01:32:52.624
where there's a montage of success and
hope and acres and winning—gunshot.

01:32:53.664 --> 01:32:57.514
And I could still feel his hand in my
hand. I just shook his hand. I said, "No."

01:32:57.564 --> 01:33:00.924
I said, "Well, is he okay?" He said, "He
took a shotgun straight to the chest."

01:33:00.984 --> 01:33:04.124
And they're like, "He's
dead." I said, "Okay."

01:33:04.164 --> 01:33:09.144
And so I had to go out to dinner
and not show the guests anything,

01:33:10.204 --> 01:33:13.824
and just smile and laugh and talk to
them about whatever and keep that in,

01:33:13.904 --> 01:33:17.624
which felt very, very difficult to do.

01:33:17.634 --> 01:33:25.724
And so what happened, as you said, the threat
level escalated and we didn't know it.

01:33:25.734 --> 01:33:29.424
The narcos had come in and started realizing
that there's so much wilderness here

01:33:29.464 --> 01:33:32.514
that they can operate and there's no
police. And then when we flew the drone,

01:33:32.604 --> 01:33:37.854
they got mad. So we realized this.

01:33:38.664 --> 01:33:42.644
We communicated with the police and
they said, "Oh yeah, these are narcos."

01:33:42.764 --> 01:33:46.504
Now we realize this is part
of the serious drug mafia.

01:33:46.524 --> 01:33:50.384
And then I had gone back—with the incident
you're referring to at the end of the book,

01:33:50.444 --> 01:34:01.364
I had gone back to New York, again, to speak to
donors to try and get this work to continue.

01:34:02.644 --> 01:34:06.624
You know how it works. We're at the station,
then you go to that little logging town,

01:34:06.724 --> 01:34:10.604
and then there's a road. And so our
pickup truck had come in on the road,

01:34:10.664 --> 01:34:17.004
and JJ was supposed to come down, get in
the truck and drive back to the city.

01:34:17.044 --> 01:34:20.824
JJ was on the river and went, "I forgot I
was supposed to get more stuff at the city."

01:34:20.864 --> 01:34:27.484
He goes, "You know, I'll go tomorrow." He
went back up and sent the boat driver down,

01:34:28.144 --> 01:34:32.084
and told our driver, Percy, who was waiting
with the pickup truck, "JJ's not coming today."

01:34:32.124 --> 01:34:35.944
"Go back and come back tomorrow."
Percy starts driving down the road

01:34:35.954 --> 01:34:39.764
and he sees a tree across the road.

01:34:39.844 --> 01:34:43.284
This is a single-lane road through the
jungle; there's nowhere else you can go,

01:34:43.324 --> 01:34:46.884
and men with guns come and stick the
pistols in through the open windows,

01:34:46.964 --> 01:34:50.884
gun against his head. They pull
him out and they go, "Where's JJ?"

01:34:50.924 --> 01:34:54.784
And "¿Donde está el gringo volador?"
They said, "Where's that shithead gringo

01:34:54.824 --> 01:34:58.644
that flew the drone?" And if either
of us had been in the car that day,

01:34:58.704 --> 01:35:01.673
if either of us had been in the car
that day, they would have killed

01:35:01.744 --> 01:35:05.694
they took his phone, our driver Percy's.
Thank God, they didn't hurt him,

01:35:05.724 --> 01:35:08.584
driver, Percy. They, thank
God, they didn't hurt

01:35:08.624 --> 01:35:12.404
but they sent a message to us.
They said, "Let them know."

01:35:12.444 --> 01:35:16.234
They said, "We missed you this time, but we'll
get you next time. We're gonna get you."

01:35:16.344 --> 01:35:26.184
And so when JJ called me, he
was howling. He just had that

01:35:27.864 --> 01:35:32.184
adrenaline and that emotion
of that it almost happened.

01:35:33.544 --> 01:35:36.774
And so that was... that changed
everything. And so since then we've

01:35:36.804 --> 01:35:40.684
been, you know, it's not counting
butterflies and taking ecological

01:35:40.724 --> 01:35:43.964
surveys, it's that there's a
drug war being fought on our

01:35:43.984 --> 01:35:47.524
river. And now when these
roads come in, we can't just

01:35:48.064 --> 01:35:51.064
go out and meet these people anymore
and talk to them, 'cause they are

01:35:51.764 --> 01:35:55.694
actively looking to shoot us.
They know our names, and then...

01:35:55.724 --> 01:35:59.634
as if all these other things weren't enough
indication, the police intercepted a

01:35:59.644 --> 01:36:03.004
phone from someone they arrested, and
on the phone, in the WhatsApp chat, it

01:36:03.044 --> 01:36:07.004
said, "If you see JJ or the gringo,
anyone in our network, please

01:36:07.044 --> 01:36:11.344
kill them. You'll be rewarded."
So we both have a hit out on us

01:36:12.324 --> 01:36:16.234
and life on the river has changed.
At the moment, we don't...

01:36:16.304 --> 01:36:20.004
we can't... I can't just go out
walking around, swimming and

01:36:20.064 --> 01:36:23.224
driving my boat. You have
to be looking over your

01:36:23.884 --> 01:36:27.484
shoulder at all times. You can get
as trained as you want with a pistol

01:36:27.544 --> 01:36:31.374
and sleep with it under your
pillow, but the way these

01:36:31.404 --> 01:36:35.124
people work, they'll catch you when you're least
expecting it. They'll wait till you're at a cafe in

01:36:35.204 --> 01:36:38.964
town. They'll wait till your motor doesn't
work on the side of the river. It'll just be a

01:36:39.044 --> 01:36:43.024
quick one and they'll go.
And so that feeling, on

01:36:43.084 --> 01:36:46.994
top of the weight of- of
protecting the ecosystem and

01:36:47.024 --> 01:36:50.924
the animals, and the race to tell people
about it and do all this, it's like

01:36:51.004 --> 01:36:54.033
now we're actively being
hunted when we're there.

01:36:54.033 --> 01:36:59.044
- And this is very directed at you and JJ?

01:36:59.084 --> 01:37:05.784
So they really don't care about
the others. They understand.

01:37:05.864 --> 01:37:11.244
Are you afraid? What's it
been like living with this,

01:37:13.324 --> 01:37:20.524
with the real fear of being
murdered at any moment?

01:37:20.744 --> 01:37:24.704
- I wish I could say I handled it
better than I've been handling it.

01:37:24.764 --> 01:37:28.724
I wonder how people in war zones do it.

01:37:28.744 --> 01:37:32.604
I wonder how some of my soldier friends that I
have immense respect for did it when they were

01:37:32.624 --> 01:37:36.334
deployed, 'cause for me,
once this happened, it was,

01:37:36.404 --> 01:37:40.394
every phone call now I think,
"Did something happen to JJ?"

01:37:40.424 --> 01:37:50.175
Every time I go to sleep, my dreams
are that I'm being shot. And

01:37:50.276 --> 01:37:54.076
it really threw me. It really
affected me. When JJ called me, the

01:37:54.215 --> 01:37:58.175
way he was just shouting... I don't even
remember what he was saying. He was just

01:37:58.255 --> 01:38:01.995
shouting, "They almost got us!
They almost got us!" He was so,

01:38:02.056 --> 01:38:06.035
terrified and angry and,

01:38:06.045 --> 01:38:09.955
so yeah, it's... There was a day
not long ago that I was swimming

01:38:09.995 --> 01:38:13.965
in the river. And I was just in the river,
you know, right in front of the stairs

01:38:13.976 --> 01:38:17.875
at the station, and a boat came
around the bend. And I remember

01:38:17.915 --> 01:38:21.875
thinking, "Do I run? Do I go
underwater? Do I hide? What the

01:38:21.936 --> 01:38:25.906
hell do I do?" I didn't have a gun near me.
The security people were up the stairs.

01:38:25.915 --> 01:38:29.635
You go, "Holy shit." And it's not the

01:38:29.675 --> 01:38:33.606
danger of, "if I jump on an anaconda, it
might kill me," or "if I climb this, I

01:38:33.656 --> 01:38:39.306
might fall." These are people who want
to kill you. And on top of it, you have

01:38:39.356 --> 01:38:46.965
the, you know... When you see
what your friend looks like after

01:38:47.076 --> 01:38:50.616
three days of floating in a river, what a
body looks like of a person you used to

01:38:50.635 --> 01:38:56.896
know, that's very viscerally terrifying
because there's the tragedy of

01:38:56.955 --> 01:39:00.856
that, that person lost his life,

01:39:00.915 --> 01:39:04.795
who was younger than I was. He
was a kid. He was in his 20s.

01:39:04.955 --> 01:39:08.736
And it's just very hard,
it's very hard to do

01:39:08.795 --> 01:39:12.726
anything because... I mean, like
right now, my hands are sweating.

01:39:12.726 --> 01:39:16.616
It affects me. And even in the daylight,
if I can go, "You know, it's fine. This is

01:39:16.715 --> 01:39:20.035
part of the thing," you know? This is the adventure,
people deal with this all over the world.

01:39:20.476 --> 01:39:24.255
You can talk yourself tough
and then, in those quiet

01:39:24.295 --> 01:39:28.135
moments, you wake up at 4:00 AM
and you go, "Fuck." You know,

01:39:28.156 --> 01:39:32.066
"Why am I sweating? Why did I just have
those dreams? Why is my heart racing?"

01:39:32.156 --> 01:39:40.066
It sinks its way into your subconscious
and it's just not what we signed up for.

01:39:40.076 --> 01:39:43.816
We wanted to just protect this
beautiful place and this is this whole

01:39:43.995 --> 01:39:48.236
new threat. We're not trained
for this. We're not a

01:39:49.255 --> 01:39:55.806
police or military force and it's like
we've now seen violence on a scale that

01:39:58.156 --> 01:40:02.146
we were very unprepared for.
And so, just two days ago, I

01:40:02.175 --> 01:40:05.915
was on my way to you and my phone rang
at nine o'clock at night and it was JJ.

01:40:05.936 --> 01:40:09.855
And my heart was jackhammering.
I had to pull over

01:40:09.915 --> 01:40:13.705
because I was going, "What news
now?" You know? "Did we lose another

01:40:13.776 --> 01:40:20.635
bunch of acres? Is it a new road? Did
somebody die?" It really scatters you.

01:40:20.656 --> 01:40:23.696
- In some sense, it's a twist that
you didn't ask for and it doesn't

01:40:24.356 --> 01:40:28.056
necessarily have anything to do with
the fight you're fighting, which is

01:40:28.076 --> 01:40:31.955
protecting the rainforest.
But because of it being

01:40:32.076 --> 01:40:39.266
pristine and quiet and away from
civilization, it also becomes a place where,

01:40:39.335 --> 01:40:43.156
you can have airstrips.
It becomes lawless in a

01:40:43.175 --> 01:40:45.976
certain way because it's so
far away from civilization.

01:40:46.035 --> 01:40:49.875
- Yeah. It's the only place that
they can operate with impunity.

01:40:49.936 --> 01:40:53.625
There's no police out there. And
so they saw us helping the police

01:40:54.635 --> 01:41:01.696
and they went, "Cut the head off the snake."
And, you know, Chico Mendes, Dorothy

01:41:01.736 --> 01:41:05.696
Stang—the list of environmental
defenders that are assassinated in the

01:41:05.715 --> 01:41:09.656
Amazon every year is huge.

01:41:09.675 --> 01:41:13.596
There are endless examples of it.
It's staggering. I forget the

01:41:14.516 --> 01:41:18.175
exact numbers, but every
year we lose local

01:41:18.236 --> 01:41:22.135
leaders who are trying to stop an oil
company or a drug cartel, and they

01:41:22.175 --> 01:41:25.976
just shoot them because they know
that one person who's able to rally

01:41:26.236 --> 01:41:28.816
that support, who has that
voice, if you just shoot

01:41:28.825 --> 01:41:32.736
them, usually it ends the thing
and then they can go back to

01:41:32.755 --> 01:41:35.686
doing whatever the hell they
want. And so right now,

01:41:35.736 --> 01:41:39.556
we're working very closely with
the Peruvian government. People

01:41:39.596 --> 01:41:43.215
assume that, you know, a Latin
American government is automatically

01:41:43.276 --> 01:41:47.215
corrupt, but we found that these
are really good people that want to

01:41:48.856 --> 01:41:52.835
help their citizens. And the
police have been working very

01:41:52.875 --> 01:41:56.816
hard to stop the narcos, to
protect the local indigenous

01:41:56.835 --> 01:42:03.335
people because with the narcos comes
human trafficking. With a team

01:42:03.396 --> 01:42:06.406
of male narcos that are
out in the woods making

01:42:07.156 --> 01:42:11.135
drugs, they want prostitutes. And how
do they get prostitutes? They go steal

01:42:11.196 --> 01:42:15.036
girls from indigenous communities
that don't know any better.

01:42:15.096 --> 01:42:18.816
Then there's reports that the narcos
have made contact with the uncontacted

01:42:18.875 --> 01:42:22.795
tribes. And of course, they're gonna shoot
machine guns at them. They're not gonna have a

01:42:22.856 --> 01:42:26.816
shotgun where it's a fair fight. They're gonna
mow them down and the uncontacted tribes are

01:42:26.835 --> 01:42:30.806
gonna have no idea. That's
why I posted a video

01:42:30.816 --> 01:42:34.594
of me in the rain saying, "This is
endgame," because there was a new

01:42:34.696 --> 01:42:38.455
road that was coming off
the north of our territory

01:42:38.536 --> 01:42:42.575
above the ancient forest. They had jumped over
'cause we stopped it at the ancient forest.

01:42:42.596 --> 01:42:45.976
They've gone above the ancient forest.
Now, they're trying to cut down to a new

01:42:46.056 --> 01:42:56.885
area. And so it looks like this,
like that. ...Trans-Amazon...

01:42:57.075 --> 01:43:00.955
Stefan made this map, of course. But
you see the area that we're trying to

01:43:00.976 --> 01:43:04.545
protect loosely, so that we
don't give away anything...

01:43:04.575 --> 01:43:08.585
Loosely, the area that we are protecting.
So, the light green is the 130,000 acres—

01:43:09.016 --> 01:43:12.795
...and then this metastasizing network of
roads just reaching out and trying to get

01:43:12.875 --> 01:43:16.795
in. And so they're trying to come in
from the north where that arrow is,

01:43:17.266 --> 01:43:21.566
they're trying to come down. And so the
police are fighting them along this—

01:43:21.616 --> 01:43:25.606
...and it's a full-on drug
war right now. And so,

01:43:25.635 --> 01:43:29.616
stopping that, securing this northern
boundary. And again, just the

01:43:29.696 --> 01:43:33.696
power of what we have. When I posted
this, I asked Stefan to make,

01:43:34.616 --> 01:43:37.715
show people the road and
where it's going to go.

01:43:37.776 --> 01:43:41.596
We posted this video and said, "We have to
protect this 100,000 acres right now." And

01:43:41.675 --> 01:43:44.825
all up here is uncontacted
tribe territory.

01:43:44.835 --> 01:43:51.465
And just from that one post, we got
$150,000 in 48 hours and we bought this

01:43:51.496 --> 01:43:55.505
concession. We stopped that
road. But now they're up here—

01:43:55.505 --> 01:43:59.456
...and they're trying to come
down. And this is the thing: it's

01:43:59.496 --> 01:44:03.255
great. Yes, you get to be an adventurer
and live in the jungle, sure.

01:44:03.276 --> 01:44:07.175
But it's like this Mission:
Impossible thing where

01:44:07.215 --> 01:44:11.156
you might get lucky enough to pull off your
psychotic mission. You know, jump your

01:44:11.196 --> 01:44:14.946
motorcycle off the train and parachute
down and stop the bomb before it goes

01:44:14.996 --> 01:44:20.675
off. Great. How many of those do you get?
And we're having to do it every month.

01:44:21.976 --> 01:44:25.936
These amazing people

01:44:25.996 --> 01:44:29.956
that are supporting the rangers allow us to patrol
and protect this because once we have this land

01:44:29.976 --> 01:44:33.956
protected, the interesting thing is
that the police can go into any of the

01:44:33.976 --> 01:44:37.416
light green areas. If anybody's
there, just arrest them.

01:44:37.436 --> 01:44:41.156
They're on Junglekeepers' land, they're
out. And eventually that land will

01:44:41.196 --> 01:44:44.976
become national park if we're successful.
The problem with the land that's

01:44:45.056 --> 01:44:48.836
not is it's a gray area. It's the
middle of the Amazon, are they

01:44:48.876 --> 01:44:52.856
allowed to be here? Do they really have
cocaine? Because they'll plant papaya

01:44:52.916 --> 01:44:56.876
for acres and a little bit of cocaine
behind it. You know, they'll put the

01:44:56.936 --> 01:45:00.866
sacks... They're sneaky. And so they have
to build a case, and it takes time, and

01:45:00.876 --> 01:45:04.576
then the road comes in... You know, and in
that time, they'll knock off a police officer.

01:45:04.616 --> 01:45:10.196
And it's like if we were just able
to get this tomorrow, the whole

01:45:11.135 --> 01:45:14.135
problem gets solved. We could
give the police two more

01:45:14.175 --> 01:45:17.356
boats, and then they could do
all the patrolling they need.

01:45:17.366 --> 01:45:18.675
- So the mission is clear.

01:45:18.715 --> 01:45:22.416
- The mission is very clear. The problem is
that right now we've been playing defense

01:45:22.736 --> 01:45:26.516
and sustaining losses. And either we need

01:45:26.576 --> 01:45:30.516
to inspire enough people that the donor
program goes through the roof, and

01:45:30.536 --> 01:45:34.505
instead of having several thousand
donors, we have, you know, 50,000 donors

01:45:34.576 --> 01:45:38.536
and we will raise... We
need $20 million to save

01:45:38.556 --> 01:45:43.206
the rest of the corridor. We'd raise $20
million overnight with enough people. Or

01:45:44.135 --> 01:45:47.916
we need one of these people that
has the resources to come in like

01:45:47.956 --> 01:45:50.936
Batman and just go, "I want
the park named after me

01:45:51.876 --> 01:45:55.715
and I'm just gonna come in and give you the
$20 million." And then we do it tomorrow,

01:45:55.785 --> 01:45:59.675
and then we make a documentary about how we
saved a river and the tribe and the monkeys and

01:45:59.715 --> 01:46:04.416
the... But right now, we're...

01:46:05.236 --> 01:46:08.696
you know, begging on the side of
the road for enough change to buy

01:46:08.976 --> 01:46:11.156
bullets so that we can stay alive.

01:46:12.596 --> 01:46:16.416
- So these narcos, they're...
There's a kind of distributed

01:46:16.476 --> 01:46:20.166
network where a bunch of them are
pretending to be farmers. So they're

01:46:20.236 --> 01:46:28.556
holding onto the land and then maybe
they start planting cocaine on the land-

01:46:28.635 --> 01:46:32.916
...slowly, and they build the airstrips.
Are they trying to stay under the canopy

01:46:32.996 --> 01:46:33.836
with the airstrip?

01:46:33.896 --> 01:46:37.255
- It's brilliant. First what they do is they

01:46:38.536 --> 01:46:44.696
subsidize the poorest people and they say,
"Go up this river, turn left at the tree

01:46:45.496 --> 01:46:49.336
and just start there." And they're like, "Here's
a few grand." And these people are like, "I

01:46:49.356 --> 01:46:52.956
never had a few grand before." They're like,
"Buy gasoline. Here's a chainsaw. Go clear some

01:46:52.996 --> 01:46:56.916
land." They send these people up there,
and then when they show up a year later

01:46:56.936 --> 01:47:00.715
and these people have made an illegal farm out
in the jungle, they go, "Hey, we need a safe

01:47:00.726 --> 01:47:04.596
house. Remember that time we gave you
gasoline and now you live here? You're gonna

01:47:04.616 --> 01:47:08.576
work for us now." And so they're kind
of a friend of the people like that,

01:47:08.596 --> 01:47:12.556
and they have safe houses all over the
jungle. And then when the bosses come to

01:47:12.616 --> 01:47:16.356
collect what they're growing out
there... I mean, the police busted

01:47:16.366 --> 01:47:20.226
a narco operation that was
in the middle of the jungle.

01:47:20.255 --> 01:47:22.726
I mean, hiking to the ancient forest

01:47:22.726 --> 01:47:26.156
days into the jungle. These people are
going on foot with sacks and stuff.

01:47:27.476 --> 01:47:31.406
And the way they do their airstrips is
you think the canopy of the rainforest

01:47:31.436 --> 01:47:34.836
is 150 or 160 feet tall. And if you

01:47:34.936 --> 01:47:38.736
clear the interior of the landing
strip, the trees are still meeting

01:47:38.796 --> 01:47:42.566
overhead. And so you can't
fly over and see down—

01:47:42.566 --> 01:47:46.296
...which is the same reason we didn't know about
the road that was going to the ancient forest,

01:47:46.396 --> 01:47:49.556
because overhead the trees are meeting, so
you're not going to see it on satellite

01:47:49.596 --> 01:47:53.316
and you're not going to see it from a plane. And
these bush pilots fly in and they'll just duck

01:47:53.416 --> 01:47:57.175
in under the canopy, land their
plane, load up, and then they fly

01:47:57.276 --> 01:48:01.036
out. I mean, expert pilots.

01:48:01.135 --> 01:48:02.956
- So it's impossible to detect.

01:48:03.016 --> 01:48:06.876
- It's almost impossible to detect.
We're working with people now. You

01:48:06.916 --> 01:48:10.696
know, it's this arms race. They've
been going okay. There are drone

01:48:10.776 --> 01:48:13.656
programs. I talked to someone that
has a different type of drone, a

01:48:13.776 --> 01:48:17.536
16-foot drone that uses the

01:48:17.556 --> 01:48:21.126
thermals to climb up and has solar panels on
the wings and flies for two weeks at a time.

01:48:21.135 --> 01:48:22.396
It's like a glider-

01:48:22.406 --> 01:48:26.346
...that recharges itself. And it'll
keep constant imagery, so we'll get

01:48:26.376 --> 01:48:30.306
almost up-to-the-moment data on
disturbances in the canopy. And it's like,

01:48:30.336 --> 01:48:34.236
well, that'll be a first-hand
alert system, but then we've gotta

01:48:34.255 --> 01:48:37.876
get the police out there which,
as you know, is a two-day

01:48:37.916 --> 01:48:40.745
expedition by boat, and
it's the only way. And

01:48:40.796 --> 01:48:44.776
so the local police force there
may be dedicated, but putting

01:48:44.796 --> 01:48:48.786
people on a multi-day expedition to go get
shot at in the jungle is nobody's idea of a

01:48:48.836 --> 01:48:49.266
good time.

01:48:49.776 --> 01:48:53.686
- Have you researched into
this whole other world of

01:48:53.776 --> 01:48:57.056
Drug trafficking, cocaine
trafficking? How big is the

01:48:57.156 --> 01:49:00.215
operation? Looking at Perplexity—

01:49:00.396 --> 01:49:04.356
...a multi-thousand ton,
multi-billion dollar global industry?

01:49:05.036 --> 01:49:07.135
- I mean, globally it's a monster.

01:49:07.156 --> 01:49:13.456
- Colombia, Peru, Bolivia. And they move
north and east through the Americas, the

01:49:13.536 --> 01:49:19.836
Caribbean, and the Atlantic to reach
major consumer markets. This is a machine

01:49:22.096 --> 01:49:25.606
fueled by a lot of money
and a lot of brutality.

01:49:27.836 --> 01:49:32.226
Number of cocaine users worldwide
is about 25 million people.

01:49:32.236 --> 01:49:33.016
- Users.

01:49:33.116 --> 01:49:35.796
- Users. So there's a market.

01:49:35.816 --> 01:49:38.596
And when there's a market,
you're going to find the way.

01:49:39.656 --> 01:49:45.836
Quick pause. Bathroom break.
All right, and we're back.

01:49:47.436 --> 01:49:50.908
Me, as somebody who is afraid of heights,

01:49:51.468 --> 01:49:55.288
and I've had a chance to interact
with you a bunch, you're in

01:49:55.548 --> 01:49:59.528
some sense fearless and I've
watched you climb a lot

01:49:59.548 --> 01:50:03.468
of trees. You've helped me
climb a tree. And there's this

01:50:03.568 --> 01:50:07.288
wonderful part of the book where you
talk about finding the tallest tree

01:50:07.788 --> 01:50:11.408
in the forest you knew at the time,
and that was something that you

01:50:11.528 --> 01:50:15.168
passed and thought was impossible to
climb. And you talk about climbing it.

01:50:15.228 --> 01:50:19.818
You take us through the experience of
that. And that leads you to seeing the

01:50:20.648 --> 01:50:24.518
Mist River in the rainforest
as the sun rises. I was

01:50:24.548 --> 01:50:28.218
wondering if you could talk
through the story of that,

01:50:28.228 --> 01:50:31.768
both for me, but even for
you at that time, the

01:50:31.808 --> 01:50:35.748
terrifying process of climbing a tree like

01:50:35.848 --> 01:50:39.498
that for the first time
with J.J. at the bottom

01:50:39.628 --> 01:50:44.568
cheering you on, and what it
felt like to see the Mist River.

01:50:44.608 --> 01:50:48.288
- That tree, you've met that
tree. She's a good one. Her

01:50:48.428 --> 01:50:54.468
base is at least as big as this
room, and she's probably about

01:50:54.528 --> 01:50:58.478
160-something feet tall. And
so when you're looking at

01:50:58.528 --> 01:51:02.308
these giant buttress roots going
up, which I'd been doing for 18

01:51:02.328 --> 01:51:06.248
years at that point, I always said,
"Man, if I could just climb it."

01:51:06.268 --> 01:51:10.128
I'd never had the rope skills, and
I'd developed as a rock climber.

01:51:10.248 --> 01:51:15.388
I was working on strength, and I
trained for it. It's like most things.

01:51:15.448 --> 01:51:18.548
You can't just do it. I'd
climb up 30 feet and go, "No

01:51:18.688 --> 01:51:22.608
way." The trunk of the tree goes vertical

01:51:22.668 --> 01:51:26.648
for about 70 feet before branches even
come out, so there's just this one

01:51:26.748 --> 01:51:30.648
big vine. And J.J. and I did it at,

01:51:31.708 --> 01:51:35.648
I want to say like 4:00 AM,
really early. The howler monkeys

01:51:35.708 --> 01:51:43.278
had just started. And you start
climbing with the rope up this vine,

01:51:43.308 --> 01:51:47.188
and you have to... It's not technical.
It's a strength climb. You gorilla up

01:51:47.288 --> 01:51:51.228
this vine, and it's all back
strength. And so I did it no shirt,

01:51:51.268 --> 01:51:55.248
no shoes, straight up, and J.J.
had the belay device. And so every

01:51:55.288 --> 01:51:58.888
30 feet or so, I would put
in a piece of webbing and a

01:51:58.948 --> 01:52:02.908
carabiner. You go up another 30
feet, and you don't know what you're

01:52:02.928 --> 01:52:05.708
gonna find. And you're
going up in the dark.

01:52:05.728 --> 01:52:09.168
- So when you say a lot of strength
is involved, there are very few

01:52:09.228 --> 01:52:12.857
places to rest. You're essentially
just lifting the whole time.

01:52:12.857 --> 01:52:13.648
So it's extremely exhausting.

01:52:13.748 --> 01:52:17.688
- Extremely exhausting. I really
trained for a long time, and there is

01:52:17.728 --> 01:52:21.698
no rest. The only rest you
get hurts. You have to

01:52:21.808 --> 01:52:25.708
cling to the tree and your feet are
smeared against the bark. You're

01:52:25.728 --> 01:52:29.577
holding on with your toes.
And if you fall, you know, if

01:52:29.748 --> 01:52:33.428
you're climbing up—this is basically
trad climbing—if you're climbing up

01:52:33.908 --> 01:52:37.768
and you put a safety—a piece of
rope with a carabiner—and you

01:52:37.808 --> 01:52:41.108
put my rope through that... It's
dangerous because if you fall,

01:52:41.188 --> 01:52:44.848
you fall. Right before you put the next

01:52:44.948 --> 01:52:48.848
one, you're going to fall double. If
you climb 30 feet, you fall 60 feet.

01:52:48.868 --> 01:52:52.848
And your head's going to smack the
tree. As you climb, you don't know

01:52:52.888 --> 01:52:55.888
if you'll reach a wasp
nest or a venomous snake.

01:52:56.648 --> 01:52:58.828
- And there's a lot of those in those trees.

01:52:58.868 --> 01:53:02.718
- A lot of those. It took me over an
hour just to get to the branches

01:53:02.788 --> 01:53:06.708
the first time. It's full exertion,
everything I had. And then you get

01:53:06.728 --> 01:53:10.698
to where the branches are above you,
each the size of a mature oak tree.

01:53:10.708 --> 01:53:14.258
They're just these huge branches.

01:53:14.288 --> 01:53:18.168
Thick as a minivan. You're
climbing up this straight tree

01:53:18.208 --> 01:53:22.108
that's like the World Trade Center.
It's huge. Then I had to traverse

01:53:22.128 --> 01:53:25.948
the tree on vines, and finally I
get up into the crown of this tree.

01:53:26.608 --> 01:53:30.528
From there, I called down to J.J.
and I just see this little speck of

01:53:31.568 --> 01:53:35.548
light, 85 feet below me. Then I
climbed up to about 120 feet,

01:53:35.588 --> 01:53:39.148
which is up here, and I sat there.

01:53:39.188 --> 01:53:41.988
- And you're doing all
this still in darkness.

01:53:41.998 --> 01:53:45.888
- We're doing all this in the pre-dawn
light. And so when I got up

01:53:45.948 --> 01:53:49.928
there, now the howler monkeys are
going and the jungle's starting

01:53:49.968 --> 01:53:53.668
to vibrate. You can hear the first macaws
starting to chirp; everything's starting to turn

01:53:53.728 --> 01:53:57.608
on. And in the east, the sun is
coming over the jungle, and so the

01:53:57.728 --> 01:53:59.388
sun, when the first rays

01:54:00.268 --> 01:54:03.908
get line of sight to the canopy of the
jungle, it starts lifting the mist off the

01:54:03.968 --> 01:54:07.768
canopy. All of that moisture starts
coming up, and I'm sitting on this branch

01:54:08.328 --> 01:54:11.308
at 100-something feet above the
ground with dark jungle below

01:54:11.328 --> 01:54:15.208
me, and all of a sudden I see the river.

01:54:15.308 --> 01:54:17.308
I see the Mist River I'd always
heard about. They say that

01:54:18.128 --> 01:54:21.997
there's a river above the
Amazon, an invisible river that

01:54:22.208 --> 01:54:26.088
has more moisture and that more water is
flowing above the Amazon than is flowing in

01:54:26.128 --> 01:54:29.908
the Amazon. And I'd heard this my whole life
and you think, "Okay, the fact that there's a

01:54:29.948 --> 01:54:33.778
molten core of the Earth or that black holes
theoretically exist." It's just like the, one of

01:54:33.788 --> 01:54:37.628
those things, you're never going to see
it." And in this moment on this tree,

01:54:37.728 --> 01:54:41.168
sweating and just ripped apart and
bleeding, I was sitting up there and I

01:54:41.368 --> 01:54:44.348
saw the Mist River and
it was flowing over the

01:54:44.388 --> 01:54:48.148
canopy in the golden rays of
the morning, and the macaws

01:54:48.208 --> 01:54:51.388
start taking flight and there were
monkeys below me that were looking

01:54:51.408 --> 01:54:55.058
up. And you could tell they were confused.
They were looking at me going, "What is that?"

01:54:55.868 --> 01:54:58.588
And I just had this absolutely
incredible moment. I wanted

01:54:58.648 --> 01:55:02.468
to... You know, it felt
like you're seeing God. I

01:55:02.528 --> 01:55:07.268
wanted to share it with everyone.
You know, I felt, I felt guilty

01:55:08.068 --> 01:55:11.948
afterwards for having had a moment
like that. But it felt like I had done

01:55:11.968 --> 01:55:15.328
this insane risk and

01:55:15.928 --> 01:55:19.908
risked falling out of the tree or
getting strung up on the ropes, and of

01:55:19.928 --> 01:55:23.238
course it's just me and J.J., so if
something goes wrong, no one's going to help

01:55:23.288 --> 01:55:27.268
you. And being out there on that
branch felt suicidal because

01:55:27.328 --> 01:55:31.308
even then, if you fall, it's a giant
swing back to the tree. But the

01:55:31.588 --> 01:55:39.288
beauty that I saw up there was so
intense that it, you know, it sucked the

01:55:39.408 --> 01:55:43.028
air right out of my lungs. I had tears
in my eyes and I'm just watching

01:55:43.648 --> 01:55:47.508
this incredible process flow
over the Earth, this legendary

01:55:47.628 --> 01:55:51.468
thing that I'd heard about, that scientists
described, and now I'm seeing it with my

01:55:51.488 --> 01:55:56.228
own eyes. It was... it felt
like the gift of the tree.

01:55:56.268 --> 01:55:59.868
- And you write, "Now, in the branches
of the greatest tree in the jungle, I

01:55:59.928 --> 01:56:03.528
watched as the Mist River caught the
morning rays, illuminating golden

01:56:03.588 --> 01:56:07.468
currents, swirling as it rushed
over the canopy like a stream from

01:56:07.508 --> 01:56:11.488
heaven. In the troughs and
basins in lower areas,

01:56:11.528 --> 01:56:15.408
the river was deep blue. But
then, as it flowed up and

01:56:15.468 --> 01:56:19.228
over the taller trees, slow rapids
washing over the canopy, the

01:56:19.268 --> 01:56:22.928
Mist River became ignited,
electrified in the gold

01:56:22.968 --> 01:56:26.708
magnificence of the sunlight.
Scores of birds flew

01:56:26.828 --> 01:56:30.738
up, in and out of the churning currents.

01:56:30.788 --> 01:56:34.758
The life and breath of the Amazon was
flowing from north to south along the basins

01:56:34.808 --> 01:56:41.828
of Las Piedras over the jungle. My
God. My God. I thought of everyone I

01:56:41.948 --> 01:56:44.868
loved, of every creature
contained in the leafy

01:56:44.888 --> 01:56:48.848
distance. The jungle itself
was like a great being, a

01:56:48.908 --> 01:56:52.838
monstrous leviathan of warm green might. I

01:56:52.888 --> 01:56:56.728
wanted to call down to JJ and
tell him to find a way up. I

01:56:56.748 --> 01:57:00.528
wanted my mother to see it. I wanted
the world to see it. The light

01:57:00.588 --> 01:57:03.668
filled my eyes, and I
found myself wiping away

01:57:03.728 --> 01:57:07.868
tears." You know, I should
take the small tangent

01:57:09.168 --> 01:57:13.008
of saying the obvious, but the
thing that needs to be said

01:57:14.028 --> 01:57:15.928
is you're a great writer.

01:57:15.968 --> 01:57:20.278
- Thank you. I mean it, come on. I'm
just describing what happened, but...

01:57:20.328 --> 01:57:25.528
- All right. You mentioned macaws as part
of the process of The Jungle Waking Up.

01:57:25.608 --> 01:57:29.248
I read that when you first start
in the jungle, that's kind of your

01:57:29.308 --> 01:57:35.978
job is studying those. And me as
a fan of monogamy and birds...

01:57:35.978 --> 01:57:39.908
So macaws are beautiful, but
they're also monogamous creatures.

01:57:39.948 --> 01:57:43.228
They scream at each other quite
loudly. What are some interesting

01:57:44.048 --> 01:57:47.828
things about them? Among which, by
the way, you write how important

01:57:47.888 --> 01:57:53.608
the ironwoods are to— ...their
wellbeing, to their life.

01:57:53.668 --> 01:57:57.518
- Yeah, I mean, when I went
down there, like I said,

01:57:57.548 --> 01:58:01.417
for young people, if you want to get out there,
go do it. I agreed to stay at the station

01:58:01.448 --> 01:58:05.068
and do six hours of macaw
research every morning.

01:58:05.088 --> 01:58:09.068
So you'd wake up before dawn and go sit
and just stare at the side of the river.

01:58:09.088 --> 01:58:11.028
And the macaws would show up-

01:58:11.038 --> 01:58:14.868
...and like you said, they all scream and
bicker at each other. It's just how they

01:58:14.908 --> 01:58:18.308
talk. It's very, very loud,
and very, very harsh.

01:58:18.348 --> 01:58:22.208
But they do love each
other. They're always...

01:58:22.248 --> 01:58:25.218
You can actually hear when you walk through
the forest; I know what the sound of

01:58:25.228 --> 01:58:29.077
macaws giving affection is. They
make a certain kind of sound when

01:58:29.108 --> 01:58:32.848
they're just preening each other's
feathers and taking care of each

01:58:32.928 --> 01:58:36.768
other and just nuzzling. And then
there's a different call altogether when

01:58:36.788 --> 01:58:40.608
they're yelling at other macaws or saying,
"Let's go." And you start to learn

01:58:40.648 --> 01:58:42.288
macaw language.

01:58:42.328 --> 01:58:46.218
- What have you learned about
relationships and successful marriage

01:58:46.218 --> 01:58:51.688
from listening to macaws screaming at
each other in nuanced different ways?

01:58:52.568 --> 01:58:54.768
- Well, I guess...

01:58:54.788 --> 01:58:56.568
- Never mind, you can skip that question.

01:58:56.577 --> 01:59:00.568
- Yeah. It's interesting to see two
animals sticking by each other's side

01:59:00.608 --> 01:59:04.568
raising a chick. And at the bottom of the
stairs at the station, there is a macaw

01:59:04.628 --> 01:59:08.528
nest in an ironwood. And the
relationship that you mentioned is

01:59:08.608 --> 01:59:11.768
that in the jungle, there's a
limited amount of macaw real estate.

01:59:11.808 --> 01:59:15.488
And those are all ancient ironwood
trees, at least 500 years or more.

01:59:15.548 --> 01:59:22.658
So they have to be thick.
Car-thickness or bigger. And

01:59:23.228 --> 01:59:26.698
when a branch falls off, it creates a hollow
and the macaws use that to reproduce.

01:59:26.698 --> 01:59:30.368
And because there's only so many
nest sites in the forest, only about

01:59:30.408 --> 01:59:34.268
17 to 20% of the macaw population
reproduces in a given year.

01:59:34.308 --> 01:59:37.908
given year. So they have a
slow replacement rate. And

01:59:37.928 --> 01:59:41.688
macaws are one of the things that
people come to the jungle to

01:59:41.748 --> 01:59:45.568
see. And so along with gold mining
and logging and all these extractive

01:59:45.608 --> 01:59:49.478
things, in our region,
ecotourism has been great. It's

01:59:49.508 --> 01:59:53.048
given the local people jobs
as guides, cooks, and chefs

01:59:53.128 --> 01:59:57.048
and carpenters. And so macaws
are a huge part of that because

01:59:57.568 --> 02:00:01.538
it's one of the last places where you can
see these flying rainbows over the canopy.

02:00:01.588 --> 02:00:06.878
Or when you're on a branch from one of
these trees and the macaws fly under you.

02:00:07.708 --> 02:00:11.598
And again, they'll fly
by. You just hear the

02:00:11.668 --> 02:00:15.568
wind in their feathers. And they just look

02:00:15.588 --> 02:00:19.068
at you over their shoulder, like,
"What?" And just keep going.

02:00:19.808 --> 02:00:23.668
Just loud, and they'll just keep going. Then they'll
join up with other macaws and they fly across the

02:00:23.708 --> 02:00:27.628
horizon. And it gives you this
sense like you're seeing something

02:00:27.768 --> 02:00:31.588
from the dinosaur times.
It just looks like

02:00:31.788 --> 02:00:35.348
wild jungle, and there's nothing
human in sight. There's just this

02:00:35.448 --> 02:00:39.438
savage canopy to the horizon and just
these beautiful birds flying over.

02:00:39.438 --> 02:00:42.688
It's just... they're just magical.

02:00:42.728 --> 02:00:46.648
- You have this Instagram post
with an anaconda around

02:00:46.668 --> 02:00:49.828
your neck. There's a million
questions. Maybe you can talk

02:00:49.888 --> 02:00:53.908
about that experience, but
also, how did you not die?

02:00:53.948 --> 02:00:57.708
- So as you know, we've
been studying the habits

02:00:57.808 --> 02:01:01.388
of Eunectes murinus for quite a while.

02:01:01.448 --> 02:01:06.878
The lowland green anaconda is the
largest, heaviest snake on earth. And

02:01:07.808 --> 02:01:11.648
I've been practicing a lot for
a long time, and this is the

02:01:11.668 --> 02:01:15.358
biggest one we've ever physically
caught. This was just under

02:01:15.548 --> 02:01:19.448
20 feet. It was 19 feet
something. And you can see

02:01:19.508 --> 02:01:23.088
she's in the middle of
shedding. And the other

02:01:23.148 --> 02:01:27.028
interesting thing with her is that she
had blue eyes because she was in the

02:01:27.068 --> 02:01:30.828
middle of shedding. The scale
over their eyes turns blue right

02:01:30.868 --> 02:01:34.908
before it comes off. And so I've never
caught a blue-eyed anaconda before.

02:01:34.928 --> 02:01:38.148
But if you look at the size of my head and
the size of my hands, you start to imagine

02:01:39.108 --> 02:01:41.268
that thing's head is bigger
than a Great Dane's.

02:01:41.288 --> 02:01:45.188
It's huge. And the power on that—when

02:01:45.228 --> 02:01:49.208
we tried to lift her to measure her, we
wanted to bring her up out of the stream and

02:01:49.248 --> 02:01:52.058
get her over to the side so we can
straighten her out and measure her.

02:01:52.058 --> 02:01:55.618
We're just trying to take some simple
data points and then release her.

02:01:55.618 --> 02:01:59.560
And she, at one point, just decided to
flex her body, and you just see 10 people

02:01:59.740 --> 02:02:03.030
fly this way, and then she's flexing the
other way and 10 people fly this way.

02:02:03.030 --> 02:02:06.680
And every time that mouth would
open, she would try to... she'd just

02:02:06.780 --> 02:02:09.200
reach back and be like,
"Just let me do it."

02:02:09.210 --> 02:02:11.480
And you know that if she gets purchase—

02:02:11.540 --> 02:02:15.530
once they get purchase, they
wrap you so quick and they'll

02:02:15.560 --> 02:02:19.540
just crush the life out of you
like you're a bag of chips. And if

02:02:19.560 --> 02:02:23.450
you've ever seen a mouse in a mousetrap, when
the trap goes down and the eyes come out?

02:02:23.460 --> 02:02:27.360
And when snakes—anybody that's owned
snakes and fed them mice knows

02:02:27.380 --> 02:02:31.320
this—that sometimes if they catch it
right, the guts will either come out the

02:02:31.360 --> 02:02:34.480
back end or the front end. So, I'd imagine
that the same thing will happen with a

02:02:34.540 --> 02:02:39.220
snake that's that big. That's
bigger than I am around.

02:02:39.260 --> 02:02:43.140
- So, they have a process. When you say purchase,
they want a bite just to hold and then

02:02:43.200 --> 02:02:44.910
they— It's good. So...

02:02:44.920 --> 02:02:48.640
- But again, all she wants is
to be let go. In her defense,

02:02:48.700 --> 02:02:56.490
this massive snake—we named her Millie for
the data entry—she just wanted to go on

02:02:56.520 --> 02:03:01.010
her way down the stream. The
comments on this are hysterical.

02:03:01.020 --> 02:03:04.960
People are like, "This is the
worst example of white people shit

02:03:05.000 --> 02:03:08.720
I've ever seen." I mean, Snoop
Dogg shared it. So, one guy goes,

02:03:08.760 --> 02:03:12.800
he goes, "Congratulations, you've
touched enough grass. Go back inside."

02:03:14.320 --> 02:03:17.680
- Yeah, somebody said,
"Interesting use of free will."

02:03:18.720 --> 02:03:23.950
Yeah, and I saw Killpopper007 commented—

02:03:24.060 --> 02:03:26.350
and maybe you can tell
me if this is correct:

02:03:26.350 --> 02:03:30.290
"Anacondas are ambush predators.
If you approach them, they will

02:03:30.360 --> 02:03:34.320
usually try to flee and will not
register you as food. There's

02:03:34.380 --> 02:03:39.780
other reasons too." This is in response to
how Paul possibly didn't die from this.

02:03:39.900 --> 02:03:43.640
"There's other reasons too, but this
is the main reason. They're pretty

02:03:43.660 --> 02:03:46.620
much apex at that size,
so their fear isn't as

02:03:46.760 --> 02:03:52.620
prominent. He was calm, so the
snake was calm. It's insane to do

02:03:52.630 --> 02:03:56.180
and still risky, but he might
actually be the most qualified

02:03:56.240 --> 02:03:59.990
anaconda handler on
Planet Earth. Paul is one

02:04:00.060 --> 02:04:05.040
interesting cat." Hugging
emoji. Is that accurate?

02:04:05.109 --> 02:04:09.070
- Yes. At that size, they're apex,
so they're really not thinking

02:04:09.140 --> 02:04:11.640
about defense. They're
just like, "Get off me."

02:04:11.700 --> 02:04:15.630
If I was to hurt her—like if I
was to touch you in the arm with

02:04:15.630 --> 02:04:19.500
a needle—you'd react. If I was to
do anything that hurt her, which

02:04:19.580 --> 02:04:23.570
I'm not doing, she would turn around
and bite me to say, "Go away." But

02:04:23.580 --> 02:04:27.540
they also don't want to bite because their
recurved teeth make it very difficult to

02:04:27.620 --> 02:04:31.260
detach. And also, they're putting
their head at the source of the

02:04:31.340 --> 02:04:34.800
danger. It's not a good
calculation. And so these giants—

02:04:34.840 --> 02:04:39.220
and I've had the privilege of
interacting with four or five

02:04:40.020 --> 02:04:43.980
anacondas in the 20 to 26-foot
range—all of them have

02:04:44.020 --> 02:04:47.780
been very Leviathan-like.
And they just don't

02:04:47.820 --> 02:04:51.700
wanna move. They just
wanna keep going. And he's

02:04:51.720 --> 02:04:55.220
100% right on all of
that stuff. I've caught

02:04:55.540 --> 02:04:59.070
90-something anacondas at this
point, and many of them have been

02:04:59.100 --> 02:05:02.750
massive. Then there's the one that JJ and I didn't
get at the Floating Forest because it was bigger

02:05:02.780 --> 02:05:06.380
than— bigger than we could tackle,
bigger than my hands. I couldn't touch

02:05:06.420 --> 02:05:10.200
fingers. But every single one
of them has chosen flight

02:05:10.660 --> 02:05:14.320
over fight. Only the little
babies and the smaller

02:05:14.360 --> 02:05:18.300
males get snappy. They'll come back at you like
a normal snake, and if you grab their tail,

02:05:18.340 --> 02:05:20.160
they'll try and bite you and
then go. But these big females,

02:05:21.240 --> 02:05:25.200
you know, they're like dragons. They're
like these big, legendary things that live

02:05:25.240 --> 02:05:28.180
in swamps, and the only reason they've
gotten that big is because they have a

02:05:28.220 --> 02:05:32.060
reliable prey source in
a secluded place away

02:05:32.080 --> 02:05:35.900
from humans, and they've been there
for decades just pulling things

02:05:35.920 --> 02:05:39.429
down to hell and eating
them. And the other

02:05:39.500 --> 02:05:43.270
thing... I mean, look, I have a
team with me. You know? So...

02:05:43.270 --> 02:05:44.780
- So, there's people holding the—

02:05:44.800 --> 02:05:48.620
- Yeah. Let's be real here. I would never
do this. If I was out in the jungle

02:05:48.640 --> 02:05:52.500
by myself at night, doing
this would be suicide,

02:05:52.540 --> 02:05:56.340
100%, because for every second
that I'm going, "Oh, I'm in this

02:05:56.420 --> 02:06:01.920
water and she's over my neck," if JJ
wasn't there to jump in and unwrap her—

02:06:01.929 --> 02:06:03.620
...then I die. 100%.

02:06:03.630 --> 02:06:06.540
- Because she's continuously wrapping.

02:06:06.580 --> 02:06:12.209
- She's on her back saying, "Come in here,"

02:06:12.209 --> 02:06:16.000
"and let me arm bar you. Let me squeeze
the guts out of you." She's just

02:06:16.040 --> 02:06:17.330
going, "Let it happen."

02:06:17.399 --> 02:06:18.839
- And moving slowly.

02:06:18.920 --> 02:06:19.940
- Moving really slow—

02:06:20.160 --> 02:06:20.170
- Conjuring

02:06:20.170 --> 02:06:24.040
- with that assurance of power where she
doesn't need to try and tap you quick.

02:06:24.050 --> 02:06:25.580
She's going to get you eventually.

02:06:25.620 --> 02:06:28.500
- Although, to push back on something
you just said, having known you long

02:06:28.560 --> 02:06:33.480
enough, let's be honest. You're saying
I wouldn't be insane enough to do it.

02:06:33.560 --> 02:06:38.030
I think you would be. I mean, there's...

02:06:38.880 --> 02:06:43.480
There's a line of insanity, and
you, my friend, walk that line

02:06:45.240 --> 02:06:48.860
masterfully so far. I think

02:06:49.320 --> 02:06:53.140
when you're able to sense the
animal, whether it's crocodiles,

02:06:53.300 --> 02:06:58.600
caiman, or anacondas, and
maybe radiate a sense of calm—

02:07:00.900 --> 02:07:06.060
I've seen you be able to go
into some dangerous situations,

02:07:06.920 --> 02:07:10.580
and make it seem like it's not
dangerous at all. And maybe when you

02:07:10.600 --> 02:07:14.420
become one with the ecosystem, maybe

02:07:14.460 --> 02:07:16.720
you're not a threat to
it, and maybe that's why

02:07:17.540 --> 02:07:21.380
you can survive? I haven't been
able to make sense of it, really.

02:07:21.480 --> 02:07:27.780
- Look, I would say this. In the case of
elephants, if we ever end up in Africa

02:07:27.800 --> 02:07:31.740
together, I can get incredibly close
to elephants because I've spent enough

02:07:31.800 --> 02:07:37.960
time with them where, time with them
where, so far, it's always been a mock

02:07:38.040 --> 02:07:41.760
charge. And you can be one with the

02:07:41.820 --> 02:07:45.340
elephant and learn their
language enough that you

02:07:45.360 --> 02:07:49.170
respect their boundaries and
you also show them that, this

02:07:49.220 --> 02:07:53.180
better be serious because you're either going to
have to kill me, or just turn around and go back to

02:07:53.240 --> 02:07:57.200
eating. And you can have
that exchange with them.

02:07:57.240 --> 02:08:00.349
With smaller snakes, I'll be
careful. I can tell you with

02:08:00.400 --> 02:08:04.110
this that when you have both of
your hands around an anaconda's

02:08:04.140 --> 02:08:07.876
neck... I truly... I mean,
I've been known to surprise

02:08:07.916 --> 02:08:16.356
myself with the decisions I make, but
this alone would lead to death, 100%.

02:08:16.396 --> 02:08:20.176
It's like laying down in front of an 18-wheeler
with it in neutral. "It's going to roll

02:08:20.236 --> 02:08:23.875
over you." This is going to turn into

02:08:23.956 --> 02:08:27.896
anaconda handcuffs with this
thickness, and then that

02:08:27.916 --> 02:08:31.756
is going to wrap you with this thickness, and then
six more of those are going to go around your

02:08:31.776 --> 02:08:36.926
body and you will get squeezed
and you will turn into goop.

02:08:36.976 --> 02:08:40.726
Just like that guy said, she probably is in
defense mode and not food mode, so she'll

02:08:40.756 --> 02:08:46.565
probably just neutralize the
threat and then go back to sleep.

02:08:47.036 --> 02:08:51.136
- I have to ask you about the floating
forest. And you write about Santiago,

02:08:52.216 --> 02:08:56.176
once again, beautifully in the
book, of the time when he told

02:08:56.196 --> 02:09:00.156
you the stories and when your
mind and eyes were still fresh

02:09:00.216 --> 02:09:04.056
and maybe skeptical and
more leaning towards the

02:09:04.096 --> 02:09:07.136
Western world point of view
versus the jungle point of

02:09:07.176 --> 02:09:11.036
view. "Santiago's eyes were glowing
in the darkness. He watched

02:09:11.096 --> 02:09:14.656
the orange ember spark upward
to join the celestial river of

02:09:14.756 --> 02:09:18.696
stars that arched across the
night sky as if the memories

02:09:18.736 --> 02:09:22.496
were written there. He squinted,
his face as wrinkled and

02:09:22.556 --> 02:09:26.396
weathered as an old map of
the world. Vast experience

02:09:26.496 --> 02:09:30.176
whispered in the firelight, as
ephemeral as the breath that

02:09:30.236 --> 02:09:33.856
spoke the words, but powerful
enough to latch on and

02:09:33.976 --> 02:09:40.586
sink down into some deep part of me."
This is Pico saying, "Papa, tell me about

02:09:40.636 --> 02:09:44.516
the anaconda on the
blackwater stream." And,

02:09:44.596 --> 02:09:50.436
He tells a story of that, and he talks
about it being big and having horns.

02:09:50.516 --> 02:09:54.476
And you write once again
masterfully about you at that

02:09:54.536 --> 02:09:58.256
time having doubts. It
sounds like bullshit, but

02:09:58.316 --> 02:10:01.576
now more and more of the things
you've seen in the jungle

02:10:02.736 --> 02:10:10.096
and the things you sense you have not
seen yet, all of those stories seem to be

02:10:10.176 --> 02:10:14.046
true. The one he was referring
to was maybe 36 feet

02:10:14.176 --> 02:10:17.996
long, this big. He says that, "The

02:10:18.036 --> 02:10:21.956
floating forest is the place
you need to go, Gringo,

02:10:22.016 --> 02:10:28.396
if you want to be liberated of your doubts
and skepticism." So tell me about the

02:10:28.456 --> 02:10:31.996
anacondas you've encountered
in the floating forest.

02:10:32.016 --> 02:10:35.966
- Well, the thing he's describing there is
that he's saying they found an anaconda that

02:10:36.016 --> 02:10:37.806
had horns.

02:10:37.836 --> 02:10:41.796
And in that moment, we were all hanging out
by the side of the river and I said, "That's

02:10:41.856 --> 02:10:45.406
enough." I stood up. I was like, "Come
on, there's no anaconda that has horns."

02:10:45.436 --> 02:10:49.156
And if I've learned anything
in 20 years of living with the

02:10:49.176 --> 02:10:52.976
indigenous people in the Amazon, it's that
they're not wrong. You know, if they say

02:10:53.016 --> 02:10:55.356
there's a tribe of naked
people with arrows out there,

02:10:56.476 --> 02:10:59.996
they're right, they're
right. And they know what an

02:11:00.036 --> 02:11:03.006
anaconda looks like. So if he
says he saw an anaconda with

02:11:03.036 --> 02:11:09.516
horns, he saw something that ain't a
normal anaconda. And a smaller version of

02:11:09.556 --> 02:11:13.536
this played out recently where
one of the people that works

02:11:13.596 --> 02:11:17.236
at the tree house, he came
and he said, "I found a

02:11:17.296 --> 02:11:20.816
snake and it was in the water
tank." And he goes, "And it had

02:11:21.296 --> 02:11:23.056
green spikes on it." And I said,

02:11:24.136 --> 02:11:28.126
"There's no snake that has green spikes." I
said, "Congratulations, you're an idiot."

02:11:28.196 --> 02:11:29.336
I made fun of him.

02:11:29.346 --> 02:11:32.636
And I said, "I know all the snake species
that are here. None of them have spikes.

02:11:32.656 --> 02:11:36.556
There's no snake that has spikes coming off of
it." And he said, "No, it had long spikes."

02:11:36.596 --> 02:11:40.496
He said, "The snake is this big and had spikes this
long on it." And I said, "There's no snake with

02:11:40.596 --> 02:11:44.296
spikes." Until finally he
came and he got me in the

02:11:44.336 --> 02:11:48.196
night and he goes, "The snake with spikes is
there." And I said, "Well, I'll get out of bed

02:11:48.276 --> 02:11:51.885
for that. Let's go." And I said, "I
guarantee it's not gonna be there."

02:11:51.916 --> 02:11:55.816
And we got to the water tank and
I shined my flashlight down and

02:11:55.956 --> 02:11:59.736
sure as shit, there's a
snake in there and it's got

02:11:59.796 --> 02:12:03.756
thousands of green spikes coming off
of it. And I could see the snake head

02:12:05.536 --> 02:12:08.516
and then the spikes are coming
completely perpendicular out from its

02:12:08.556 --> 02:12:12.356
body. And for a second, I really was having
this out-of-body experience. And then the

02:12:12.396 --> 02:12:16.336
snake saw us, got scared
and swam, and all of the

02:12:16.356 --> 02:12:20.156
the spikes collapsed onto
its body and became smooth.

02:12:20.176 --> 02:12:24.075
And then I realized the snake had been living
in the stagnant water for a while and developed

02:12:24.116 --> 02:12:28.056
algae that was growing off of it.
So when it was sitting still, all

02:12:28.096 --> 02:12:31.076
the algae would settle out.

02:12:31.085 --> 02:12:35.036
And so if you look straight down on it,
it's a water snake that has algae growing

02:12:35.096 --> 02:12:39.696
on it. And so it does look like a
snake with spikes. He's not wrong.

02:12:39.736 --> 02:12:42.516
It was a water snake. It
was some sort of Helicops.

02:12:42.636 --> 02:12:44.706
But there's always an answer like that.

02:12:44.706 --> 02:12:45.166
- Amazing.

02:12:45.196 --> 02:12:48.936
- They're not wrong. So when they tell
you something like, "There's an

02:12:48.996 --> 02:12:51.916
anaconda with horns," and
multiple people have seen it—

02:12:52.216 --> 02:12:54.256
...you make an expedition there.

02:12:54.296 --> 02:12:58.196
If somebody said there's giant ground sloths in
this valley, I wouldn't be like, "They're extinct."

02:12:58.256 --> 02:13:02.116
I'd be like, "Where?" You start
to listen. I mean, after,

02:13:02.156 --> 02:13:05.836
after the tribe walked out of the
forest, you could tell me anything.

02:13:05.856 --> 02:13:09.496
That day, if a Tyrannosaurus rex walked out
behind them, I would've been like, "Makes

02:13:09.536 --> 02:13:10.166
sense."

02:13:10.176 --> 02:13:13.976
- Let's go to the floating forest. Do you
ever think about what creatures are in

02:13:14.056 --> 02:13:17.816
there? I just had a conversation with

02:13:17.856 --> 02:13:21.296
Michael Levin at Tufts
University. He's this biologist

02:13:21.656 --> 02:13:25.616
who creates biological life forms in the

02:13:25.696 --> 02:13:29.156
lab, but he also studies all
kinds of weird, what he calls

02:13:29.316 --> 02:13:33.076
unconventional intelligences
on Earth. And he speaks

02:13:33.156 --> 02:13:37.136
about that from a perspective
of just understanding the

02:13:37.176 --> 02:13:40.636
incredible intricacies and
weirdnesses of biological

02:13:40.736 --> 02:13:48.236
systems. So the soup of organisms that's
there in the floating forest is probably

02:13:48.276 --> 02:13:53.876
incredible. Do you ever think about
what kind of weirdness is there?

02:13:53.886 --> 02:14:00.376
- Yeah. Along with giant snakes,
there are animals existing in

02:14:01.176 --> 02:14:05.136
an ecosystem that's isolated,
right? And so the tepuis...

02:14:05.176 --> 02:14:08.856
In the movie Up, those Venezuelan
cliff jungles with the straight walls,

02:14:09.056 --> 02:14:12.888
like Angel Falls? Up there you
have this allopatric speciation

02:14:12.928 --> 02:14:18.338
occurring where these isolated communities
are departing from whatever's down there.

02:14:18.448 --> 02:14:22.368
So on the floating forest, you have
this very unique ecosystem where

02:14:23.188 --> 02:14:27.068
animals are living on grassy islands
and in the tops of palm trees.

02:14:27.078 --> 02:14:32.068
In that nightmare soup that exists
beneath the rafts, there are

02:14:32.388 --> 02:14:36.168
probably insects and, I mean,
I've seen lizards there that we

02:14:36.188 --> 02:14:40.148
have been unable to identify.
There are things there in the...

02:14:40.228 --> 02:14:43.768
I can't imagine the...

02:14:43.808 --> 02:14:47.668
decay is probably not happening. There's
not a lot of oxygen in that water.

02:14:47.748 --> 02:14:51.338
I've brought a few scientists there
and they've all just been like,

02:14:51.338 --> 02:14:52.508
"This is... this is..." you know.

02:14:52.548 --> 02:14:53.108
- Yeah. How do you even

02:14:53.128 --> 02:14:56.738
- "How did this form?" We've brought hydrologists
there and they're like, "How the hell did this

02:14:56.948 --> 02:15:04.408
thing form?" And then trying to study what
creatures live under that is amazing.

02:15:04.448 --> 02:15:08.128
- But the big anacondas, it's
interesting because they

02:15:08.188 --> 02:15:12.448
truly are the apex, so they're
unbothered. They're not really using

02:15:12.548 --> 02:15:13.948
their power for anything.

02:15:14.028 --> 02:15:16.348
- No, and I'm sure if I bit her,
she'd turn around and kill me.

02:15:17.048 --> 02:15:20.498
- Yeah, but in a bored kind of
way. Like, it wouldn't even...

02:15:20.508 --> 02:15:22.148
It would just slowly kill you.

02:15:22.168 --> 02:15:27.388
- I wonder though, once she killed
you, if she'd just be like-

02:15:27.408 --> 02:15:28.248
- Just take a bite?

02:15:28.548 --> 02:15:30.948
- I mean, would she bite?
They swallow, right?

02:15:30.988 --> 02:15:30.998
- Well-

02:15:30.998 --> 02:15:34.868
- Once you collapse your shoulders,
it's like if you killed

02:15:34.928 --> 02:15:38.468
a perfectly good hamburger and it was
like in your hands dead, you'd be like-

02:15:38.888 --> 02:15:41.358
"Maybe I'll try it."

02:15:41.568 --> 02:15:43.078
- I mean, they need the calories.

02:15:43.108 --> 02:15:45.668
- Yeah, and then take a six-month nap.

02:15:47.388 --> 02:15:51.408
- Yeah. They're truly incredible,
majestic creatures.

02:15:51.448 --> 02:15:58.148
- Yeah, I love this picture.
Just, again, look at the size.

02:15:58.188 --> 02:16:02.168
I want you one day to feel
them. And again, the wild

02:16:02.208 --> 02:16:05.768
ones are not like the captive ones,
which are soft from sitting in a cage.

02:16:05.788 --> 02:16:11.708
These guys have been flexing every day.
It's like you're hitting steel cables.

02:16:11.748 --> 02:16:12.098
It's just wild.

02:16:12.098 --> 02:16:15.928
- And even if it's just being chill, you
can probably get a hint of the power

02:16:15.968 --> 02:16:18.318
it's capable of, right?

02:16:18.348 --> 02:16:22.098
- The one good thing about those really big
ones is that when they do strike, it's like

02:16:22.168 --> 02:16:26.068
it's like being in a fight with
a big fat guy. It's like that,

02:16:26.108 --> 02:16:28.428
that haymaker comes from way
back here and you're like-

02:16:28.438 --> 02:16:32.288
..."Oh, good." You're like, "I'm gonna
duck." And you get down. Because

02:16:32.308 --> 02:16:36.318
they open their mouth and
they start accelerating.

02:16:37.108 --> 02:16:40.928
And it's pretty easy to
either get out of the way or,

02:16:40.968 --> 02:16:43.168
you know, catch it before it hits you.

02:16:43.268 --> 02:16:47.148
...usually. Again, if you ever mess that
up, just like the haymaker from the

02:16:47.168 --> 02:16:49.368
big guy, it's over.

02:16:49.448 --> 02:16:53.428
- Your level of knowledge and comfort
with snakes is incredible. I think they

02:16:53.438 --> 02:16:53.558
- Play with them a lot.

02:16:53.558 --> 02:16:57.488
- ...sense that. I mean, I've seen you with
snakes and they must sense it, because

02:16:57.528 --> 02:17:04.968
they must sense in you the
camaraderie. You have a way of

02:17:05.128 --> 02:17:08.968
speaking to animals and about
animals like there's zero danger.

02:17:09.088 --> 02:17:13.028
Well, from my outsider
perspective, it seems like a

02:17:13.168 --> 02:17:18.407
lot of them are full of danger if you're
not communicating to them correctly.

02:17:18.448 --> 02:17:22.228
- With snakes, I think it's more of a

02:17:24.088 --> 02:17:27.988
highway analogy: it's dangerous,
but you can drive safely.

02:17:28.008 --> 02:17:31.928
I know what I'm doing, so if I'm working
with a snake that can't envenomate

02:17:31.968 --> 02:17:35.888
me and is small, I can allow it to
freak out. And then if I can get it

02:17:35.928 --> 02:17:39.907
into my hands and it goes, "Ooh, it's
nice in here." And of course, like

02:17:39.948 --> 02:17:43.918
you said, I'm not scared. They are very
sensitive to that, so he's going, "Okay, this

02:17:43.948 --> 02:17:47.827
isn't so bad." You can chill him
out. But I don't think snakes

02:17:47.888 --> 02:17:51.558
have any camaraderie. I
think that whales, monkeys,

02:17:51.668 --> 02:17:55.608
elephants, I think they can sense. They can
say, "Okay, this person's trying to help"

02:17:55.648 --> 02:17:59.488
to get me out of this net. I'm
gonna relax and not kill them."

02:17:59.528 --> 02:18:00.868
In those cases, you have that dynamic.

02:18:00.948 --> 02:18:04.248
- Speaking of an animal that does
have camaraderie, there's this

02:18:04.258 --> 02:18:08.118
incredible video on your Instagram
that people should go watch where

02:18:08.168 --> 02:18:12.088
incredible video where this spider monkey
was drowning and you jumped in to rescue it.

02:18:12.168 --> 02:18:16.038
- Sure. So we're coming down river.
It's seven o'clock in the morning,

02:18:16.088 --> 02:18:19.978
so I'm cold. I'm sitting on
the boat and I'm wearing

02:18:20.008 --> 02:18:23.767
whatever. JJ's like, "Look,
spider monkey." And I go, "Great,

02:18:23.838 --> 02:18:27.628
spider monkey in the river." That's
normal. But JJ's like, "No, she's

02:18:27.668 --> 02:18:30.677
having trouble." And I was like,
"Why? They swim all the time."

02:18:30.688 --> 02:18:34.168
And he goes, "You should help."
So the boat comes around.

02:18:34.208 --> 02:18:38.138
Then sure enough, what you can't see in the video is
that the river was so full that there were these little

02:18:38.168 --> 02:18:41.498
whirlpools and currents, and she was trying to get
to the side. And again, all the animal rights people

02:18:41.528 --> 02:18:45.348
are very quick to be like,

02:18:45.368 --> 02:18:49.208
"Let nature take its course. Let the monkey drown."
Or, "She doesn't need help. You're interfering."

02:18:49.248 --> 02:18:52.268
Sure, sure, sure. If you were
actually there, you would know

02:18:52.327 --> 02:18:56.308
that she did need help and she was
drowning. Her head kept going under.

02:18:56.368 --> 02:19:00.288
And so I saw that JJ was
right. And so we pull around.

02:19:00.327 --> 02:19:04.288
I took off whatever I could in the
moment, jumped in with the paddle—

02:19:04.368 --> 02:19:07.968
because, now, here again, I trust monkeys,

02:19:08.368 --> 02:19:16.148
but I don't want her to bite me. She is going to be
scared, so I thought, there's two ways I can do this.

02:19:16.208 --> 02:19:21.948
I can grab her by the neck and the tail and take her
out of the river, which is going to be scary for her.

02:19:23.028 --> 02:19:26.968
Instead I thought, "I know spider monkeys
so well. I've raised so many of them."

02:19:27.048 --> 02:19:30.998
And when you raise them, they curl
up to your neck and they'll...

02:19:31.028 --> 02:19:34.868
If you have an orphan spider monkey whose mother
got shot by poachers and you're taking care of her

02:19:34.928 --> 02:19:38.358
before we bring them to the
animal rehabilitation experts,

02:19:39.308 --> 02:19:42.398
they'll curl up on your neck and
they'll go, "Oh, oh, oh, oh,"

02:19:43.288 --> 02:19:49.418
and they'll just talk to you in your ear. So I feel
like I know a little bit of broken spider monkey.

02:19:50.248 --> 02:19:52.648
I pull up next to her and
I give her the paddle.

02:19:52.658 --> 02:19:55.908
We're in this rushing river moving
at 10 miles an hour downstream,

02:19:56.728 --> 02:20:00.528
and I try to give her the
paddle and she smacks it away.

02:20:00.628 --> 02:20:04.538
She was like, "No, get away from me." Then she keeps
swimming, goes under again, and I give her the paddle again.

02:20:04.628 --> 02:20:08.588
She puts a hand around the paddle, and that
moment that you paused on, she looked back at me.

02:20:08.628 --> 02:20:16.276
She looked at me like—yeah, right there.
She registered like, "Oh, this is

02:20:16.316 --> 02:20:18.325
another animal with a face."

02:20:18.576 --> 02:20:22.476
- For people just listening, you need to go watch the
video. You guys are just looking at each other,

02:20:22.516 --> 02:20:26.036
and she's looking right
at you. It's so cool.

02:20:26.096 --> 02:20:30.036
- She looked right at me, but then she went,
"No." She was like, "Whatever you are, no."

02:20:30.116 --> 02:20:33.796
She was like, "I'd rather die in the
river." She was so scared and drowning,

02:20:33.976 --> 02:20:36.796
and she looked at me and got
scared and jumped back in.

02:20:36.816 --> 02:20:40.596
Then I lifted her up and I went, "Oh, oh, oh,
oh," and I started talking in spider monkey.

02:20:40.656 --> 02:20:47.725
And she just... then, in the next moment,
you see it. She just goes, "Sure."

02:20:48.636 --> 02:20:52.616
And she wraps her tail... you see her
tail is around the edge of the paddle.

02:20:52.626 --> 02:20:56.566
She puts her hand around it, and then I lifted her. Because
I'm taller than she is, I lifted her out of the river.

02:20:56.636 --> 02:21:02.326
So now, instead of manhandling her like
a raccoon you're catching by the neck

02:21:02.326 --> 02:21:06.116
she's holding on in her spider
monkey way to the paddle, and she

02:21:06.156 --> 02:21:10.136
and she looks back over her shoulder. I'm sitting there
going, "Oh, oh, oh, oh," talking to her in spider monkey.

02:21:10.216 --> 02:21:13.666
And she looks at me, and
you hear her. She goes...

02:21:13.716 --> 02:21:17.476
I can't do the sound she makes,
but she does this, "Whoa!"

02:21:17.576 --> 02:21:19.946
spider monkey sound like, "Guh!"

02:21:19.956 --> 02:21:23.736
And she goes, "Fine." And then she's looking
off the front end of the paddle as she's

02:21:23.776 --> 02:21:26.386
looking at the jungle, and she looks back at
me and she's like... You could just tell.

02:21:26.396 --> 02:21:28.256
She's like, "I have no
idea what's happening."

02:21:28.276 --> 02:21:32.156
But she accepted the help. And
the difference is, it's because I

02:21:32.216 --> 02:21:35.956
spoke her language in this case. And
I know that would be one of those

02:21:35.976 --> 02:21:39.626
stories that people would nail me on every
time if it wasn't on camera. You can

02:21:39.656 --> 02:21:45.486
see the moment that she makes direct
eye contact with me and goes, "Okay."

02:21:45.516 --> 02:21:48.626
And then as soon as we get to shore, she jumps
off and runs off into the forest, but it was-

02:21:48.626 --> 02:21:52.496
- It's so... I mean, just watching the
video, it's so amazing. She's looking at

02:21:52.576 --> 02:21:58.296
you. Like, real... You can see
that there's an actual connection.

02:21:58.316 --> 02:22:01.176
It's... that there's like communication,
like a social... You know, the way

02:22:01.736 --> 02:22:05.156
humans, when you're maybe

02:22:05.596 --> 02:22:08.486
saving a human being that's
drowning or something like this.

02:22:08.496 --> 02:22:12.456
There's that connection. It was
beautiful to see, man. And then I read

02:22:12.516 --> 02:22:14.826
a little bit that spider monkeys have...

02:22:15.956 --> 02:22:19.396
they're very intelligent, but they're
especially socially intelligent. So they

02:22:19.476 --> 02:22:23.336
have social connections with each
other. So they understand what

02:22:23.396 --> 02:22:27.296
that means. They understand what
another entity means. So you

02:22:27.516 --> 02:22:31.416
speaking it in a broken language, probably

02:22:32.376 --> 02:22:37.016
is really important and a powerful
way to indicate that, "Wow, you're

02:22:38.176 --> 02:22:42.556
in network." Like a foreigner, but like

02:22:42.596 --> 02:22:45.066
- It's like you're in a foreign country
and someone goes, "Helping, helping."

02:22:45.216 --> 02:22:45.676
- Yeah, exactly.

02:22:45.685 --> 02:22:49.566
- Like, "Helping." And you go, "Okay,
sure." Like, you know, "You're not

02:22:49.596 --> 02:22:51.866
robbing me, you're helping," right?

02:22:51.866 --> 02:22:55.696
But no, they're incredibly... And I'm telling
you, I've had orphan spider monkeys so many

02:22:55.736 --> 02:23:01.026
times. And they wrap their tail
around your neck and they hug you.

02:23:01.036 --> 02:23:05.016
And you realize that connection that they
have with their mothers when they hold onto

02:23:05.036 --> 02:23:08.936
them in the canopy... When the
loggers shoot the mother and then I'm

02:23:08.976 --> 02:23:11.576
taking care of this baby,
they hold onto you.

02:23:11.586 --> 02:23:16.396
And they need that love and that
connection more than they need food.

02:23:16.416 --> 02:23:21.526
If you put food or you put warmth of
a body, they'll choose the connection

02:23:21.876 --> 02:23:22.956
over the sustenance.

02:23:22.976 --> 02:23:26.296
- Yeah, they really value the
touching, that connection.

02:23:26.356 --> 02:23:27.916
- Very tactile. They're very loving.

02:23:27.936 --> 02:23:31.656
They wrap their long spider
monkey arms around each other.

02:23:31.676 --> 02:23:35.596
They're very much like us.
They hold their babies.

02:23:35.656 --> 02:23:39.476
When it rains, spider monkeys
will get together and huddle up.

02:23:39.536 --> 02:23:43.386
They'll pull leaves down and all
huddle up together. When it's cold-

02:23:43.436 --> 02:23:45.736
they get close. It's very cute.

02:23:45.776 --> 02:23:49.146
- Yeah, I mean, they're distant relatives,
but that's true for a lot of our

02:23:49.216 --> 02:23:52.916
relatives. The apes, the chimps,
all of them, they have this

02:23:53.016 --> 02:23:57.096
intricate... They're different. Sometimes
more violent, sometimes more loving.

02:23:57.116 --> 02:23:59.846
But social interactions,
it's cool that way.

02:23:59.896 --> 02:24:03.776
- Yeah, I mean, you expect it from
them. They're practically us.

02:24:03.796 --> 02:24:07.716
To me, it's when other animals
show. The times that I've

02:24:07.756 --> 02:24:11.716
been on a trail and a jaguar has
walked by and just been like, "'Sup?"

02:24:11.996 --> 02:24:15.726
Keep walking. And it's like, "It's
kind of cool of you not to eat me."

02:24:15.756 --> 02:24:16.866
"I appreciate it."

02:24:16.916 --> 02:24:18.556
- Has that happened to you?

02:24:18.576 --> 02:24:21.366
- Yeah. I thought somebody was walking on
the trail. I was doing a camera trap.

02:24:21.376 --> 02:24:24.906
And I put my finger up and I was gonna
go, "Could you walk any louder?"

02:24:24.976 --> 02:24:25.146
- Oh, yeah.

02:24:25.156 --> 02:24:29.035
- I'm crouched because I was
doing a camera trap. A jaguar

02:24:29.056 --> 02:24:32.736
walked by and he literally was just
like shoom, shoom, kicking leaves,

02:24:32.836 --> 02:24:36.476
just having fun, mouth open. And
he just walked by, looked at me,

02:24:36.516 --> 02:24:39.605
and went, "'Sup?" Never broke stride.

02:24:39.605 --> 02:24:43.596
Dead-ass eye contact with the bottom
teeth out and that jaguar look

02:24:43.636 --> 02:24:49.596
of just like, "Hey." I was like, "Okay."
Now I'm going to have a full meltdown.

02:24:49.616 --> 02:24:50.816
Your system, you start sweating.

02:24:50.836 --> 02:24:54.776
You're like, "Whoa." Because
they're also so beautiful.

02:24:54.816 --> 02:24:58.566
When you see a jaguar, it's bright
yellow and the teeth and the muscles...

02:24:58.616 --> 02:25:00.816
It's... You know...

02:25:00.886 --> 02:25:04.716
- What do you think you communicated to
the jaguar that it didn't kill you?

02:25:04.776 --> 02:25:08.576
- No, nothing. The jaguar was making
the decisions. I didn't do anything.

02:25:08.636 --> 02:25:11.156
saved my life. He was
just going somewhere.

02:25:11.216 --> 02:25:16.716
And because he's the king
there, he just went, "Uh."

02:25:16.756 --> 02:25:18.596
- Yeah, probably also not threatened.

02:25:18.636 --> 02:25:18.846
- Not threatened at all.

02:25:18.846 --> 02:25:22.796
- I think there is something to you.
You're just taking for granted

02:25:22.856 --> 02:25:25.276
the things that you're
putting out into the world.

02:25:25.316 --> 02:25:31.086
You're probably radiating calm.
Or not calm- but non-threat.

02:25:31.116 --> 02:25:34.856
- Certainly non-threat. I also smell
like an animal when I'm in the

02:25:34.916 --> 02:25:38.876
jungle, right? I shower in the
river. I don't use deodorant

02:25:38.976 --> 02:25:42.876
or shampoo or any of that
stuff. So I don't smell...

02:25:42.936 --> 02:25:46.496
Imagine to animals that have a
smell that's four times as good as

02:25:46.556 --> 02:25:49.726
that's four times as good as ours,
just your deodorant, your conditioner—

02:25:49.726 --> 02:25:54.636
... just whatever other products,
the detergent on your clothes...

02:25:54.656 --> 02:25:59.046
We smell like Times Square. We
smell like a fire alarm to them.

02:25:59.056 --> 02:26:03.036
They're like, "What is this thing?
It smells very foreign and scary."

02:26:03.096 --> 02:26:07.036
Everything's scary. Speaking of scary,
the jaguar was kind of friendly.

02:26:07.076 --> 02:26:10.816
He was like, "'Sup?" It's almost
like he'd seen me before.

02:26:10.936 --> 02:26:14.808
He was like, "Oh, it's just
you." The one time I stood—

02:26:14.888 --> 02:26:18.788
on the forest floor in India with
a wild tiger and nobody else,

02:26:18.848 --> 02:26:22.728
the thing the tiger did that was so
unnerving... And again, a tiger's back

02:26:22.768 --> 02:26:26.488
is... they're so much bigger than
you think. It's like four jaguars.

02:26:26.588 --> 02:26:28.808
They're so big.

02:26:29.768 --> 02:26:33.648
She wouldn't look at me, and it was
terrifying. She would look over there,

02:26:33.728 --> 02:26:37.528
she would look like this,
she would look like that,

02:26:37.908 --> 02:26:41.888
and never eye contact. It was like,
"You're as important to me as a stick."

02:26:41.928 --> 02:26:45.848
When you see two fighters square
up, it's all about the eye contact.

02:26:45.928 --> 02:26:49.668
But you look through a person; you
pretend they're not even there.

02:26:49.728 --> 02:26:53.528
person. You pretend they're
not even there. That-

02:26:53.608 --> 02:26:57.458
That tiger insulted me on such
a profound and disarming level

02:26:57.688 --> 02:27:01.448
that I never forgot it. It was like,
"You matter as much as a sparrow."

02:27:01.608 --> 02:27:05.568
"You're just not one of the
things that I care about."

02:27:05.648 --> 02:27:08.448
She just was looking around
and carried on doing it.

02:27:09.488 --> 02:27:13.128
She was like, "I'm gonna walk
this way." And I was just like,

02:27:13.148 --> 02:27:15.468
"Holy shit, I'm gonna run."

02:27:15.508 --> 02:27:19.488
It's just profound insignificance
from this god of an animal

02:27:19.528 --> 02:27:23.428
with paws the size of dinner plates. I
was like, "Man, if she does look at me,

02:27:23.448 --> 02:27:26.658
if she looks at me, I'm gonna probably..."

02:27:27.208 --> 02:27:27.868
- That's the end.

02:27:27.878 --> 02:27:28.488
- You know, that's the end.

02:27:28.588 --> 02:27:34.238
- Yeah, it shows how much more powerful
she is. That's probably the most

02:27:35.368 --> 02:27:37.918
terrifying animal on earth. Tigers—

02:27:37.928 --> 02:27:40.568
- The rock-paper-scissors of land predators.

02:27:40.648 --> 02:27:44.207
I think the polar bear and tiger
have to be the most scary.

02:27:44.308 --> 02:27:45.648
- Yeah, polar bears.

02:27:45.688 --> 02:27:46.688
- Polar bear's pretty scary.

02:27:46.698 --> 02:27:47.488
- Yeah, you don't mess with a polar bear.

02:27:47.528 --> 02:27:52.668
- I don't think they're as fast as tigers,
but you're not going fast on the ice.

02:27:52.688 --> 02:27:56.628
With a tiger, you can't outrun it. If
you climb a tree, they climb better.

02:27:56.668 --> 02:28:00.548
If you get in a car, they could smash the
door. If a tiger decides it wants you,

02:28:00.588 --> 02:28:04.478
pretty much nothing... Even if you had a
gun, even if you had a nine millimeter,

02:28:04.548 --> 02:28:08.248
it isn't going to stop
a tiger that wants you.

02:28:08.308 --> 02:28:12.288
- In the jungle, have you ever felt
in danger? Putting humans aside,

02:28:12.328 --> 02:28:16.128
were there animals...?

02:28:16.188 --> 02:28:19.238
You've talked about how humans
are really the source of danger.

02:28:19.238 --> 02:28:21.848
...how humans, they're
the source of danger.

02:28:21.888 --> 02:28:25.008
Is there... You often
speak about animals as

02:28:26.288 --> 02:28:29.018
a, you know, source of beauty and wonder—

02:28:29.028 --> 02:28:32.608
...and elegance and grace and
all these things which they

02:28:32.708 --> 02:28:38.888
are. But I'm sure you've felt danger.

02:28:38.948 --> 02:28:43.848
- Yeah. I mean, I'm very aware that a hornet's
nest can kill you. They'll kill you.

02:28:43.868 --> 02:28:45.108
- Oh, so the little guys.

02:28:45.118 --> 02:28:47.608
- The little guys suck. You know, the—

02:28:47.668 --> 02:28:49.437
I always think like when we
were going through the jungle—

02:28:49.508 --> 02:28:53.268
...one machete whack, and again, people
don't realize how dense it is. You try to

02:28:53.308 --> 02:28:57.168
run, you get hung up on vines, you trip,
you fall onto one of those trees with the

02:28:57.188 --> 02:29:01.138
black spikes. And then while you're laying there
dealing with all that, they're just stinging

02:29:01.208 --> 02:29:01.997
you and your body—

02:29:01.997 --> 02:29:05.148
...goes into anaphylactic shock and
you die instantly. It's like you

02:29:05.208 --> 02:29:08.268
just... That can very
quickly just take you out.

02:29:08.308 --> 02:29:12.268
- You're right. I mean, speaking of spikes,
the biggest danger is not even the

02:29:12.368 --> 02:29:15.968
spikes. The spikes just, 'cause it creates
open wounds and then that can lead

02:29:16.088 --> 02:29:16.418
slowly—

02:29:16.428 --> 02:29:16.868
- Infection

02:29:16.888 --> 02:29:20.528
- ...to infection. So it's really
that—that is the biggest danger.

02:29:20.588 --> 02:29:24.018
- Yeah. In the Amazon, I've never heard of a

02:29:24.208 --> 02:29:27.438
human-directed violent jaguar in
our region. They just don't attack

02:29:27.468 --> 02:29:31.638
people. I'd say mosquitoes are
the thing that come after you.

02:29:31.668 --> 02:29:35.518
The snakes just want to be left
alone. Even the venomous snakes.

02:29:35.568 --> 02:29:39.488
Again, I grabbed an 11-foot
bushmaster by the tail and he turned

02:29:39.528 --> 02:29:43.348
around, he lifted up to about this
high off the ground. And if you

02:29:43.388 --> 02:29:47.328
could translate what he said,
it was just, "Don't make me

02:29:47.368 --> 02:29:50.428
do it." It just said,
you know, "Make my day."

02:29:50.488 --> 02:29:53.128
- See, but that's the thing.
You speak snake language.

02:29:53.138 --> 02:29:54.298
- And then I put the tail down.

02:29:54.308 --> 02:29:54.608
- You speak snake.

02:29:54.618 --> 02:29:58.557
- I went, "Okay." I was
sufficiently scared. So the

02:29:58.628 --> 02:30:01.648
problem happens when you don't know
what you're doing. I'll give you—

02:30:01.658 --> 02:30:05.608
...an example. You want a dangerous animal
story, I'll give you one. I was walking one

02:30:05.668 --> 02:30:08.497
time and I was trying to be responsible. It
always happens when I'm trying to be responsible—

02:30:08.497 --> 02:30:12.488
...I get into trouble. Trying
to be safe, and you fall down.

02:30:13.108 --> 02:30:16.338
I'm on the side of the stream and there's
elephants on the other side of the...

02:30:16.348 --> 02:30:19.988
I'm in India. There's a deep,
like a 12-foot thing, and then a

02:30:20.068 --> 02:30:23.768
stream and then on the other side there's elephants.
And I'm walking and I'm like, "I'm gonna sit in a

02:30:23.828 --> 02:30:27.468
tree and I'm gonna enjoy these elephants.
I'm gonna make notes in my book like Jane

02:30:27.528 --> 02:30:34.407
Goodall." Then I came up against a cement
wall, and it was the back of a male

02:30:34.488 --> 02:30:38.468
elephant. And in India, it's a male
elephant that's been harassed and had

02:30:38.508 --> 02:30:42.428
fire thrown at it and God knows what
else. And he... And if I translate

02:30:42.448 --> 02:30:46.328
what he said, he turned around and he just went,
"What the fuck?" He just looked at me like,

02:30:46.408 --> 02:30:52.588
how dare you? And then just... smacks
apart the tree, turns around, and then

02:30:52.628 --> 02:30:56.218
that elephant was trying to kill
me. That was not a mock charge.

02:30:56.248 --> 02:31:00.128
I threw off my backpack, zigzagged
through the woods. He broke

02:31:00.168 --> 02:31:04.098
apart trees. If I had a GoPro on
my back to show you what I saw,

02:31:04.188 --> 02:31:08.028
just the shrapnel and devastation
of this thing just bashing through

02:31:08.088 --> 02:31:12.068
trees. Every bush that I
encounter is a possible trip.

02:31:12.108 --> 02:31:16.048
Every vine is a possible hang-up.
And if they get you, he'll step

02:31:16.088 --> 02:31:19.958
on you and crush you. So I
threw myself off the edge of

02:31:19.988 --> 02:31:23.268
this cliff, rolled down into the stream,
and the elephant got to the edge and

02:31:24.768 --> 02:31:27.468
almost fell on me. He got to
the edge and did one of these,

02:31:28.848 --> 02:31:31.308
and then came back down on his hind feet.

02:31:31.328 --> 02:31:35.208
Picked up a stick, threw it at
me. And the stick just smacked

02:31:35.228 --> 02:31:40.038
down next to me in the stream. I remember
I gave him the finger because I was alive.

02:31:40.108 --> 02:31:42.148
And then he just stormed
off into the jungle.

02:31:42.158 --> 02:31:43.168
- I mean, there's nothing like an elephant.

02:31:43.188 --> 02:31:44.778
- There's nothing like an
elephant anywhere. There's a...

02:31:45.628 --> 02:31:49.528
I loved listening. I was so
excited when I put on your podcast

02:31:49.568 --> 02:31:50.417
with the dinosaur guy—

02:31:50.417 --> 02:31:54.388
because he was like, "When a baby
is born, it learns, you know,

02:31:54.448 --> 02:31:57.968
elephant, giraffe, T-Rex."

02:31:58.008 --> 02:32:01.888
And I was like, "Holy shit."
Along with like banana, water,

02:32:02.088 --> 02:32:07.068
sky is blue. Somehow these are initial
things in your first few months on Earth—

02:32:07.108 --> 02:32:10.998
these are the characters you're introduced
to. How the hell did T-Rex get there?

02:32:11.088 --> 02:32:12.778
They don't even exist anymore.

02:32:12.778 --> 02:32:16.748
It was just such a fun... I could
hear you smiling through the mic,

02:32:16.788 --> 02:32:18.928
and I was like, "Oh, this
is gonna be a good one."

02:32:19.036 --> 02:32:22.016
- Yeah. I mean, the dinosaur
world is incredible—

02:32:22.056 --> 02:32:22.066
- It's wild.

02:32:22.066 --> 02:32:27.276
- but the fact that you have such a
predator evolve with such a gigantic jaw,

02:32:27.796 --> 02:32:30.476
so much destructive power, is weird.

02:32:30.496 --> 02:32:34.156
- And then he broke my heart because he
was talking about how the T-Rex and

02:32:34.236 --> 02:32:37.876
Stegosaurus... he's like, "All the
books have them together," and then,

02:32:37.886 --> 02:32:39.466
"They're nowhere near each other."

02:32:39.466 --> 02:32:42.546
"They did not exist at the
same time," and I was like...

02:32:42.916 --> 02:32:44.476
- I want them to battle with each other.

02:32:44.516 --> 02:32:45.936
- Yes.

02:32:46.076 --> 02:32:49.816
- Speaking of elephants, I feel like we'll
be up for an adventure at some point.

02:32:49.896 --> 02:32:58.876
After all this chaos is over, you think
back in the jungle? Africa? India?

02:32:58.956 --> 02:33:02.796
- I think I would love to show you
a herd of truly wild elephants

02:33:02.996 --> 02:33:06.756
in the African jungle. I think that us

02:33:06.816 --> 02:33:12.096
going on a boat trip through
the Amazon, not a hiking one—

02:33:12.116 --> 02:33:16.006
where we're going through areas where
you can get permits to go through

02:33:16.096 --> 02:33:19.366
where no one's allowed to go.
They're completely protected areas,

02:33:19.476 --> 02:33:23.416
and you can just go for a week through
areas where the animals have no idea

02:33:23.475 --> 02:33:28.976
what a human is. So you can move through
it, and it'd be a little bit more of an

02:33:29.056 --> 02:33:32.756
enjoyable experience, not a survival
situation. And go with J.J. in a boat

02:33:32.796 --> 02:33:36.756
and just travel through the Amazon.
"Hey, maybe we protect this river."

02:33:36.796 --> 02:33:43.596
And then the river's mapped from north
to south, and we just raft down with

02:33:43.636 --> 02:33:45.256
boat support, you know?

02:33:45.296 --> 02:33:49.236
- It's really incredible to see how it's
all connected. I mean, the river,

02:33:49.306 --> 02:33:52.266
it's the thread that connects the
whole story. And so it's nice

02:33:52.266 --> 02:33:55.956
to see how it all is connected.
And that's why us starting in the

02:33:55.996 --> 02:33:59.276
mountains is also really nice to
see, you know, where it begins.

02:33:59.296 --> 02:34:01.706
But it keeps going. The story keeps going.

02:34:01.776 --> 02:34:06.686
- It keeps going. We did start in the
mountains. An epic first day together.

02:34:07.976 --> 02:34:11.666
- And hopefully, people get a
chance to see that video.

02:34:11.776 --> 02:34:15.916
So I gotta ask you about the
writing. I mentioned you're

02:34:15.936 --> 02:34:19.776
an incredible writer. What's
your writing process like for

02:34:19.836 --> 02:34:26.995
this book, Jungle Keeper, for The Mother
God, and for future books you're writing?

02:34:27.976 --> 02:34:31.846
Are you like a Stephen King? Do you go
to some dark places in the basement?

02:34:31.916 --> 02:34:35.656
Do you write every single day?

02:34:36.256 --> 02:34:41.366
Do you take little notes? Like, your
notebook has a bunch of doodles

02:34:41.366 --> 02:34:44.316
and a bunch of writing. Like,
what's your process like?

02:34:44.396 --> 02:34:48.016
- I try to journal every day
for a number of reasons.

02:34:48.076 --> 02:34:52.056
It's accountability. It helps me keep track...
It's fun to see your hopes and dreams.

02:34:52.096 --> 02:34:56.056
It's fun to record the mundane
moments that we all forget about,

02:34:56.136 --> 02:34:59.816
and that might be, like, cooking
in the kitchen with your mother.

02:34:59.856 --> 02:35:03.836
That might be a fun walk you had with
your dog. Like, little things that you

02:35:03.916 --> 02:35:07.445
think you're going to remember, but you just
don't. And so I have piles of notebooks.

02:35:07.476 --> 02:35:11.316
I have just piles and piles
of notebooks in my room.

02:35:11.996 --> 02:35:19.096
And when something happens, I write it down.
If a cool story happens, I will write it down,

02:35:19.176 --> 02:35:22.656
story happens, I will write
it down, or if I find a

02:35:23.136 --> 02:35:27.056
leaf from an extinct tree
I will make an etching

02:35:27.076 --> 02:35:31.686
Anything that happens that I
find remarkable in any way,

02:35:33.636 --> 02:35:37.576
either for my own personal
memory or for writing,

02:35:37.616 --> 02:35:41.396
I'll write it down. And then when I go

02:35:41.476 --> 02:35:45.056
back to it later, A, I have a very
good memory, and B, the facts are

02:35:45.096 --> 02:35:48.736
there. And so when something happens
like you rescue a spider monkey

02:35:48.796 --> 02:35:52.496
or something happens that's remarkable in

02:35:52.536 --> 02:35:56.516
life—you get to spend time with
someone that you haven't in a

02:35:56.576 --> 02:36:00.526
long time and you get that feeling of like, "Oh,
that's why I'm such good friends with them."

02:36:00.556 --> 02:36:03.746
You write these things
down, and then it's always

02:36:03.776 --> 02:36:07.626
there. And so I feel like whenever I
don't journal that I'm missing out

02:36:07.736 --> 02:36:11.596
on keeping my life and my memories.

02:36:11.736 --> 02:36:15.716
So yeah. I don't do the... That
Stephen King quote about how

02:36:16.136 --> 02:36:20.016
"Amateurs wait for inspiration, and
the professionals, we go to work every

02:36:20.156 --> 02:36:24.536
day." And he's like, "Ten pages a day,"
or whatever it is. I don't do that.

02:36:26.156 --> 02:36:29.576
I write when I feel like it. And I like

02:36:29.676 --> 02:36:33.416
to... You know, I'll start thinking,
"Oh, this is a perfect way

02:36:33.456 --> 02:36:37.206
to start this scene," because
the moment this happened, I

02:36:37.216 --> 02:36:41.116
felt so intensely. And if we bring
people in and out, I'll just be in a car

02:36:41.156 --> 02:36:44.996
or boat or something, and I'll just start
thinking about it and I'll go, "This is..."

02:36:45.036 --> 02:36:45.876
Just the thing is, you gotta carpe diem.

02:36:46.896 --> 02:36:50.716
Then I'll go, "Okay, where did that happen
again?" And I'll go to that page. And I'll go,

02:36:50.726 --> 02:36:54.136
"Okay, so what exactly happened?"
Then you get the laptop, and yeah.

02:36:54.156 --> 02:36:57.366
So it's brain to paper to
laptop, always paper in between.

02:36:57.376 --> 02:37:00.596
- Well, how do you go from
disparate notes to the final

02:37:00.656 --> 02:37:06.276
thing? Because it's difficult to
convey the experience through words,

02:37:07.576 --> 02:37:13.936
and you do that well. So is this like...
Do you edit a lot? Do you iterate?

02:37:13.996 --> 02:37:17.776
- That's where Stephen King was right.
Because I look at writing like

02:37:17.836 --> 02:37:21.016
sculpting. You- you have
to have something to

02:37:21.136 --> 02:37:23.946
sculpt. And so when you're thinking of a

02:37:24.076 --> 02:37:27.856
story... Again, a lot of...
I mean, I love listening to

02:37:27.936 --> 02:37:31.896
great storytellers. And I actually love listening to
bad stories, just like I like watching bad movies to

02:37:31.936 --> 02:37:35.836
see what they did wrong. When you listen to
someone that starts a story and they have you

02:37:35.916 --> 02:37:39.836
hooked from the second they start, and then
you're like, "Wait, but how did that happen?

02:37:39.856 --> 02:37:43.576
And why was that happening? What happened next?"
And they keep you going and they drop the

02:37:43.616 --> 02:37:47.396
information perfectly. And so every now
and then, you figure that out in that

02:37:47.416 --> 02:37:51.056
moment of inspiration. So then I
have my facts written down here.

02:37:51.116 --> 02:37:55.066
And then I'll do an outline on a page
or something. But then I have to get

02:37:55.096 --> 02:38:01.756
it all out of me with a pen. Then I can
move to... I'll almost close my eyes.

02:38:01.796 --> 02:38:05.466
I'll almost just close my eyes and write the
story out. I just need to... You're making

02:38:05.556 --> 02:38:09.486
the... You're literally making your
clay, and so it's like you make the

02:38:09.616 --> 02:38:14.776
shape of the thing before you... And
then editing is giving it details.

02:38:14.836 --> 02:38:16.276
- So you do take passes like—

02:38:16.556 --> 02:38:22.256
- Oh, my God, yes. I mean, dozens.
That's where writing sucks.

02:38:22.276 --> 02:38:25.836
When you're finishing a book—and I'll
never do that again. So what I'm doing now

02:38:25.916 --> 02:38:30.004
is... this last book, there's
so much that it covered.

02:38:30.014 --> 02:38:33.864
And I was in the jungle, and it'd be like
hiking for ten hours a day, you know,

02:38:34.204 --> 02:38:37.954
dealing with narcotraffickers, and
then I'd have to edit at night.

02:38:37.964 --> 02:38:40.994
It was like, "This is no way to
live." So now what I'm doing is

02:38:42.604 --> 02:38:46.304
I'm writing chapters as I feel like
writing chapters. When something

02:38:46.364 --> 02:38:50.204
something remarkable happens, I go,
"This is going to be its own chapter."

02:38:50.264 --> 02:38:54.244
I write it, edit it, and then I
send it to my sister who's an

02:38:54.284 --> 02:38:58.244
expert editor and has lived
more in literature than

02:38:58.284 --> 02:39:02.134
most people live in real life. She'll
let me know if it's good or bad,

02:39:02.164 --> 02:39:05.844
if it needs to be tweaked. When I get
it back from her, it's marked up.

02:39:05.924 --> 02:39:08.704
And now what I'm going to do
is I'm just going to put those

02:39:08.784 --> 02:39:12.673
aside. And then, the next time I
want to write a book, it's not

02:39:12.784 --> 02:39:18.204
starting from scratch on 300,000
words; it's just here, and it's ready.

02:39:19.224 --> 02:39:20.104
Much easier.

02:39:20.124 --> 02:39:23.124
- What kind of books do you think
you might write in the future?

02:39:23.184 --> 02:39:26.984
- Well, there's Mother of God, and
now Jungle Keeper. And then I'm

02:39:27.044 --> 02:39:32.324
already working on Endgame. Because
there is so much that has happened. I

02:39:32.384 --> 02:39:36.144
think I told you when you were
there, but right before you

02:39:36.184 --> 02:39:40.084
came, me and JJ went to the
back end, behind our river—

02:39:40.094 --> 02:39:43.704
to this horrible part of the
Amazon that's 10 times more

02:39:43.824 --> 02:39:47.214
lawless than where we are. Instead
of no people, there are people.

02:39:48.204 --> 02:39:52.084
If you want to talk about Amazonian
No Country for Old Men, it's the oil

02:39:52.184 --> 02:39:56.064
companies, the missionaries,
and the newly contacted tribes.

02:39:56.104 --> 02:39:59.624
There's a people called the
Nahua, and they were recently

02:39:59.744 --> 02:40:03.704
contacted and ripped out of the
forest. They're standing there

02:40:03.724 --> 02:40:07.464
with their little bows and
arrows. They're tiny people. The—

02:40:07.524 --> 02:40:11.264
the normales are tall. The Nahua
are small. And we just saw

02:40:11.424 --> 02:40:16.324
brutality in this horrific...
It's like Sicario. It's just

02:40:17.564 --> 02:40:21.044
absolute lawlessness. I remember the
moment JJ looked at me and said,

02:40:22.604 --> 02:40:26.084
and we both think of ourselves as
tough, I think, until we get in

02:40:26.124 --> 02:40:29.154
these situations. And he looked
at me and went, "We're not safe."

02:40:30.064 --> 02:40:33.704
And we looked at the people around
us at this side of the river

02:40:33.844 --> 02:40:36.793
port, eight days up, and you
could tell everyone looking at

02:40:36.864 --> 02:40:40.844
us was making a calculation
about how inconvenient it

02:40:40.864 --> 02:40:49.204
would be to kill us. They were like:
camera, watch, clothing, backpack.

02:40:49.884 --> 02:40:52.774
They were like, "That's a nice
backpack." You could tell they

02:40:52.804 --> 02:40:56.374
were just shopping. And JJ
and me were like, "We're

02:40:56.424 --> 02:40:59.584
gonna..." "Where are we putting
the tent tonight?" "We're not

02:40:59.624 --> 02:41:03.594
staying here." Then I was like,
"Well, maybe we should stay."

02:41:03.604 --> 02:41:07.404
And then one of the little Nahua
people came over to JJ asking for

02:41:07.424 --> 02:41:11.594
food, and he made the mistake of
explaining money. They'd never

02:41:11.604 --> 02:41:15.464
had money before. He gave them a
couple coins and said, "If you

02:41:15.524 --> 02:41:19.384
go over there, that man will sell
you something and you can eat."

02:41:19.424 --> 02:41:22.904
The guy was like, "Bow and arrow?"
JJ said, "No, give him this and

02:41:22.984 --> 02:41:26.804
he'll give you food," and it
worked. Then JJ got swarmed by

02:41:27.284 --> 02:41:31.254
60 of these little tribals with
bows and arrows, hands out. JJ was

02:41:31.284 --> 02:41:35.074
running with all these half-naked
people behind him. That—

02:41:35.144 --> 02:41:39.064
that whole saga right there
is like... That chapter's

02:41:39.084 --> 02:41:40.694
gonna be called "River
of the Dolphin Fuckers"

02:41:42.384 --> 02:41:44.704
'cause everyone we met on
the river kept telling us,

02:41:45.904 --> 02:41:49.724
I'd have my camera with me and I'd go,

02:41:49.804 --> 02:41:53.104
"Are there dolphins here?" And
they'd go, "Yeah, there's dolphins.

02:41:53.144 --> 02:41:56.474
And if you fuck one, be careful
'cause they'll pull you under."

02:41:57.104 --> 02:41:59.214
I went, "Okay, weirdo," to the first guy.

02:41:59.214 --> 02:42:03.204
And then we got to like eight hours further
upriver, met the next guy and I had my camera out,

02:42:03.264 --> 02:42:07.184
and I'm like, "Hey, are there any dolphins here?"
And he goes, "Yeah. If you fuck any, be careful."

02:42:07.204 --> 02:42:08.924
He's like, "'Cause they'll grab on
and pull you under." And I was like,

02:42:09.824 --> 02:42:14.334
"What?" And then four more people told me
the same thing. So I was like, "Okay."

02:42:14.344 --> 02:42:18.594
- The lesson we learned in the jungle:
horned anacondas, believe 'em.

02:42:18.604 --> 02:42:22.364
- Believe 'em. On that river, they were
all trying to be good Samaritans and

02:42:22.444 --> 02:42:27.284
warn me about the clear and present
dangers involved with amorous dolphin

02:42:27.304 --> 02:42:27.984
encounters.

02:42:28.044 --> 02:42:32.124
- So stylistically, I mean, that
is a bit Cormac McCarthy.

02:42:32.244 --> 02:42:33.664
- Ooh, he would've loved it.

02:42:33.704 --> 02:42:40.424
- There are writers you draw inspiration from
like that. I mean, you're very close to him—

02:42:40.444 --> 02:42:40.894
- It's too big of a compliment.

02:42:40.924 --> 02:42:45.264
- You plug in every once in a while. You
jump around stylistically, actually.

02:42:45.504 --> 02:42:49.464
- I do. It depends, because
sometimes I want to sink in and

02:42:49.544 --> 02:42:53.404
flex a little bit, which I don't think
people really enjoy, but I enjoy it.

02:42:53.444 --> 02:42:57.734
You know, talk about the... Just
use all those flowery words—

02:42:57.734 --> 02:43:01.524
and make these beautiful metaphors.
But what I'm finding more and more is

02:43:01.584 --> 02:43:08.484
that modern readers aren't really looking
for that. They want an easy read.

02:43:08.544 --> 02:43:12.484
And for my style of storytelling,
people really tend to

02:43:12.524 --> 02:43:15.494
thank me for more of an
Anthony Bourdain style,

02:43:16.324 --> 02:43:20.224
where you're like, "So we found ourselves
on the side of this river and we knew we

02:43:20.244 --> 02:43:24.024
were in danger. The reason we were in danger..."
And you just start telling the story.

02:43:24.064 --> 02:43:27.984
Forget the... Maybe once every two pages
you can throw in one of those beautiful

02:43:28.044 --> 02:43:30.624
little zingers, but nobody
wants to watch you flex.

02:43:30.664 --> 02:43:34.544
- But also sometimes you go even more
than... I don't think Anthony Bourdain did

02:43:35.204 --> 02:43:41.384
like Hemingway-like minimal, like—
word, period— word, like that.

02:43:41.404 --> 02:43:45.404
That's another way to flex that I really
like that you do sometimes is just—

02:43:45.544 --> 02:43:49.504
less, and just power in the spacing,

02:43:49.544 --> 02:43:52.584
the silences. The unsaid
is what does the driving.

02:43:53.344 --> 02:43:56.384
- I mean, that's what's so arresting.
You read like For Whom the Bell

02:43:56.484 --> 02:44:00.204
Tolls. And, you know, "The air
was crisp, and the water was

02:44:00.264 --> 02:44:04.204
sweet, and the wine was good,
and the afternoon was warm."

02:44:04.244 --> 02:44:08.164
And you're like, "I know what that's like."
These are not complicated sentences,

02:44:08.184 --> 02:44:12.104
but when he puts them together into a
paragraph, you go, "Oh, yeah. I want

02:44:12.124 --> 02:44:15.864
to drink wine out of leather and
lay by the side of that stream."

02:44:15.904 --> 02:44:21.384
It sounds so beautiful. And so sometimes,
you know, I mean, just look at that.

02:44:21.624 --> 02:44:23.654
Look at that fire cracking
on the horizon there.

02:44:23.654 --> 02:44:27.024
Sometimes the only way is
just these simple statements.

02:44:27.976 --> 02:44:31.725
- Writing's beautiful. I love writing, I
love reading it. Have you interacted with

02:44:31.836 --> 02:44:39.436
LLMs much? You know, AI systems? ChatGPT?
There's a bit of a scary and a sad

02:44:39.576 --> 02:44:45.166
aspect to the fact that they can
generate language extremely well.

02:44:45.196 --> 02:44:49.976
But something is missing, and it's
very hard to put your finger on it.

02:44:50.456 --> 02:44:56.156
- My question to you is: I can
pick out with stunning accuracy

02:44:57.356 --> 02:45:01.286
when someone sends me a message and
they've passed it through ChatGPT—

02:45:02.276 --> 02:45:06.226
I know. Somehow I could
tell, and I don't know how,

02:45:06.256 --> 02:45:10.016
but I could tell. It's one of
those things like with the images,

02:45:10.036 --> 02:45:13.476
where we're at the point where
we can't tell anymore, almost.

02:45:13.556 --> 02:45:17.226
I don't know if that's going to go away,
or if, like you said, there's something...

02:45:17.236 --> 02:45:21.476
Like, one of the things that F.
Scott Fitzgerald does so much

02:45:22.556 --> 02:45:29.536
is he describes these incredibly human
moments with such crystalline accuracy

02:45:29.606 --> 02:45:33.436
that you go, "It must have
taken you a month. You

02:45:33.476 --> 02:45:37.006
must have studied life
so much to be able to

02:45:37.036 --> 02:45:40.976
string those words together."
I think in a book he writes

02:45:41.056 --> 02:45:45.036
about someone screaming with such
abandonment that at the highest register,

02:45:45.056 --> 02:45:48.876
her voice wobbled and cracked. And you're
like, "Oh my God, I know that sound."

02:45:48.916 --> 02:45:55.356
And I wonder if... because
you can say, for example,

02:45:56.236 --> 02:46:00.216
"Write me The Jungle Book, but make it
sound like Cormac McCarthy wrote it."

02:46:00.236 --> 02:46:04.516
And it'll be like, "The jungle was dark
and stern, and the boy was..." You know?

02:46:04.536 --> 02:46:08.496
It'll do it, and it's amazing.
But my question to you is,

02:46:08.536 --> 02:46:12.296
what are we picking up on in something
as simple as a text message?

02:46:12.336 --> 02:46:16.896
- It is very difficult to define. But
it's important to keep thinking about,

02:46:17.056 --> 02:46:19.336
because: what makes us human?

02:46:19.456 --> 02:46:23.436
- You reassured me recently
because I called you and I said,

02:46:23.456 --> 02:46:27.346
of the jungle and all anybody
wants to talk about is AI."

02:46:27.416 --> 02:46:31.176
It's like people are walking themselves
into the Matrix and asking to

02:46:31.196 --> 02:46:34.526
be hooked. You know, everyone's
just obsessed with this topic.

02:46:34.576 --> 02:46:38.915
And you were like, "Man,
human art and human

02:46:40.196 --> 02:46:44.036
literature is going to actually become so
valuable as this other thing happens."

02:46:44.116 --> 02:46:48.066
other thing happens." And I expected
the opposite answer. I thought you were

02:46:48.076 --> 02:46:51.916
gonna be like, "Yeah, man, this really is.
Everything's gonna change." And you were like,

02:46:51.936 --> 02:46:57.126
"Man, like, real artists are going
to become more appreciated."

02:46:57.156 --> 02:47:02.406
- As more and more compelling and
effective bots appear on the internet—

02:47:02.406 --> 02:47:04.376
... we're going to value
that less and less, I think.

02:47:04.456 --> 02:47:07.916
And we're going to value human
interaction more and more.

02:47:07.976 --> 02:47:13.656
So, you know, artists showing art at
galleries versus on the internet—

02:47:13.936 --> 02:47:17.756
... meeting in person. And,
actually, it's going to

02:47:17.916 --> 02:47:21.896
force people to be more authentic and
real and raw with each other. That's

02:47:21.936 --> 02:47:25.356
going to be the valuable resource.

02:47:25.396 --> 02:47:29.076
- I mean, I think already, AI
aside, I think that in today's

02:47:29.156 --> 02:47:32.556
world, everyone's so... I
mean, movies have become so

02:47:32.596 --> 02:47:36.526
polished. Like, there's no weird quirky
stuff. There's no risky stuff anymore.

02:47:36.536 --> 02:47:41.766
It's all very, very curated. I've
almost stopped watching movies.

02:47:41.776 --> 02:47:45.676
And I used to love movies. But it's fun

02:47:45.696 --> 02:47:49.836
when they take risks, when
they're messy, when they're real.

02:47:49.876 --> 02:47:53.476
- I think Hollywood, the Hollywood stars,
the Hollywood movie-making process

02:47:54.016 --> 02:47:57.996
has become less and less popular
because of that. So I can't

02:47:58.036 --> 02:47:59.936
wait for movies to be reinvented-

02:47:59.996 --> 02:48:00.286
- Oh, I can't wait.

02:48:00.286 --> 02:48:03.856
- ... for independent film. Just raw,
edgy, dangerous, all that kind of stuff.

02:48:03.866 --> 02:48:07.686
- And all the actors we like are in TV
shows on various streaming platforms.

02:48:07.696 --> 02:48:09.606
It's like they've all just gone home.

02:48:09.616 --> 02:48:13.116
Like, they're not there. I was
literally like, "Man, I miss movies.

02:48:13.156 --> 02:48:17.036
What happened to movies? I'm re-watching
all the old movies that I like."

02:48:17.136 --> 02:48:21.126
And I was like, "Where is everybody?"

02:48:21.156 --> 02:48:23.036
What are they doing? It's
like they all have a TV

02:48:24.136 --> 02:48:28.236
series on Hulu or something,
you know? It's like, "Fuck."

02:48:28.256 --> 02:48:32.436
- Yeah. I think it'll come. The
raw, the dangerous, the edgy.

02:48:32.476 --> 02:48:36.336
- What we just described is almost perfect...
There's a scene in Dead Poets Society where Robin

02:48:36.376 --> 02:48:40.256
Williams makes them open their books.
And the first page of the poetry book

02:48:40.316 --> 02:48:44.236
is like, "How do you identify a good poem?"
He's like, "A good poem can be..." And he makes

02:48:44.296 --> 02:48:48.166
a graph. And he's like, "By the subject of
the poem, and then the accuracy with which

02:48:48.176 --> 02:48:51.976
it is described, you can tell whether
or not it's a good poem." The whole

02:48:51.996 --> 02:48:55.046
class is sitting there bored. And he's
like, "Now rip that page out of your

02:48:55.116 --> 02:48:59.056
book." And they rip the page out. And then
he's like, "Now stand up." And he's like,

02:48:59.066 --> 02:49:02.916
"Now describe something." And he makes
them bleat it and scream it. And

02:49:02.976 --> 02:49:06.796
it's almost exactly what we're describing.
It's like, yeah, you can turn it into a

02:49:06.836 --> 02:49:09.936
graph if you need to, but it's
something way messier than that.

02:49:10.896 --> 02:49:16.816
- Yeah. And Robin Williams, the person— ...
is a perfect example of a complicated,

02:49:16.996 --> 02:49:24.906
beautiful human. I miss him. And whenever
I see clips of him come up, it's just-

02:49:24.976 --> 02:49:29.456
I still to this day can't make
sense that a person like that can

02:49:30.736 --> 02:49:35.696
take their own life. Somebody who's
brought so much joy to the world.

02:49:37.556 --> 02:49:41.496
It scares me, man. It scares
me. I'm scared of my own mind

02:49:41.556 --> 02:49:47.066
in that way, you know? That he
could be at the top of the world...

02:49:47.066 --> 02:49:50.216
- But he had an illness.

02:49:50.996 --> 02:49:57.256
- Yeah, that's what I understand.
Dude, life is a rollercoaster.

02:49:57.276 --> 02:49:57.536
- I'm telling you.

02:49:57.556 --> 02:49:58.806
- And you're living through it.

02:49:58.856 --> 02:50:02.696
- As scary as that is... Since you
mentioned Robin Williams, I'll give you

02:50:02.756 --> 02:50:06.746
this. My very close friend
Gleb, he has a story.

02:50:06.776 --> 02:50:10.306
He was in New York City as a kid and
he saw Robin Williams walking down the

02:50:10.396 --> 02:50:14.296
street. And he went up to him
and went, "Oh my God, it's Robin

02:50:14.356 --> 02:50:17.836
Williams." And Robin was like, "Yeah." And he goes,
"Can I have an autograph?" He goes, "Do you have any

02:50:17.916 --> 02:50:21.706
paper?" And my friend was
like, "No, I'm eleven." And

02:50:21.756 --> 02:50:25.056
Robin Williams was like,
"Go get some paper."

02:50:25.336 --> 02:50:29.246
His manager was with him and he was like, "Robin,
we don't have time. We gotta get up there."

02:50:29.276 --> 02:50:32.116
And he was like, "Hold on. I told
the kid I'd give him a thing.

02:50:32.156 --> 02:50:36.024
He'll be back." And my friend heard this
as he's thinking, "Just please stay,"

02:50:36.044 --> 02:50:39.954
his whole life depended on this thing.

02:50:39.964 --> 02:50:43.884
And he ran into a diner,
grabbed a napkin, ran back

02:50:43.924 --> 02:50:47.724
out into the street. It took him a few minutes,
and Robin Williams was still sitting there.

02:50:47.984 --> 02:50:50.654
This irate manager was there,
being like, "Come on, let's go."

02:50:51.663 --> 02:50:52.864
Robin had waited there and

02:50:53.724 --> 02:50:59.984
signed the napkin for him, and actually
did it with a smile and a wink, you know.

02:51:00.044 --> 02:51:03.844
- Yeah, man. You can bring a lot of
joy to the world. Never forget

02:51:03.884 --> 02:51:07.464
that. All those little
interactions. I love it. I love it.

02:51:07.483 --> 02:51:11.024
- That was another one of Jane Goodall's
amazing quotes that I couldn't

02:51:11.064 --> 02:51:14.844
reproduce, but it's that you
don't realize the degree to which

02:51:15.844 --> 02:51:18.104
the things you do each day matter-

02:51:18.204 --> 02:51:21.204
...even if it's just to the people
around you. And it's like you

02:51:21.924 --> 02:51:25.904
are, to the people around you,
their entire life experience-

02:51:26.024 --> 02:51:30.384
...if they're your kids, your parents,
your partner. So yeah, the things you do.

02:51:31.624 --> 02:51:35.583
And if you can manage to put
that extra energy where you

02:51:35.604 --> 02:51:39.594
put a little magic on it, where it is
fun. You show up home with something, you

02:51:39.644 --> 02:51:43.583
know, play with the kids in a way that
surprises them. I had a good friend of

02:51:43.624 --> 02:51:47.583
mine, Vinnie. I called him and
said, "What are you doing?" He

02:51:47.604 --> 02:51:51.454
said, "Oh, I have a whole plan set
up. It's supposed to be really good

02:51:51.544 --> 02:51:55.514
stars tonight. I'm putting
my daughter to bed."

02:51:55.524 --> 02:51:59.484
He goes, "I'm gonna wake her up in the middle
of the night. I'm gonna have a candle."

02:51:59.503 --> 02:52:03.354
"I'm gonna take her up to the roof
to go stargazing." He's like, "But I

02:52:03.384 --> 02:52:07.264
want her to sleep. Remember when you
were a kid and you would wake up?"

02:52:07.384 --> 02:52:11.014
He was curating a magical
experience for her to see the

02:52:11.163 --> 02:52:15.024
stars, and like, making warm
tea and all this. Like,

02:52:15.064 --> 02:52:17.104
man, you can just make it so great.

02:52:18.224 --> 02:52:20.854
- Jane Goodall's the
reason you met this guy.

02:52:20.864 --> 02:52:21.364
- That's right.

02:52:21.444 --> 02:52:25.404
- You've continuously spoken
really highly of him, and he

02:52:25.464 --> 02:52:31.184
gave me this book that he has recently
written, Echoes from Eden. Signed it.

02:52:31.243 --> 02:52:35.163
- Yeah. Dax, A, saved my
life, and B, is the example

02:52:35.224 --> 02:52:38.804
of what everybody wishes.
Dax made an amazing

02:52:38.884 --> 02:52:43.033
company, amassed an amazing fortune, and
then said, "I'm gonna use it for good."

02:52:43.083 --> 02:52:46.924
- He's given a lot of resources, a lot of

02:52:46.964 --> 02:52:50.484
love, a lot of effort to
helping the Amazon rain

02:52:50.524 --> 02:52:53.833
forest and the environment in general.

02:52:53.924 --> 02:52:58.864
He's one of the only guys I know
who has a sexier beard than you.

02:52:58.944 --> 02:53:01.144
- Yeah, he's got me beat big time.

02:53:01.264 --> 02:53:05.253
- He wrote, "Thank you, brother, for your
love of the wild. This book is about

02:53:05.284 --> 02:53:08.844
the heroes fighting on the front
line for nature. Together we can

02:53:08.884 --> 02:53:14.624
protect Earth's last wild
places. Speak soon, Dax."

02:53:14.663 --> 02:53:18.524
- He supported all these
initiatives. He went to the Amazon

02:53:18.564 --> 02:53:22.484
with Jane. He supported Junglekeepers
and Sea Shepherd. And so

02:53:22.544 --> 02:53:26.424
he really went out and said, "Okay, what are
the environmental projects that are doing the

02:53:26.484 --> 02:53:30.424
most good? And where do I want to put my
resources?" It's like everyone always

02:53:30.484 --> 02:53:33.944
whines about that. "How come these
guys don't..." And it's like he

02:53:33.984 --> 02:53:37.944
did, and he got a lot done.
Then he went and visited all

02:53:37.964 --> 02:53:41.743
those projects: sea turtles and Indonesian

02:53:41.784 --> 02:53:45.594
orangutans and working with
Jane. And so then that

02:53:45.604 --> 02:53:49.583
book is sort of a state of the
union on where conservation is at.

02:53:49.624 --> 02:53:53.064
There's a lot of knowledge about how the
different strategies... It's so different

02:53:53.104 --> 02:53:56.644
protecting sea turtle eggs versus
trying to save a river in the Amazon

02:53:56.724 --> 02:54:00.624
versus Jane's global message of hope.

02:54:00.644 --> 02:54:04.583
And then he has a guy in there who's
trying to save a specific part

02:54:04.624 --> 02:54:07.503
of Sumatra, and it's just amazing stuff.

02:54:07.544 --> 02:54:08.484
- The Congo.

02:54:08.503 --> 02:54:11.874
- The Congo. And then he actually took
the time to go to these places and

02:54:12.424 --> 02:54:14.464
see the operations on the ground.

02:54:14.564 --> 02:54:16.243
- And are you still working with him?

02:54:16.304 --> 02:54:22.163
- Yeah. Well, that's sort
of the... The way it

02:54:22.204 --> 02:54:24.243
happened in my life was, the one time I

02:54:25.384 --> 02:54:29.333
quit conservation was right around the
time COVID hit. I was going through

02:54:29.364 --> 02:54:40.184
a divorce, I'm 32 years old, and I had no
job, no nothing. JJ's mom had COVID. Don

02:54:40.224 --> 02:54:43.924
Ignacio the shaman had COVID. Pico's
leg was coming off. Nothing was

02:54:43.964 --> 02:54:47.294
working. Nobody could go anywhere.
And I called Mohsin and I

02:54:47.344 --> 02:54:51.304
was like, "I quit." I was like,
"We're never going back to

02:54:51.344 --> 02:54:55.314
the jungle." The loggers just went
out and were tearing down everything.

02:54:55.323 --> 02:54:59.264
I just said, "I got nothing."
And in the absolute

02:54:59.384 --> 02:55:02.924
black depression, I called him and
I said, "I quit. I'm gonna go get a

02:55:02.964 --> 02:55:06.944
job. I guess I'm just..." You
know, "I guess I've been like

02:55:07.003 --> 02:55:09.784
jungle Peter Pan and it's time to grow

02:55:09.844 --> 02:55:13.684
up." And I was really embarrassed
at the time that I did

02:55:13.743 --> 02:55:17.364
that. And then I spent like four days just

02:55:17.524 --> 02:55:21.304
laying in bed, with no idea what
to do. The only thing I can do is

02:55:21.364 --> 02:55:25.204
this. And I had talked
to Dax months earlier,

02:55:25.243 --> 02:55:29.054
told him my plan for protecting the river, for
making a ranger team, and he'd been looking

02:55:29.124 --> 02:55:32.413
over the budgets and spreadsheets
and seeing if this was real.

02:55:32.464 --> 02:55:34.204
He was still forming
Age of Union. And then

02:55:35.884 --> 02:55:39.724
four days after I quit, the phone
rings and it's Dax. And he goes,

02:55:39.743 --> 02:55:43.624
"Hey, I looked over the budget. I'd
like to make a 10-year commitment

02:55:43.684 --> 02:55:47.604
to Jungle Keepers. Let's go." He had
no idea what I was going through,

02:55:47.663 --> 02:55:50.554
and he was just like,
"Let's go." I was like,

02:55:51.604 --> 02:55:55.524
going from that depressed to
that inspired in a single

02:55:55.564 --> 02:55:57.493
conversation... You could
get the bends from that.

02:55:57.493 --> 02:56:00.924
- Yeah, and it's not just the money- ...
it's that somebody believes in you.

02:56:01.003 --> 02:56:04.743
- No, it's that he believes in
us, that we can... Money, you

02:56:04.784 --> 02:56:08.604
know, that money means tuna
cans and gasoline and being

02:56:08.663 --> 02:56:12.493
able to buy shoes, you know? We never

02:56:12.604 --> 02:56:16.384
had those things before. We were just
living in the jungle watching our bodies

02:56:16.444 --> 02:56:20.404
decay. And he was like, "No, I know
how to run a company, and I can tell

02:56:20.424 --> 02:56:22.384
what you guys need to run
an organization." And he

02:56:24.264 --> 02:56:26.844
did that and then has stuck by us. And

02:56:26.904 --> 02:56:31.094
he came not that long ago
to the Amazon, and we...

02:56:31.144 --> 02:56:34.083
And we took him around, and he
just looked around and went,

02:56:34.243 --> 02:56:38.174
"I've never seen people..." Because he
said, "You guys remind me of a startup."

02:56:38.184 --> 02:56:42.970
He said, "You're a mess." And that
was right before Stephan had come

02:56:43.000 --> 02:56:46.779
And so now, he's seeing ranger teams and
boats going up and down. And we have

02:56:46.839 --> 02:56:50.800
complex systems and a donor program,
and all these things are working well.

02:56:50.859 --> 02:56:54.419
We're making progress and we have annual
reports and all this data. And he's like,

02:56:54.460 --> 02:56:58.369
"Yo, you know, people have
donor fatigue, where they

02:56:58.400 --> 02:57:02.349
donate money and don't know where
it's going." And he goes, "Here,

02:57:02.359 --> 02:57:06.160
they can see what's happening."
So having someone like

02:57:06.199 --> 02:57:13.289
Dax in your corner is a miracle, really.
In the book, it's gonna sound... A lot of

02:57:13.300 --> 02:57:17.229
the things that happened to me in my life
sound like bad writing. You know in movies,

02:57:17.300 --> 02:57:21.199
they have a gun to their head, and you go,
"They're not getting out of this one." And then

02:57:21.220 --> 02:57:24.800
someone bursts through the door and saves
them. That's just happened too many times to

02:57:24.820 --> 02:57:30.269
me. It sounds like bad writing,
but it's a really good life.

02:57:31.140 --> 02:57:36.560
- Since you mentioned Stephan one
more time- ... one of my happiest

02:57:36.679 --> 02:57:42.660
moments in life, and I had many
in the jungle with you, is just

02:57:43.220 --> 02:57:47.650
talking late at night after
ayahuasca, funny enough-

02:57:47.650 --> 02:57:51.449
... chatting with Stephan and Dan
and you, giggling and talking about

02:57:51.539 --> 02:57:55.320
life and everything. And Dan is a guy I
have to give a shout-out to. You should

02:57:55.419 --> 02:58:00.179
follow him on Instagram, Life with Dan.
He's an incredible wildlife photographer.

02:58:00.189 --> 02:58:05.119
I've seen him; he's worked
quite a lot with you.

02:58:05.130 --> 02:58:09.039
He has a love of nature, a
love of the wilderness, a love

02:58:09.119 --> 02:58:15.990
of beauty, and is extremely good at
taking pictures, but just goes to the

02:58:16.080 --> 02:58:19.500
edges with you. He's
the only guy I've seen

02:58:20.199 --> 02:58:23.599
with the two giant cameras able
to follow you into the darkness.

02:58:24.500 --> 02:58:27.890
- Well, Dan... First of all, that
picture I showed you where I'm in the

02:58:28.000 --> 02:58:31.619
tree, because I told you the story
about with JJ where I climbed the giant

02:58:31.679 --> 02:58:35.550
tree. Well, this is years later,
I climbed it with Dan. Dan was

02:58:35.580 --> 02:58:38.080
there, and so he flew the drone
up and got me in the tree.

02:58:38.099 --> 02:58:42.060
But what Dan's a really good example of is,
like you were saying, what would you say

02:58:42.099 --> 02:58:49.439
to the kids? It's like Dan listened to our
talk, our first podcast, was living in

02:58:49.500 --> 02:58:53.438
Singapore, and he's
like a young filmmaker.

02:58:53.539 --> 02:58:57.039
Again, just get out there.
He signed himself up

02:58:57.740 --> 02:59:01.679
to come on a Tamandua Expedition with my
company, and he showed up on the thing. And

02:59:01.759 --> 02:59:05.560
sure enough, their boat broke down,
and I was off doing Junglekeepers

02:59:05.679 --> 02:59:09.669
stuff, and someone was like, "Yo, their
boat broke down." So we show up and I

02:59:09.720 --> 02:59:13.679
haul their boat and he comes up and says, "I'm
such a big fan. I just wanted to say hi."

02:59:13.740 --> 02:59:16.750
I said, "Well, great. Hello." I said,
"Well, let's get you back on the

02:59:16.800 --> 02:59:20.759
river." And then, you know,
someone came up to me and

02:59:20.800 --> 02:59:24.650
said, "He's a really good photographer." I
said, "Everybody's a good photographer today."

02:59:24.679 --> 02:59:28.369
I said, "That's great. Amazing. We have
Stefan and Mohsin. What else do we need?"

02:59:29.720 --> 02:59:33.539
And then someone I trust was like,
"Hey, listen, look at his stuff.

02:59:33.619 --> 02:59:37.140
It's not normal." And then I watched
a few of his videos and I went,

02:59:37.160 --> 02:59:40.729
"Holy shit." And I went,
"Would you ever think

02:59:40.820 --> 02:59:44.699
of coming down for a few weeks to film?"
And at the time, he was like, "No

02:59:45.039 --> 02:59:48.929
way." He was so amazed. And now we're

02:59:48.939 --> 02:59:52.820
bros. And we film together all
the time. But he put himself

02:59:52.859 --> 02:59:56.599
in the position where he has
the skill, the insane skill.

02:59:56.720 --> 03:00:00.460
I mean, some of his things—
he's doing tracking shots of a

03:00:00.539 --> 03:00:04.339
white-winged sparrow over the water
where he's in the boat with an

03:00:04.539 --> 03:00:09.839
800 millimeter lens, getting
these insane shots. I've

03:00:09.880 --> 03:00:12.449
never seen a talent like him with video.

03:00:12.460 --> 03:00:16.449
- But wildlife photography and documentary
filmmaking in general, it's not just

03:00:16.519 --> 03:00:20.000
about the competence of being able
to pull off a difficult shot.

03:00:20.480 --> 03:00:22.919
It's like the patience required

03:00:23.919 --> 03:00:27.699
and the discipline to just sit
there and wait. I mean, when we

03:00:28.000 --> 03:00:32.320
went out into the jungle, he waited.

03:00:32.380 --> 03:00:35.650
- Yeah. I mean, even looking on
this page, that shot of the-

03:00:35.650 --> 03:00:39.539
of the emerald tree boa there; he
got up before dawn to wait for the

03:00:39.619 --> 03:00:43.199
sideways light. He had a vision
of lighting the snake from the

03:00:43.339 --> 03:00:47.069
side. And then the macaws coming
off the clay lick. How many

03:00:47.179 --> 03:00:50.699
days at the clay lick till he
got the explosion of macaws?

03:00:50.720 --> 03:00:54.589
And I'm up in the tree and he's on
the walkie-talkie. And then also

03:00:54.640 --> 03:00:58.560
your lenses are going to fog. You have
to be able to hike and do everything

03:00:58.619 --> 03:01:04.080
everybody else is doing, and
your job. I mean, the dude is...

03:01:04.160 --> 03:01:07.900
- You attract a lot of incredible
people because the mission is

03:01:07.960 --> 03:01:09.519
clear and there's just like...

03:01:10.419 --> 03:01:14.300
There's a vibrancy and energy to
the whole thing. It's exciting.

03:01:14.339 --> 03:01:17.480
That's why the best people come to work
with you, come to hang out with you.

03:01:17.539 --> 03:01:20.259
- It's become an amazing team.
I look around at the people

03:01:21.080 --> 03:01:24.189
and I go, "How did this happen?"

03:01:24.220 --> 03:01:28.099
- But it is getting more intense
and dangerous. I have to ask

03:01:28.140 --> 03:01:32.039
you the thing we've talked about. What
do you think you'll do when you're

03:01:32.320 --> 03:01:39.539
getting older? This is pretty intense.
Where do you see yourself years from now?

03:01:39.580 --> 03:01:43.519
- I want to protect this river. We have to
protect this river in the next year and

03:01:43.580 --> 03:01:45.400
a half or else we'll lose the chance.

03:01:46.300 --> 03:01:50.259
Either I'm going to have... First book, I
got to the Amazon and it was wild. Second

03:01:50.320 --> 03:01:53.080
book, we went, we built this amazing
organization and we got so close.

03:01:53.199 --> 03:01:56.810
It'll be like those movies, like
Blow, where it's like, "For a

03:01:56.919 --> 03:02:00.589
time it was amazing," and then
at the end... it's not so great.

03:02:00.619 --> 03:02:01.619
- By the way, great movie.

03:02:01.640 --> 03:02:05.599
- Great movie. But, you know, I'm writing

03:02:05.660 --> 03:02:08.919
this story as it happens and,
you know, the endgame might be

03:02:10.060 --> 03:02:13.900
written by somebody else. Or we
just got really close and then it

03:02:13.960 --> 03:02:19.960
all fell apart. But we're 130,000
acres of the way. If we make it to

03:02:20.000 --> 03:02:23.919
300,000, I'm calling it now,

03:02:23.939 --> 03:02:27.560
I think enough people are going to learn
about this. It's going to tidal wave.

03:02:27.619 --> 03:02:31.500
We're going to make an amazing documentary
about how we protected the wildest place

03:02:31.560 --> 03:02:38.869
on Earth. And then I would love to
have a few kids, get a PhD, and teach

03:02:38.900 --> 03:02:42.500
conservationists around the world
how to do this to save really wild

03:02:42.519 --> 03:02:46.449
places, keep inspiring people,
keep writing books, keep going on

03:02:46.500 --> 03:02:50.092
expeditions. I don't have any
problems with that. I can tell you, I

03:02:50.212 --> 03:02:54.452
can't do this much longer
because the pressure of

03:02:55.972 --> 03:02:59.872
wondering if it's going to be okay,
I've used all of it that I can.

03:02:59.912 --> 03:03:03.212
My Lord of the Rings analogy of carrying
the ring; you can only do that for so

03:03:03.252 --> 03:03:07.052
long. And so I'm actually
very excited to... I need to

03:03:07.072 --> 03:03:11.052
know that it's safe. I
mean, that monkey that

03:03:11.112 --> 03:03:15.012
I rescued out of the river,
or the toucan, Lucas, who

03:03:15.172 --> 03:03:19.152
comes back to visit us. We
just saw a giant anteater not

03:03:19.172 --> 03:03:22.992
that long ago with Dax
in the jungle. I know

03:03:23.032 --> 03:03:26.912
these animals and I'm responsible for
protecting their home. It would be so

03:03:26.952 --> 03:03:30.712
amazing to bring people to the treehouse
and show them this amazing place

03:03:30.752 --> 03:03:32.812
and put out documentaries.
I have no problem

03:03:34.032 --> 03:03:37.992
imagining a transition period.
I'd like to transition out

03:03:38.032 --> 03:03:45.762
of Blood Diamond and go to more the
sort of professor role after this.

03:03:45.792 --> 03:03:48.682
- You mean like an Indiana
Jones type of professor?

03:03:48.682 --> 03:03:52.852
- Yeah. Running from the tribes.

03:03:52.912 --> 03:03:56.552
...as long as it doesn't go supernatural at
the end, I'll be very happy. That always

03:03:57.072 --> 03:03:58.512
kind of let me down.

03:03:58.552 --> 03:04:01.282
- Well, thank you for giving

03:04:02.212 --> 03:04:08.872
basically everything you got towards
this mission that you're doing. And

03:04:08.932 --> 03:04:12.852
thank you for being who you are. It's been
an honor of a lifetime to be able to call

03:04:12.892 --> 03:04:16.852
you a friend and to have
this conversation, brother.

03:04:17.052 --> 03:04:20.882
This is the third time we've spoken. I
think we'll talk at least 10 more times,

03:04:21.552 --> 03:04:25.412
and I think I speak for everybody
in saying thank you and please

03:04:25.452 --> 03:04:29.572
don't die in trying to
save the rainforest.

03:04:30.392 --> 03:04:35.412
- I have to say thank you to you
because our first conversation

03:04:37.392 --> 03:04:41.232
changed everything. It really
did. In this story, it

03:04:41.312 --> 03:04:45.292
brought so many more people
onto the mission. And

03:04:45.392 --> 03:04:49.292
I think also lifted me up because, as we

03:04:49.372 --> 03:04:53.252
often acknowledge, this can weigh
you down. And I often do get

03:04:53.292 --> 03:04:56.172
weighed down and I lose hope
myself. And then I get lifted up by

03:04:57.032 --> 03:05:00.972
moments like that where someone
I'm a huge fan of and who I

03:05:00.992 --> 03:05:04.692
respect so much reaches out and goes, "Do you
wanna come to Austin and do this podcast?"

03:05:04.732 --> 03:05:11.572
And I respond, "The Lex fucking Fridman
podcast?" But, you know, you've

03:05:12.012 --> 03:05:18.612
really changed the narrative and
allowed this to be a reality, so.

03:05:18.672 --> 03:05:21.192
- And everybody, go pre-order

03:05:22.012 --> 03:05:27.562
The Jungle Keeper, the book, available
everywhere. And if you can, donate on

03:05:27.592 --> 03:05:31.572
junglekeepers.org. This
is an important mission,

03:05:31.612 --> 03:05:35.502
an ultra-competent team, and this
is such a beautiful part of the

03:05:35.572 --> 03:05:39.502
world that I really,
really, really hope we

03:05:39.592 --> 03:05:45.392
protect. So thank you for talking
today, and now let's go eat.

03:05:45.412 --> 03:05:47.452
- Thank you, brother.

03:05:47.512 --> 03:05:51.312
- Thanks for listening to this conversation with Paul
Rosolie. To support this podcast, please check out our

03:05:51.372 --> 03:05:54.952
sponsors in the description, or
you can also find links to contact

03:05:54.992 --> 03:06:01.892
me, ask questions, give feedback, and so
on. And once more, let me say thank you for

03:06:01.932 --> 03:06:05.672
everything. Thank you for your support.
Thank you for the love. And thank you for

03:06:05.732 --> 03:06:13.332
listening. And I hope
to see you next time.

